rstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://portal.www.gov.qa/wps/wcm/connect/8abaea8046be1deaae97ef70b3652ad8/Penal+Code.pdf?MOD=AJPERES&useDefaultText=0&useDefaultDesc=0 |publisher=Government of Qatar |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 305</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Singapore}}\n| {{Yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 305. Abetment of suicide of child or insane person\n|If any person under 18 years of age, any insane person, any delirious person, any idiot, or any person in a state of intoxication, commits suicide, whoever abets the commission of such suicide shall be punished with death or imprisonment for life, or with imprisonment for a term not exceeding 10 years, and shall also be liable to fine.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|Article 306. Abetment of suicide\n|If any person commits suicide, whoever abets the commission of such suicide shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 10 years, and shall also be liable to fine.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|Suicide discriminalised\n|On 11 February 2019, the Singapore government announced the decriminalisation of suicide.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-attempted-suicide-to-no-longer-be-crime-11229108|publisher=Channel News Asia |title= Criminal Law reform Bill |accessdate=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|South Korea}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 252 (Murder upon Request or with Consent)\n|CRIMINAL ACT 53\n(1) A person who kills another upon ones request or with ones consent shall be punished by imprisonment for not less than one year nor more than ten years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oecd.org/site/adboecdanti-corruptioninitiative/46816472.pdf |publisher=Government of South Korea |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 252</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|299. Abetment of suicide\n|If any person commits suicide, whoever abets the commission of such suicide shall be punished with death.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://hrlibrary.umn.edu/research/srilanka/statutes/Penal_Code.pdf |publisher=Government of Sri Lanka |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 299</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Syria}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Taiwan}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.moj.gov.tw/Eng/LawClass/LawAll.aspx?PCode=C0010001 |publisher=Government of Taiwan |title=Criminal Code |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Tajikistan}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 109. Driving to Suicide\n|(1) Driving an individual to suicide or attempt upon suicide by threat, cruel treatment, or systematic degrading the dignity of a victim is punishable by imprisonment for a period of 3 to 5 years.\n(2) The same actions committed in regard to a person, who was in financial or other dependence of the guilty person, or committed in regard to a minor is punishable by imprisonment for a period of 5 to 8 years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislationline.org/download/action/download/id/1707/file/207b8150765af2c85ad6f5bb8a44.htm/preview |publisher=Government of Tajikistan |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 109</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Thailand}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Section 292 \n|Whoever, practicing the cruelty or employing the similar factor on the person to have depended on him for subsistence or any other activities so as to that person shall commit the suicide, if suicide to have occurred or to have been attempted, shall be imprisoned not out seven years and fined not out of fourteen thousand Baht.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|Section 293 \n|Whoever aids or instigates a child not over sixteen years of age, or a person who is unable to understand the nature and importance of his act or who is unable to control his act, to commit suicide, shall, if suicide has occurred or has been attempted, be punished with imprisonment not exceeding five years or fined not exceeding ten thousand Baht, or both.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.samuiforsale.com/law-texts/thailand-penal-code.html |publisher=Government of Thailand |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 292 and 293</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Turkmenistan}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/crime/suicide-punishable-under-uae-law-1.808785 |publisher=Gulf News |title=Suicide punishable under UAE law |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Uzbekistan}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 103. Bringing to Suicide\n|Bringing to suicide or attempt thereat by cruel treatment or persistent degrading of honor and dignity of a person, who was not in financial or other dependence on a guilty person shall be punished with correctional labor up to three years or imprisonment up to five years.\n\nThe same acts committed in respect of a person, who was in financial or other dependence on a guilty person shall be punished with correctional labor up to three years or imprisonment up to five years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislationline.org/download/action/download/id/1712/file/a45cbf3cc66c17f04420786aa164.htm/preview |publisher=Government of Uzbekistan |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 103</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 100. Forced suicide\n|1. Any person who cruelly treats, constantly intimidates, illtreats or humiliates a person dependent on him/her, inducing the latter to commit suicide, shall be sentenced to between two and seven years of imprisonment.\n2. Any person who commits the crime of compelling more than one person to commit suicide shall be sentenced to between five and twelve years of imprisonment.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|Article 101. Inciting or assisting other persons to commit suicide\n|1. Any person who incites another person to commit suicide or assists another person to commit suicide shall be sentenced to imprisonment for between six months and three years.\n2. Any person who commits the crime of assisting or inciting more than one person to commit suicide shall be sentenced to between two and seven years of imprisonment.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://un-act.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Vietnam-Penal-Code.1999.en_.pdf |publisher=Government of Vietnam |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 100 and 101</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Yemen}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|}\n\n===Europe===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:20%;\"|Country/region\n! colspan=3 style=\"width:25%;\"|[[De jure]]\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:25%;\"|Penalty\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:30%;\"|Notes\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Suicide\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Physician-assisted suicide\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Voluntary euthanasia\n|-\n| {{flag|Albania}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 99 Causing suicide\n|Causing suicide or a suicide attempt by a person because of the systematic maltreatment or other systematic misbehaviors which seriously affect the dignity [of the person], committed by another person under whose material dependence or any other dependence the former person is subject, is punishable by a fine or up to five years of imprisonment.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/al/al037en.pdf |publisher=Government of Albania |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 99</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Armenia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 110. Causing somebody to commit suicide.\n|1. Causing somebody to commit suicide or make an attempt at a suicide by indirect willfulness or by negligence, by means of threat, cruel treatment or regular humiliation of one\u2019s dignity, is punished with imprisonment for the term of up to 3 years. \n2. The same act committed in relation to a person in financial or other dependence of the perpetrator, is punished with imprisonment for the term of up to 5 years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|Article 111. Abetment of suicide.\n|Abetment of suicide, creation of determination in the person to commit suicide by means of instructions, deception, etc., if the person committed suicide or made a suicide attempt, is punished with imprisonment for the term of up to 3 years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unodc.org/res/cld/document/armenia_criminal_code_html/Armenia_Criminal_Code_of_the_Republic_of_Armenia_2009.pdf |publisher=Government of Armenia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 110 and 111</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Austria}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n|Killing a person on request by such person, or aiding or helping another person to commit suicide is punished with imprisonment of 6 months up to 5 years. \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/GeltendeFassung.wxe?Abfrage=Bundesnormen&Gesetzesnummer=10002296 |publisher=Government of Austria |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 77 and 78</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 125. Bringing to suicide\n|Bringing a person, who is taking place in material, service or other dependence from guilty, to suicide or to attempt at suicide by threats, cruel treatment or regular humiliation of his dignity \u2013 shall be punished by restriction of freedom for the term up to three years or imprisonment for the term from three up to seven years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.am/library/Qreakan/Azerbadjan.pdf |publisher=Government of Azerbaijan |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 125</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Belarus}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 105. Bringing to Suicide\n|Bringing to suicide or to an attempted suicide through brutal treatment of the sufferer or systematic humiliation of his personal dignity - shall be punishable with the deprivation of freedom for a term of up to three years. The same action committed in relation to a person who has been materially or otherwise dependent on the culprit - shall be punishable with the deprivation of freedom for a term of up to five years. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/pdf/Belarus/BYE_Crim_Law_EN.pdf |publisher=Government of Belarus |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 105</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Belgium}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n|Legal since 2002\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Bulgaria}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Art. 127. \n|(1) Who, in any way whatsoever, helps or prevails upon a suicide and suicide or attempted suicide takes place, shall be punished by imprisonment of up to three years. \n(2) For the same crime regarding a minor person or a person of whom the culprit is aware that he is in no position to guide his ac\nts or he does not understand the quality or the importance of the act the punishment shall be imprisonment of three to ten years. \n(3) Who, by a cruel treatment or systematic humiliation of the dignity of a person in material or other dependence on him leads him to a suicide or suicide attempt, having expected it, shall be punished by imprisonment of two to eight years. \n(4) If the act under the preceding para is committed by negligence the punishment shall be imprisonment of up to three years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://prostitution.procon.org/sourcefiles/BulgariaCriminalCode.pdf |publisher=Government of Bulgaria |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 127</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Croatia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 96 Participating in Suicide \n|(1) Whoever induces or assists another in committing suicide which is accomplished or attempted shall be punished by imprisonment for six months to five years.\n(2) Whoever induces or assists a juvenile person in committing suicide, or induces or assists in committing suicide a person whose capability of understanding his own acts and of controlling his own will is significantly diminished, and the suicide is accomplished or attempted shall be punished \nby imprisonment for one to eight years.\n(3) Whoever induces or assists a child in committing suicide or whoever induces or assists a person who is not capable of understanding the significance of his act, or could not control his own will so that the suicide is attempted or accomplished, shall be punished pursuant to Article 90 of this Code. \n(4) Whoever treats a person who is in a state of subordination or dependence in a cruel or inhuman way and thereby negligently causes the suicide of that person shall be punished by imprisonment for three months to three years. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iracm.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/code-criminel-anglais-24081.pdf |publisher=Government of Croatia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 96</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Cyprus}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|214. Attempt to murder.\n|Any person who - \n(a) attempts unlawfully to cause the death of another; or \n(b) with intent unlawfully to cause the death of another does any act, or omits to do any act which it is his duty to do, such act or omission being of such a \nnature as to be likely to endanger human life, is guilty of a felony, and is liable to imprisonment for life.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|288. Abetting suicide. \n|Any person who-- \n(a) procures another to kill himself; or \n(b) counsels another to kill himself and thereby induces him to do so; or\n(c) aids another in killing himself,\nis guilty of a felony, and is liable to imprisonment for life.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|219. Attempting suicide. \n|Any person who attempts to kill himself is guilty of a misdemeanour.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/pdf/Cyprus/CYP_Penal_Code_1959_CAP_154_EN.pdf |publisher=Government of Cyprus |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 214, 288 and 219</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Section 144 Accessory to Suicide\n|(1) Whoever encourages another person to commit suicide or assists another person in committing suicide, shall be sentenced, if at least an attempted suicide occurred, to imprisonment for up to three years.\n(2) An offender shall be sentenced of imprisonment for two to eight years, if he/she commits the act referred to in Subsection (1) on a child or a pregnant woman.\n(3) An offender shall be sentenced of imprisonment for five to twelve years, if he/she commits the act referred to in Subsection (1) on a child under fifteen years of age or on a person suffering from a mental disorder.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ejtn.eu/PageFiles/6533/Criminal%20Code%20of%20the%20Czech%20Republic.pdf |publisher=Government of the Czech Republic |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 244</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|\u00a7 240\n|Any person who assists another person in committing suicide shall be liable to a fine or to imprisonment for any term not exceeding three years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}} \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/pdf/Denmark_Criminal_Code_2005.pdf |publisher=Government of Denmark |title=Criminal Code <sup>\u00a7 240</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Estonia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riigiteataja.ee/en/eli/522012015002/consolide |publisher=Government of Estonia |title=Criminal Code |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Finland}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|France}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Georgia|Georgia (country)}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n|A suicide attempt is punished by a fine of 500 [[Georgian lari|Lari]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matsne.gov.ge/ka/document/view/952?publication=0 |publisher=Legislative Herald of Georgia |title=Law of Georgia <sup>Article 2937</sup> |accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ambebi.ge/article/84689-carumatebeli-tvitmkvleloba-500-lariani-jarimit-isjeba/ |publisher=Ambebi.ge |title=Unsuccessful suicide is punishable by a fine of 500 Lari |accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kvira.ge/121701 |publisher=Kvira.ge |title=Suicidal citizen who tried to drown himself into the Kura river was fined 500 GEL. |accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n{{hidden\n|Article 115 - Incitement to suicide\n|Incitement to suicide or attempted suicide accompanied with intimidation or cruel treatment of the victim or by degrading of the victim's honour or dignity, \u2013\nshall be punished by restriction of liberty for up to three years or by imprisonment for a term of two to four years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}} \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://matsne.gov.ge/en/document/download/16426/156/en/pdf |publisher=Government of Georgia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 115</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Germany}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw.com/en/german-federal-court-rules-patients-should-have-access-to-life-ending-drugs/a-37790952 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |title=German Federal Court rules patients should have access to life-ending drugs |accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |title=Germany overturns ban on professionally assisted suicide |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-51643306 |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Gibraltar}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|158. Suicide pacts. \n|(1) A person who, in pursuance of a suicide pact between him and another person\u2013 \n(a) kills that person; or \n(b) is party to the killing of that person by a third person, \ncommits the offence of manslaughter and not murder.\n\n(2) If it is shown that a person charged with the murder of another killed the other or was a party to his being killed, it is for the defence to prove that \nthe person charged was acting in pursuance of a suicide pact between him and the other.\n\n(3) For the purposes of this section, \u201csuicide pact\u201d means a common agreement between two or more persons having for its object the death of all of them, whether or not each is to take his own life, but nothing done by a person who enters into a suicide pact is to be treated as done by him in pursuance of the pact unless it is done while he has the settled intention of dying in pursuance of the pact.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|159. Complicity in suicide. \n|(1) A person (\u2018D\u2019) commits an offence if\u2013 \n(a) D does an act capable of encouraging or assisting the suicide or attempted suicide of another person; and \n(b) D\u2019s act was intended to encourage or assist suicide or an attempt at suicide.\n\n(2) The person referred to in subsection (1)(a) need not be a specific person (or class of persons) known to, or identified by, D.\n\n(3) D may commit an offence under this section whether or not a suicide, or an attempt at suicide, occurs.\n\n(4) A person who commits an offence under this section is liable on conviction on indictment to imprisonment for 14 years.\n\n(5) If on the trial of an indictment for murder or manslaughter of a person it is proved that the deceased person committed suicide, and the defendant committed an offence under subsection (1) in relation to that suicide, the jury may find the defendant guilty of the offence under subsection (1).\n\n(6) If D arranges for a person (\u2018D2\u2019) to do an act that is capable of encouraging or assisting the suicide or attempted suicide of another person and D2 does that act, D is to be treated for the purposes of this Part as having done it.\n\n(7) If the facts are such that an act is not capable of encouraging or assisting suicide or attempted suicide, for the purposes of this section it is to be treated as so capable if the act would have been so capable had the facts been as D believed them to be at the time of the act; or had subsequent events happened in the manner D believed they would happen, or both.\n\n(8) A reference in this section to a person doing an act that is capable of encouraging the suicide or attempted suicide of another person includes a reference to his doing so by threatening another person or otherwise putting pressure on another person to commit or attempt suicide.\n\n(9) A reference in this section to an act includes a reference to a course of conduct, and a reference to doing an act is to be read accordingly.\n\n(10) No prosecution for an offence against this section may be commenced except by, or with the consent of, the Attorney General.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gibraltarlaws.gov.gi/bills/bills2011/2011B07.pdf |publisher=Government of Gibraltar |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 158, 159</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Greece}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Hungary}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Section 162\n|(1) Any person who persuades another to commit suicide, or provides aid for suicide is guilty of a felony punishable by imprisonment between one to five years, if the suicide is attempted or committed.\n(2) Any person over the age of eighteen years who persuades another person under the age of eighteen years to commit suicide, or provides aid for committing suicide is punishable by imprisonment between two to eight years, if the suicide is attempted orcommitted.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.am/library/Qreakan/Hungary.pdf |publisher=Government of Hungary |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 162</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Art. 214 \n|In case a person be conducive to another person\u2019;;s committing suicide he/she shall be subject to [imprisonment for up to 1 year] 1) or fines. In case this be done for a selfish purpose the penalty shall be imprisonment for up to 3 years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/en/text.jsp?file_id=190914 |publisher=Government of Iceland |title=Criminal Code <sup>Art. 214</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Ireland}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Italy}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Kosovo}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 183 Inciting suicide and assisting in suicide \n|1.Whoever incites or assists another person to commit suicide, and the suicide is committed, shall be punished by imprisonment of one (1) to five (5) years. \n2. Whoever commits the offense provided for in paragraph 1 of this Article against a minor or a person whose capability to understand the gravity of his or her act or whose ability to control his or her behavior was substantially diminished, shall be punished by imprisonment of one (1) to ten (10) years. \n3. Whoever commits the offense provided for in paragraph 1 of this Article against a person under the age of fourteen (14) years \nor against a person who was incapable of understanding the gravity of his or her act or controlling his or her behavior shall be punished in accordance with Article 178 of this Code. \n4. Whoever treats another person in a subordinate position in a cruel or inhumane way and thereby causes such person to commit suicide shall be \npunished by imprisonment of six (6) months to five (5) years. For the purpose of this paragraph \u201cperson in a subordinate position\u201d means a person who is under the supervision, rank, control or custody of the person who acted in a cruel or inhumane way. \n5. If, as a result of an offense provided for in paragraphs 1 to 4 of this Article, suicide has only been attempted, the punishment may be reduced. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly-kosova.org/common/docs/ligjet/Criminal%20Code.pdf |publisher=Government of Kosovo |title=Criminal Code <sup>Art. 183</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Latvia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Section 124. Causing a Suicide to be Committed \n|(1) For a person who commits causing a person to commit suicide or attempt suicide by cruel treatment of the victim or systematic demeaning of his or her personal dignity, if such person has not been in financial or other dependence upon the offender, the applicable sentence is deprivation of liberty for a term not exceeding three years. \n(2) For a person who commits the same acts with regard to a person who has been in financial or other dependence upon the offender, the applicable sentence is deprivation of liberty for a term not exceeding five years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/untc/unpan018405.pdf |publisher=Government of Latvia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 124</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Liechtenstein}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n|Killing somebody on request, or aiding somebody to commit suicide is punished with imprisonment from six months up to five years.\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Lithuania}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Luxembourg}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Malta}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|213.\n|Whosoever shall prevail on any person to commit suicide or shall give him any assistance, shall, if the suicide takes place, be liable, on conviction, to imprisonment for a term not exceeding twelve years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.justiceservices.gov.mt/DownloadDocument.aspx?app=lom&itemid=8574 |publisher=Government of Malta |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 213</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Moldova}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Montenegro}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 149 Incitement to suicide and aid in the commission of suicide\n|(1) Anyone who incites other person to suicide or aid him in committing suicide, and should suicide be committed or attempted, shall be \nsentenced to one to eight years of imprisonment.\n(2) Anyone who aids other person in committing suicide subject to conditions referred to in Article 147 of the present Code, and should suicide be committed or attempted, shall be sentenced to three months to five years of imprisonment.\n(3) Anyone who commits the act referred to in Paragraph 1 of this Article against a juvenile or a person in the state of substantialy diminished mental capacity, shall be sentenced to two to ten years of imprisonment.\n(4) Should the act referred to in Paragraph 1 of this Article be committed against a child or a mentally incapable person, the perpetrator shall be sentenced in line with provisions of Article 144 of the present Code.\n(5) Anyone who treats with cruelty or brutality other person subordinate or dependant on him, and should the person in question due to such treatment, commit or attempt suicide that can be attributed to the offender\u2019s negligence, shall be sentenced to six months to five years of impris\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/res/cld/document/mne/2003/criminal_code_html/Montenegro_Criminal_Code.pdf |publisher=Government of Montenegro|title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 149</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal medical assisted suicide}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n|\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/jci1.3:c:BWBR0001854&boek=Tweede&titeldeel=XIX&artikel=293&z=2017-03-01&g=2017-03-01|title=wetten.nl - Regeling - Wetboek van Strafrecht - BWBR0001854|website=wetten.overheid.nl|language=nl|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|North Macedonia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 128 Instigation to suicide and helping in suicide\n|(1) A person who instigates another to suicide or helps him in committing suicide, and this was committed, shall be punished with imprisonment of three months to three years.\n\n(2) If the crime from item 1 is committed against a juvenile who reached the age of fourteen or against a person who is in a state of decreased mental competence, the offender shall be punished with imprisonment of one to ten years.\n\n(3) If the crime from item 1 is committed against a juvenile who has not reached the age of fourteen years yet, or against a mentally incompetent person, the offender shall be punished according to article 123.\n\n(4) A person behaving cruelly or inhumanely towards another who has a subordinate or dependent relationship to him, and if this person commits suicide because of this relationship, which could be attributed to negligence by the offender, shall be punished with imprisonment of six months to five years.\n\n(5) If because of the crimes from items 1 to 4 the suicide was only attempted, the court may punish the offender more leniently.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislationline.org/documents/action/popup/id/16066/preview |publisher=Government of Macedonia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 128</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Norway}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Poland}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Articles 150. and 151.\n|Art. 150. \u00a7 1. Whoever kills a human on his own request and driven by compassion towards him, shall be subject to the penalty of imprisonment for a term of between 3 months and 5 years. \n\u00a7 2. In special cases the court may imopse an extraordinary mitigation of punishment or even forego the punishment.\n\nArt. 151. Whoever by encouraging or help drives a human to a suicide, shall be subject to the penalty of imprisonment for a term of between 3 months and 5 years. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imolin.org/doc/amlid/Poland_Penal_Code1.pdf |publisher=Government of Poland |title=Criminal Code |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Portugal}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Romania}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 191. Determining or facilitating suicide\n|(1). An act of determining or facilitating the suicide of an individual, if the suicide has taken place, shall be punishable by no less than 3 and no more than 7 years of imprisonment. \n(2).When the act specified by par. (1) was committed against a juvenile between 13 and 18 years of age or against a person having a reduced competence, the penalty shall be no less than 5 and no more than 10 years of imprisonment. \n(3). Determining or facilitating the suicide of an underage person who did not reach the age of 13 or of a person who was unable to realize the consequences of their actions or inactions or to control them, if suicide has taken place, shall be punishable by no less than 10 and no more than 20 years of imprisonment and a ban on the exercise of certain rights.\n(4). If actions of determining or facilitating suicide set under par. (1) - (3) were followed by a suicide attempt, the special limits of the penalty shall be reduced down to half.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.juridice.ro/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Noul-cod-penal-EN.doc |publisher=Government of Romania |title=Penal Code <sup>Article 191</sup> |accessdate=2017-02-27}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Russia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 110. Incitement to Suicide \n|Incitement of a person to commit or attempt to commit suicide by means of threats, cruel treatment of a person, or systematic denigration of the human dignity of the victim - Shall be punishable by restraint of liberty for a term of up to three years or by deprivation of liberty for a term of up to five years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/ru/ru006en.pdf |publisher=Government of Russia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 110</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Serbia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 119 Incitement to Suicide and Aiding in Suicide \n|(1) Whoever incites another to suicide or aids in committing suicide and this is committed or attempted, shall be punished with imprisonment of from six months to five years. \n(2) Whoever assists another in committing suicide under provisions of Article 117 hereof, and this is committed or attempted, shall be punished with imprisonment from three months to three years. \n(3) Whoever commits the act specified in paragraph 1 of this Article against a juvenile or person in a state of substantially diminished mental capacity, shall be punished with imprisonment from two to ten years. \n(4) If the act specified in paragraph 1 of this Article is committed against a child or mentally incompetent person, the offender shall be punished in accordance with Article 114 hereof. \n(5) Whoever cruelly or inhumanely treats another who is in a position of subordination or dependency and due to such treatment the person commits or attempts suicide that may be attributed to negligence of the perpetrator, shall be punished with imprisonment from six months to five years.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.osce.org/serbia/18244?download=true |publisher=Government of Serbia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 119</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Slovakia}} \n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Section 154 Participating in a Suicide\n|(1) Any person who incites another person to committing suicide, or helps him to commit suicide, shall, if at least a suicide attempt takes place, be liable to a term of imprisonment of between six months and three years.\n(2) The offender shall be liable to a term of imprisonment of three to eightyears if he commits the offence referred to in paragpraph 1\na) acting in a more serious manner, \nb) against a protected person, or\nc) by reason of specific motivation.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.am/library/Qreakan/slovakia.pdf |publisher=Government of Slovakia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Section 154</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Slovenia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 120 Solicitation to and Assistance in Suicide \n|(1) Whoever intentionally solicits another person to kill himself or assists him in doing so, resulting in that person indeed committing suicide, shall be sentenced to imprisonment for not less than six months and not more than five years. \n (2) Whoever commits the offence under the preceding paragraph against a minor above fourteen years of age or against a person whose ability to understand the meaning of his act or to control his conduct was substantially diminished shall be sentenced to imprisonment for not less than one and not more than ten years. \n (3) In the event of the offence under paragraph 1 of this Article being committed against a minor under fourteen years of age or against a person who was not capable of understanding the meaning of his act or of controlling his conduct shall be punished according to the prescription for murder. \n(4) Whoever treats his subordinate or a person depending on him in a cruel or inhumane manner, resulting in this person's suicide, shall be sent\nenced to imprisonment for not less than six months and not more than five years. \n(5) Whoever, under particularly mitigating circumstances, assists another person to commit suicide, and if that person indeed commits suicide, shall be sentenced to imprisonment for not more than three years. \n(6) If, relating to a criminal offence under the above paragraphs, the suicide has only been attempted, the Court may reduce the punishment of the perpetrator. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.policija.si/eng/images/stories/Legislation/pdf/CriminalCode2009.pdf |publisher=Government of Slovenia |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 120</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Spain}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Article 143\n|1. Whoever induces another to suicide shall be punished with a sentence of imprisonment from four to eight years.\n2. A sentence of imprisonment of two to five years shall be imposed on whoever co-operates in the necessary acts for a person to commit suicide. \n3. Punishment shall involve a sentence of imprisonment from six to ten years if such co-operation were to reach the point of death ensuing. \n4. Whoever causes or actively co-operates in the necessary, direct acts causing the death of another, at the specific, serious, unequivocal request of that person, in the event of the victim suffering a serious disease that would unavoidably lead to death, or that causes permanent suffering that is hard to bear, shall be punished with a punishment lower by one or two degrees to those described in Sections 2 and 3 of this \nArticle.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.am/library/Qreakan/ispania.pdf |publisher=Government of Spain |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 143</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{partial|Legal, with some exemptions}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Penal Code, Chapter 3 \u00a7 1 Murder\n|A person who takes the life of another shall be sentenced for murder to imprisonment for a fixed period of at least ten and at most eighteen years, or, if there are aggravating circumstances, for life.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| {{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Switzerland}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{yes|Legal medical assisted suicide}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.admin.ch/opc/en/classified-compilation/19370083/201501010000/311.0.pdf |publisher=Government of Switzerland |title=Criminal Code |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Turkey}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|ARTICLE 84 Suicide\n|(1) Any person who solicits, encourages a person to commit suicide, or supports the decision of a person for suicide or helps the suicide action in any manner whatsoever, is punished with imprisonment from two years to five years.\n\n(2) In case of commission of suicide, the person who is involved in such act is sentenced to imprisonment from four years to ten years.\n\n(3) Any person who openly encourages others to commit suicide is punished with imprisonment from three years to eight years.\n\n(5) Persons who encourage others, lack of ability to understand the meaning and consequences of the executed act, to commit suicide, or force a person to commit suicide under threat, are convicted of felonious homicide.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislationline.org/documents/action/popup/id/6872/preview |publisher=Government of Turkey |title=Criminal Code <sup>Article 84</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Ukraine}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|Criminal liability for complicity in another\u2019s suicide.\n|'''[<sup>F1</sup>'''(1) A person (\u201cD\u201d) commits an offence if\u2014\n\n::(a) D does an act capable of encouraging or assisting the suicide or attempted suicide of another person, and\n\n::(b) D's act was intended to encourage or assist suicide or an attempt at suicide.\n\n(1A) The person referred to in subsection (1)(a) need not be a specific person (or class of persons) known to, or identified by, D.\n\n(1B) D may commit an offence under this section whether or not a suicide, or an attempt at suicide, occurs.\n\n(1C) An offence under this section is triable on indictment and a person convicted of such an offence is liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 14 years.''']'''\n\n(2) If on the trial of an indictment for murder or manslaughter '''[<sup>F2</sup>'''of a person it is proved that the deceased person committed suicide, and the accused committed an offence under subsection (1) in relation to that suicide, the jury may find the accused guilty of the offence under subsection (1). ''']'''\n\n(3) The enactments mentioned in the first column of the First Schedule to this Act shall have effect subject to the amendments provided for in the second column (which preserve in relation to offences under this section the previous operation of those enactments in relation to murder or manslaughter).\n\n(4). . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . '''<sup>F3</sup>'''no proceedings shall be instituted for an offence under this section except by or with the consent of the Director of Public Prosecutions.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Eliz2/9-10/60 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdomb|title=Suicide Act 1961 |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UK Supreme Court Backs Ruling Allowing Vegetative State Patients to Die |url=https://www.news18.com/news/world/uk-supreme-court-backs-ruling-allowing-vegetative-state-patients-to-die-1828417.html |accessdate=1 August 2018 |date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Oceania===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:20%;\"|Country/region\n! colspan=3 style=\"width:25%;\"|[[De jure]]\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:25%;\"|Penalty\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:30%;\"|Notes\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Suicide\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Physician-assisted suicide\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Voluntary euthanasia\n|-\n|''{{flag|American Samoa}}''\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|46.3506 Promoting suicide.\n|(a) A person is guilty of promoting suicide when he intentionally causes or aids another person to attempt suicide, or when he intentionally aids another person to commit suicide.\n(b) Promoting suicide is a class D felony. \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asbar.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=749&Itemid=172 |publisher=Government of American Samoa |title=Criminal Code <sup>46.3506</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Australia}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{partial|Legal in the states of Victoria and Western Australia}}\n| {{partial|Legal in the state of Western Australia}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Fiji}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|199.-\n|(1) Any person who of malice aforethought causes the death of another person by an unlawful act or omission is guilty of murder:\n Provided that it shall be manslaughter, and shall not be murder, for a person acting in pursuance of a suicide pact between him and another to kill the other.\n\n(2) Where it is shown that a person charged with the murder of another killed the other, it shall be for the defence to prove that the person charged was acting in pursuance of a suicide pact between him and the other.\n\n(3) For the purposes of this section \"suicide pact\" means a common agreement between two or more persons having for its object the death of all of them, whether or not each is to take his own life, but nothing done by a person who enters into a suicide pact shall be treated as done by him in pursuance of the pact unless it is done while he has the settled intention of dying in pursuance of the pact.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paclii.org/fj/legis/consol_act_OK/pc66/ |publisher=Government of Fiji |title=Criminal Code <sup>46.3506</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|''{{flag|Guam}}''\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n|''{{flag|Northern Mariana Islands}}''\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Palau}}\n| {{yes|Legal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Papua New Guinea}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{no|Illegal}}\n| {{hidden\n|310. AIDING SUICIDE. \n|A person who\u2013 \n(a) procures another to kill himself; or \n(b) counsels another to kill himself and so induces him to do so; or \n(c) aids another in killing himself, \nis guilty of a crime. \nPenalty: Subject to Section 19, imprisonment for life.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n{{hidden\n|311. ATTEMPTING TO COMMIT SUICIDE. \n|A person who attempts to kill himself is guilty of a misdemeanour. \nPenalty: Imprisonment for a term not exceeding one year.\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/pdf/Papua_New_Guinea_Criminal_Code_Act_1974.pdf |publisher=Government of Papua New Guinea |title=Criminal Code <sup>310, 311</sup> |accessdate=2016-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Samoa}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Solomon Islands}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n|''{{flag|Tokelau}}''\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{hidden\n|9. Counselling Suicide\n|Any person who counsels or procures a person to commit suicide, or aids or abets a person in the commission of suicide commits an offence.\n\n(Penalty \"not exceeding more than $150 fine or 3 months imprisonment\")\n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center;\n|}}\n| <ref>[http://www.paclii.org/cgi-bin/sinodisp/tk/legis/num_act/cpaer2003302/cpaer2003302.html \"Crimes, Procedure and Evidence Rules 2003\"]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Tonga}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Vanuatu}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n| {{unknown}}\n|\n|}\n\n==Laws in individual jurisdictions==\n\n===Australia===\nIn the [[Australia]]n state of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], while suicide itself is no longer a crime, a survivor of a [[suicide pact]] can be charged with [[manslaughter]]. Also, it is a crime to counsel, [[incitement|incite]], or aid and abet another in attempting to suicide, and the law explicitly allows any person to use \"such force as may reasonably be necessary\" to prevent another from dying by suicide.\n\nOn 29 November 2017 the state of Victoria passed the [[Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2017 (Victoria)|Voluntary Assisted Dying Act]], making it legal for a doctor to assist a terminally ill patient with less than six months to live to end their own life. The law came into effect on 19 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Victoria becomes first state to legalise assisted dying as parliament passes bill |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/nov/29/victoria-becomes-first-state-to-legalise-assisted-dying-as-parliament-passes-bill |accessdate=2 February 2019 |publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==== Legislation decriminalizing suicide in Australian States and Territories ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Jurisdiction\n!Legislation\n|-\n|Australian Capital Territory\n|''Crimes Act 1900'' (ACT) s 16\n|-\n|New South Wales\n|''Crimes Act 1900'' (NSW) s 31A\n|-\n|Northern Territory\n|''Criminal Code'' (NT) s 186 (repealed)\n|-\n|Queensland\n|''Criminal Code 1899'' (Qld) s 312 (repealed by ''Criminal Law Amendment Act'' (1979) s 4)\n|-\n|South Australia\n|''Criminal Law Consolidation Act 1932'' (SA) s 13A\n|-\n|Tasmania\n|''Criminal Code 1924'' (Tas) s 163\n|-\n|Victoria\n|''Crimes Act 1958'' (Vic) s 6A\n|-\n|Western Australia\n|''Criminal Code 1899'' (WA) s 289 (repealed by ''Criminal Code Amendment Act 1972'' s 10)\n|-\n|}\n\n===Canada===\n{{main|Euthanasia in Canada}}\nThe common law crimes of attempting suicide and of assisting suicide were codified in Canada when Parliament enacted the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]] in 1892. It carried a maximum penalty of 2 years' imprisonment.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/criminalcodevic00canagoog/criminalcodevic00canagoog_djvu.txt ''Criminal Code,1892'', SC 1892, c 29, ss 237, 238]</ref> Eighty years later, in 1972, Parliament repealed the offence of attempting suicide from the Criminal Code based on the argument that a legal deterrent was unnecessary.<ref name=Carter2012/> The prohibition on assisting suicide remained, as s 241 of the Criminal Code:\n\n:Counselling or aiding suicide\n:241. Every one who\n\n::(a) counsels a person to commit suicide, or\n\n::''(b) aids or abets a person to commit suicide'',\n\n:whether suicide ensues or not, is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding fourteen years.<ref>''Criminal Code'', RSC 1985, c C-46, s 241, as amended by RSC 1985, c 27 (1st Supp), s 7.</ref>\n\nHowever, the law against assisted suicide, including physician-assisted suicide, was the subject of much debate including two reports of the [[Law Commission of Canada|Law Reform Commission of Canada]] in 1982 and 1983, though these did not support changing the law.<ref>[http://www.lareau-law.ca/LRCReport20.pdf Euthanasia, Aiding Suicide and Cessation of Treatment, Report # 20, 1983. Law Reform Commission of Canada]</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the offence of assisted suicide survived a constitutional challenge in the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], in the case of ''[[Rodriguez v. British Columbia (Attorney General)]]''. The plaintiff, [[Sue Rodriguez]], had been diagnosed with [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (ALS) in early 1991. She wished to be able to commit suicide at a time of her own choosing, but would require assistance to do so, because her physical condition prevented her from doing so without assistance. By a 5-4 majority, the Court held that the prohibition on assisted suicide did not infringe [[Section 7 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|s 7 of the ''Canadian Charter of RIghts and Freedoms'']], which provides constitutional protection for liberty and security of the person. The majority held that while the law did affect those rights, it did so in a manner consistent with the principles of fundamental justice. The majority also held that the prohibition on assisted suicide did not infringe the Charter's prohibition against [[Section Twelve of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|cruel and unusual treatment or punishment]]. Assuming the prohibition did discriminate on basis of disability, the majority held that the infringement was a [[Section One of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|justifiable restriction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/suicide|title=Suicide|publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=OLAD/><ref>[http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/1054/index.do ''Rodriguez v. British Columbia (Attorney General)'', [1993<nowiki>]</nowiki> 3 SCR 519.]</ref>\n\nIn 1995 the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] issued a report on assisted suicide entitled ''Of Life and Death''.<ref name=OLAD>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/content/sen/committee/351/euth/rep/lad-tc-e.htm|title=Of Life and Death - Table of Contents|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> In 2011 the [[Royal Society of Canada]] published its report on end-of-life decision-making.<ref>[https://rsc-src.ca/en/expert-panels/rsc-reports/end-life-decision-making Royal Society of Canada:End-of-Life Decision Making. 2011]</ref> In the report it recommended that the Criminal Code be modified so as to permit assistance in dying under some circumstances.<ref name=CarterSCC>{{cite web|url=https://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14637/index.do|title=Carter v. Canada (Attorney General) - SCC Cases (Lexum)|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> In 2012 a Select Committee on Dying with Dignity of the [[Quebec National Assembly]] produced a report recommending amendments to legislation to recognize medical aid in dying as being an appropriate component of end-of-life care.<ref name=CBCJune214>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-passes-landmark-end-of-life-care-bill-1.2665834|title=Quebec passes landmark end-of-life-care bill|date=5 June 2014|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> That report resulted in ''An Act respecting end-of-life care'', which is set to come into force on December 10, 2015.<ref name=CarterSCC/><ref name=CBCJune214/><ref>[http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=5&file=2014C2A.PDF ''An Act respecting end-of-life care'', SQ 2014, c 2, s 78]; [http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=2&file=/S_32_0001/S32_0001_A.html CQLR, c. S-32.0001].</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2012, in ''[[Carter v Canada (AG)]]'', the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]] ruled that the criminal offence prohibiting physician assistance of suicide was unconstitutional on the grounds that denying people access to assisted suicide in hard cases was contrary to the [[Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] guarantee of equality under Section 15.<ref name=Carter2012>{{cite web|url=http://www.canlii.org/en/bc/bcsc/doc/2012/2012bcsc886/2012bcsc886.html|title=CanLII - 2012 BCSC 886 (CanLII)|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/06/15/bc-assisted-suicide-ruling.html|title=Assisted-suicide ban struck down by B.C. court - British Columbia - CBC News|publisher=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\nThis decision was subsequently overturned by the majority of the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]] (2:1) on the basis that the issue had already been decided by the Supreme Court of Canada in the Rodriguez case, invoking ''[[stare decisis]]''.\n\nA landmark [[Supreme Court of Canada]] decision on February 6, 2015<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/supreme-court-says-yes-to-doctor-assisted-suicide-in-specific-cases-1.2947487 |title=Supreme Court says yes to doctor-assisted suicide in specific cases |last=Payton |first=Laura |date=February 6, 2015 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC/Radio Canada |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref> overturned the 1993 Rodriguez decision that had ruled against this method of dying. The unanimous decision \nin the further appeal of [[Carter v Canada (AG)]], stated that a total prohibition of physician-assisted death is unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14637/index.do |title=Supreme Court Judgments |author=no by-line.--> |date=February 6, 2015 |website=Supreme Court of Canada |publisher=SCC/CSC |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref> The court's ruling limits exculpation of physicians engaging physician-assisted death to hard cases of \u201ca competent adult person who clearly consents to the termination of life and has a grievous and irremediable medical condition, including an illness, disease or disability, that causes enduring suffering that is intolerable to the individual in the circumstances of his or her condition.\u201d The ruling was suspended for 12 months to allow the Canadian parliament to draft a new, constitutional law to replace the existing one.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/supreme-court-rules-on-doctor-assisted-suicide/article22828437/ Supreme Court rules Canadians have right to doctor-assisted suicide] Sean Fine, Globe and Mail 6 Feb. 2015</ref>\n\nSpecifically the Supreme Court held that the current legislation was overbroad in that it prohibits \"physician\u2011assisted death for a competent adult person who (1) clearly consents to the termination of life and (2) has a grievous and irremediable medical condition (including an illness, disease or disability) that causes enduring suffering that is intolerable to the individual in the circumstances of his or her condition.\" The court decision includes a requirement that there must be stringent limits that are \u201cscrupulously monitored.\u201d This will require the death certificate to be completed by an independent medical examiner, not the treating physician, to ensure the accuracy of reporting the cause of death.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Guichon, Alakija, Doig, Mitchell and Thibeault |date=December 28, 2015 |title=Assisted dying: Four problems, one simple solution |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/assisted-dying-four-problems-one-simple-solution/article27924838/ |newspaper=Glove and Mail |location=Toronto, Canada |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe newly (November 2015) elected federal government subsequently requested a six-month extension for implementation; the arguments for this request were scheduled to be heard by the Supreme Court in January 2016.<ref name=\"The Canadian Press\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/health/canadian-doctors-express-mixed-opinions-on-assisted-dying-1.2715008 |title=Canadian doctors express mixed opinions on assisted dying |author=The Canadian Press |date=December 27, 2015 |website=CTV News |publisher=Bell Media |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian Medical Association (CMA) reported that not all doctors would be willing to help a patient die. The belief in late 2015 was that no physician would be forced to do so. The CMA was already offering educational sessions to members as to the process that would be used after the legislation had been implemented.<ref name=\"The Canadian Press\"/>\n\n===India===\nThe [[Section 309 of the Indian Penal Code|Indian penal code 309]] deals with punishment for attempted suicide. The [[Mental Health Care Act, 2017|Mental Health Care Act 2017]] greatly limits the scope for the code to be implemented.<ref>{{cite news|first=Rhythma|last= Kaul|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mental-healthcare-bill-that-decriminalises-suicide-attempt-passed-by-parliament/story-iL3DXiatxP7BFhS2t4zGCM.html|title=Mental Healthcare Bill decriminalising suicide attempt passed by Parliament|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> The bill states, \u201cAny person who attempts to commit suicide shall be presumed, unless proved otherwise, to have severe stress and shall not be tried and punished under the said Code\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prsindia.org/uploads/media/Mental%20Health/Mental%20Healthcare%20Act,%202017.pdf |title=The Mental Health Care Act, 2017 |publisher=Government of India |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> State governments are required to provide adequate care and rehabilitation for such individuals as to prevent a recurrence of an attempt to suicide.\n\n===Iran===\nThe act of suicide has not been criminalized in the [[Judicial system of Iran|penal law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]].<ref name=\"firoozmand56\">{{cite web |title=Freewill termination: A look into psychological and legislative aspects of suicide in Iran |website=magiran.com |url=http://www.magiran.com/view.asp?Type=pdf&ID=1017038 |language=fa |access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> However, no one is allowed to ask another to kill him/her.<ref name=\"firoozmand56\"/> In addition, threatening to kill oneself is not an offense by the law, however if this act of threatening is done by a prisoner in a [[prison]], then that would be considered as violation of the prisons' regulations and the offender may be punished according to penal law.<ref name=\"firoozmand56\"/>\n\nAccording to the Act. 836 of the [[Judicial system of Iran|civil law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] if a [[suicidal person]] prepares for suicide and writes a [[Will and testament|testament]], if he/she dies, then by law the will is considered void and if he/she doesn't die, then the will is officially accepted and can be carried out.<ref name=\"tabnak\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tabnak.ir/fa/news/530947/\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0647\u06cc-\u0628\u0647-\u062e\u0648\u062f\u06a9\u0634\u06cc-\u0627\u0632-\u0632\u0627\u0648\u06cc\u0647-\u0642\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646\u06cc |title=Suicide from the point of view of law |publisher=[[Mohsen Rezaee|Tabnak News Agency]] |date=September 12, 2015 |access-date=June 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the theory of \"borrowed crime\", because suicide itself is not a crime in penal law, thus any type of assisting in an individual's suicide is not considered a crime and the assistant is not punished.<ref name=\"ettelaat\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ettelaat.com/etiran/?p=35136 |title=Suicide in law and fiqh |publisher=[[Ettela'at]] |date= December 29, 2013 |access-date=June 5, 2016 |author=Amir Sharifi Khezarati}}</ref> [[Assisted suicide|Assisting in suicide]] is considered a crime only when it becomes the \"'''cause'''\" of the suicidal person's death; for example when someone takes advantage of someone else's unawareness or simplicity and convince him/her to kill him/herself. In such cases assisting in suicide is treated as [[murder]] and the offender is punished accordingly.<ref name=\"firoozmand56\"/><ref name=\"ettelaat\"/> In addition, assisting in suicide is considered a crime under section 2 of the Act. 15 of [[Judicial system of Iran|the cyber crimes law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] which was legislated on June 15, 2009. According to the mentioned act, any type of encouragement, stimulation, invitation, simplification of access to lethal substances and/or methods and teaching of suicide with the help of [[computer]] or any other media network is considered assisting in suicide and thus, is punished by imprisonment from 91 days up to 1 year or fines from 5 to 20 million [[Iranian Rials]] or both.<ref name=\"firoozmand56\"/>\n\n===Ireland===\nAttempted suicide is not a criminal offence in Ireland and, under Irish law, self-harm is not generally seen as a form of attempted suicide. It was decriminalised in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1993/en/act/pub/0011/index.html |title=Criminal Law (Suicide) Act, 1993 |publisher=Irishstatutebook.ie |date=1993-06-09 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> Assisted suicide and [[euthanasia]] are illegal. This is currently being challenged at the High Court, as of December 2012. As of 2014 assisted suicide remains illegal in Ireland.\n\n===Malaysia===\nUnder section 309 of the [[Penal Code (Malaysia)|Penal Code of Malaysia]], whoever attempts to commit suicide, and does any act\ntowards the commission of such offence, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to one year or with fine\nor with both.<ref>{{cite web|title=Act 574 Penal Code|url=http://www.agc.gov.my/Akta/Vol.%2012/Act%20574.pdf|website=Attorney General's Chambers Website|access-date=3 July 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226041337/http://www.agc.gov.my/Akta/Vol.%2012/Act%20574.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn the [[Netherlands]], being present and giving moral support during someone's suicide is not a crime; neither is supplying general information on suicide techniques. However, it is a crime to participate in the preparation for or execution of a suicide, including supplying lethal means or instruction in their use. ([[Physician-assisted suicide]] may be an exception. See [[Euthanasia in the Netherlands]].)\n\n===New Zealand===\nAs with many other western societies, [[New Zealand]] currently has no laws against suicide in itself, as a personal and unassisted act. However, as with comparable societies, there are still legislative sanctions against 'assisting or abetting' the suicides of others, under Section 179 of the Crimes Act 1961. (For further details, see [[Euthanasia in New Zealand]].)\n\n===Norway===\nSuicide or attempted suicide is not illegal in Norway. However, [[complicity]] is.<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/nb/dep/jd/dok/regpubl/otprp/2008-2009/otprp-nr-22-2008-2009-/6/5/1.html?id=540447 Justis- og politidepartementet: Ot.prp. nr. 22 (2008-2009) Om lov om endringer i straffeloven 20. mai 2005 nr. 28]. Chapter 6.5.1, page 183.</ref>\n\n===Romania===\nSuicide itself is not illegal in Romania, however encouraging or facilitating the suicide of another person is a criminal offense and is punishable by up to 7, 10 or 20 years in prison, depending on circumstances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II/Q= |title=Penal Code of Romania, art. 191 |access-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308121055/http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II%2FQ%3D |archive-date=8 March 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Russian Federation===\nIn Russia, a person whose [[mental disorder]] \u201cposes a direct (imminent?) danger to themselves\u201d{{Verify source|date=November 2012}} can be [[Involuntary commitment|put into a psychiatric hospital]].\n\nInciting someone to suicide by threats, cruel treatment, or systematic humiliation is punishable by up to 5&nbsp;years in prison. (Article 110 of the [[Criminal Code of the Russian Federation]])\n\n[[Federal law of Russian Federation no. 139-FZ of 2012-07-28]] prescribes censorship of information about methods of suicide on the Internet. According to a website created by the [[Pirate Party of Russia]], some pages with suicide jokes have been [[Russian Internet blacklist|blacklisted]], which may have led to blocking of an IP address of [[Wikia]].<ref name=\"rublacklist\">{{cite web|url=http://rublacklist.net/|title=RUBLACKLIST.NET &#124; \u0420\u041e\u0421\u041a\u041e\u041c\u0421\u0412\u041e\u0411\u041e\u0414\u0410|publisher=rublacklist.net|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n|url = http://hitech.newsru.com/article/02nov2012/rupirtsvscnsr\n|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u0435\u0449\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f \u043a \"\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0431\u043b\u043e\u043a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c\" \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0438\u0437 \"\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\"\n|language = ru\n|publisher = [[NEWSru.com]]\n|date = 2012-11-02\n|accessdate = 2013-01-16\n}}</ref> See also: [[Dumb Ways to Die#Censorship in Russia]].\n\n===Singapore===\nSuicide has been decriminalised since 11 February 2019, with the passing of the Criminal Law Reform Bill,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/law-reforms-passed-outlaw-marital-rape-penalise-voyeurism-11508472|title=Sweeping law reforms to outlaw marital rape, penalise voyeurism passed|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Bills-Supp/6-2019/Published/20190211?DocDate=20190211|title=Criminal Law Reform Bill - Singapore Statutes Online|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> which repealed Section 309<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/PC1871?ProvIds=pr309-|title=Penal Code - Singapore Statutes Online|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> of the Singapore Penal Code.\n\n===South Africa===\nSouth African courts, including the [[Appellate Division (South Africa)|Appellate Division]], have ruled that suicide and attempted suicide are not crimes under the [[Roman-Dutch law]], or that if they ever were crimes, they have been abrogated by disuse. Attempted suicide was from 1886 to 1968 a crime in the [[Transkei]] under the Transkeian Territories Penal Code.<ref>{{cite book |last=Milton |first=John |title=South African Criminal Law and Procedure: Common-law crimes |year=1996 |publisher=Juta |location=Cape Town |edition=3rd |isbn=978-0-7021-3773-0 |pages=353\u2013354}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n\n====England and Wales====\n{{See also|Felo de se}}\nLaws against suicide (and attempted suicide) prevailed in English [[common law]] until 1961. English law perceived suicide as an immoral, criminal offence against God and also against the Crown.<ref>{{citation|title=Constitutional Aspects of Physician-Assisted Suicide After Lee v. Oregon|author=SM Canick|publisher=Am. JL & Med.|year=1997|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/amlmed23&section=9}}</ref> It first became illegal in the 13th century. Until 1822, in fact, the possessions of somebody who committed suicide could even be forfeited to the Crown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holt |first=Gerry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-14374296 |title=BBC News - When suicide was illegal |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-08-03 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\nSuicide ceased to be a criminal offence with the passing of the [[Suicide Act 1961]]; the same Act made it an offence to assist in a suicide. With respect to [[Civil law (common law)|civil law]] the simple act of suicide is lawful but the consequences of dying by suicide might turn an individual event into an unlawful act, as in the case of Reeves v Commissioners of Police of the Metropolis [2000] 1 AC 360,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm |title=House of Lords - Commissioners of Police for the Metropolis v. Reeves (A.P.) (Joint Administratix of the Estate of Martin Lynch, Deceased) |publisher=Parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> where a man in police custody hanged himself and was held equally liable with the police (a cell door defect enabled the hanging) for the loss suffered by his widow; the practical effect was to reduce the police damages liability by 50%. In 2009, the House of Lords ruled that the law concerning the treatment of people who accompanied those who committed assisted suicide was unclear, following [[Debbie Purdy]]'s case that this lack of clarity was a breach of her human rights. (In her case, as a sufferer from multiple sclerosis, she wanted to know whether her husband would be prosecuted for accompanying her abroad where she might eventually wish to commit assisted suicide, if her illness progressed.)\n\n====Scotland====\nSuicide directly involving only the deceased person is not by itself a criminal offence under Scots Law and has not been in recent history. However, attempting suicide might be a [[Breach of the peace]] if it is not done as a private act; this is routinely reported in the case of persons threatening suicide in areas frequented by the public. The Suicide Act 1961 applies only to England and Wales but under [[Scots Law]] a person who assists a suicide might be charged with murder, [[culpable homicide]], or no offence depending upon the facts of each case. Despite not being a criminal offence, consequential liability upon the person attempting suicide (or if successful, his/her estate) might arise under civil law where it parallels the civil liabilities recognised in the (English Law) Reeves case mentioned above.\n\n===United States===\nHistorically, various states listed the act of suicide as a felony, but these policies were sparsely enforced. In the late 1960s, 18 U.S. states had no laws against suicide.<ref>{{citation |volume=6 |publisher=Washburn L.J. |page=395 |date=1966\u20131967 |title=Medical-Legal Aspects of Suicide |author=Litman, Robert E. |url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/wasbur6&section=41}}</ref> By the late 1980s, 30 of the 50 states had no laws against suicide or suicide attempts, but every state had laws declaring it to be a felony to aid, advise, or encourage another person to commit suicide.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Approaches and commonalities of suicide |author=ES Shneidman |publisher=Suicide and its prevention |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=6d3777E9uAEC&oi=fnd&pg=PA14|page=24 |title=Suicide and Its Prevention: The Role of Attitude and Imitation|isbn=9789004086135|year=1989 }}</ref> By the early 1990s only two states still listed suicide as a crime, and these have since removed that classification.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} In some U.S. states, suicide is still considered an unwritten \"[[common law crime]],\" as stated in ''[[Blackstone's Commentaries]]''. (So held the [[Virginia Supreme Court]] in 1992. ''Wackwitz v. Roy'', 418 S.E.2d 861 (Va. 1992)). As a common law crime, suicide can bar recovery for the late suicidal person's family in a lawsuit unless the suicidal person can be proven to have been \"of unsound mind.\" That is, the suicide must be proven to have been an involuntary act of the victim in order for the family to be awarded monetary damages by the court. This can occur when the family of the deceased sues the caregiver (perhaps a jail or hospital) for negligence in failing to provide appropriate care.<ref>[http://www.jaapl.org/cgi/content/full/33/2/176 On Sound and Unsound Mind: The Role of Suicide in Tort and Insurance Litigation], ''Journal of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law'', 2005</ref> Some American legal scholars look at the issue as one of personal liberty. According to [[Nadine Strossen]], former President of the [[ACLU]], \"The idea of government making determinations about how you end your life, forcing you...could be considered [[cruel and unusual punishment]] in certain circumstances, and [[Justice Stevens]] in a very interesting opinion in a [[Right to Die|right-to-die]] [case] raised the analogy.\"<ref>[[n:ACLU President Strossen on religion, drugs, guns and impeaching George Bush#Gun rights|Interview with Nadine Strossen]], David Shankbone, ''[[Wikinews]]'', October 30, 2007.</ref>\nPhysician-assisted suicide is legal in some states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nightingalealliance.org/pdf/state_grid.pdf |title=Account Suspended |publisher=Nightingalealliance.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> For the terminally ill, it is legal in the state of [[Oregon]] under the [[Oregon Death with Dignity Act]]. In Washington state, it became legal in 2009, when a law modeled after the Oregon act, the [[Washington Death with Dignity Act]] was passed. A patient must be diagnosed as having less than six months to live, be of sound mind, make a request orally and in writing, have it approved by two different doctors, then wait 15&nbsp;days and make the request again. A doctor may prescribe a lethal dose of a medication but may not administer it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/health/2009/03/05/washingtons-physician-assisted-suicide-law-takes-effect/tab/article/ |work=The Wall Street Journal |first=Jacob |last=Goldstein |title=Washington's Physician-Assisted Suicide Law Takes Effect |date=March 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn California, medical facilities are empowered or required to commit anyone whom they believe to be suicidal for evaluation and treatment.<ref>See [[Code 5150|California Welfare and Institutions Code section 5150]], for example.</ref>\n\nIn [[Maryland]], it is an open question as to whether suicide is illegal. In 2018, a Maryland man was convicted of [[attempted suicide]].<ref>[http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-suicide-criminal-charge-20180222-story.html Attempting suicide is not a crime under Maryland law. But an Eastern Shore man was convicted of it - Baltimore Sun<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.myeasternshoremd.com/stardem/news/local_news/rare-attempted-suicide-charge-goes-through-caroline-court/article_3e8f7813-a2c6-555c-a8cd-7876e09013e3.html Rare attempted suicide charge goes through Caroline court |Local News |myeasternshoremd.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5441037/Mentally-ill-Maryland-man-convicted-attempted-suicide.html Maryland man convicted of attempted suicide |Daily Mail Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.stardem.com/opinion/columns/attempted-suicide-likely-not-a-crime/article_5cc4e7d0-ffbf-5cce-8eb4-bb7a503141ab.html Attempted suicide likely not a crime |Columns |stardem.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn [[New York State]] in 1917, while suicide was \"a grave public wrong\", an attempt to commit suicide was a felony, punishable by a maximum penalty of two years' imprisonment.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=tEEQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA779&lpg=PA779&dq=suicide+new+york+illegal&source=bl&ots=B3R1Ajow7H&sig=ACfU3U3P6UbmIEOnJmrgNiylXfmnAadZPw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjD06XwqPXjAhWptVkKHQXrAlAQ6AEwK3oECCcQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false McKinney's Consolidated Laws of New York Annotated - New York (State), William Mark McKinney - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=251pAAAAMAAJ&q=%22commit+suicide%22+%22new+york%22+illegal&dq=%22commit+suicide%22+%22new+york%22+illegal |title=Legal Medicine|isbn=9780323010603|year=2001}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[State-assisted suicide]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/30/us-euthanasia-europe-survey-idUSBRE8AT0EG20121130 Large Europe majorities for assisted suicide: survey]\n* [[Wikiversity:Should suicide be legal?|Should suicide be legal?]] - Wikidebate at Wikiversity\n\n{{Law country lists}}\n\n{{Suicide navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Suicide|Legislation]]\n[[Category:Statutory law]]\n", "name_user": "BrainVE", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suicide_legislation"}
{"title_page": "Queen Mary 2", "text_new": "{{short description|British 21st-century transatlantic ocean liner}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English | date = June 2018}}\n{{about|the ship|the monarch|Mary II of England|other uses|Queen Mary (ship)|and|Queen Mary (disambiguation)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image = RMS_Queen_Mary_2_(6973549904).jpg\n|Ship image size = 300px\n|Ship caption = ''Queen Mary 2'' in 2012\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship flag=[[File:Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name=''Queen Mary 2''\n|Ship namesake=[[Mary of Teck]], consort of [[King George V]]\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival]]<ref name = Lloyds>{{Cite ship register|register=LR|id=9241061|shipname=Queen Mary 2|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship operator=[[Cunard Line]]\n|Ship ordered=6 November 2000\n|Ship builder=[[STX Europe]] [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]], [[Saint-Nazaire]], France\n|Ship original cost=UK [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]460&nbsp;million <small>([[euro|\u20ac]]731&nbsp;million, US  $687&nbsp;million)</small>\n|Ship yard number=G32<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunardproductionservices.com/page679/page695/page695.html |title=Queen Mary 2: G32 nightclub |author=Cunard Production Services |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514074143/http://www.cunardproductionservices.com/page679/page695/page695.html |archivedate=14 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=4 July 2002<ref name=qm2techinfo>{{cite web|title=QUEEN MARY 2 TECHNICAL INFORMATION|url=http://www.cunard.com/documents/press%20kits/queen%20mary%202/queen_mary_2_technical.pdf|work=Cunard.com|publisher=Cunard|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n|Ship launched=21 March 2003<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship completed=22 December 2003<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=9241061|shipname=Queen Mary 2 |accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Ship christened=8 January 2004<ref name=qm2techinfo /> by [[Elizabeth II]]\n|Ship maiden voyage=12 January 2004<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship registry=* {{flagicon|Great Britain}} [[Southampton|Southampton, U.K.]] (2004\u20132011)\n* {{flagicon|Bermuda}} [[Hamilton, Bermuda]] (2011\u2013present)\n|Ship status= In service\n|Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: ZCEF6\n*{{IMO Number|9241061}}\n*{{MMSI Number|310627000}}\n}}\n|-\n| Designer:\n|[[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]]\n|-\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Ocean liner]]\n|Ship tonnage={{GT|149,215}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship displacement=79,287 tonnes<ref name = CGMIX>United States Coast Guard Maritime Information Exchange, [https://cgmix.uscg.mil/psix/psixsearch.aspx Search for \"Queen Mary 2\"], Retrieved 2016-07-18</ref>\n|Ship length={{convert|345.03|m|ft|0|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship beam=*{{convert|41|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}} waterline,<ref name = Lloyds />\n*{{convert|147.5|ft|abbr=on}} extreme (bridge wings)<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship height={{convert|236.2|ft|abbr=on}} [[keel]] to (top of) funnel\n|Ship draught={{convert|10.3|m|ft|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship decks=14 passenger, 18 total decks<ref name=\"CunardFacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/cruise-ships/queen-mary-2/ |title=''Queen Mary 2'' \u2013 Ship Facts |publisher=[[Cunard Line]] |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2011-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/ |title=Queen Mary 2: A ship of superlatives |date= |publisher=[[Cunard Line]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|Ship power=* 4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 16V46C-CR (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}16,800{{nbsp}}kW)\n* 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[General Electric]] [[General Electric LM2500|LM2500+]] (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}25,060{{nbsp}}kW)\n|Ship propulsion=[[Integrated electric propulsion]]; [[diesel generators]] & [[gas turbine]]s used to generate electricity to drive four [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]]/[[Alstom]] Mermaid propulsion units (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}21.5{{nbsp}}MW)\n|Ship speed={{convert|30|kn}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Queen Mary 2 |url=http://www.maritimematters.com/queenmary2.html |publisher=Maritime Matters |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030805160525/http://www.maritimematters.com/queenmary2.html |archivedate=5 August 2003 }}</ref>\n|Ship capacity=* 2,695 passengers (after 2016 refit)\n* 2,620 passengers (original design)\n|Ship crew=1,253 officers and crew\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Queen Mary 2''''' (also referred to as the '''''QM2''''') is a British [[transatlantic crossing|transatlantic]] [[ocean liner]]. She has served as the [[flagship]] of [[Cunard Line]] since succeeding ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' in 2004.<ref name=\"largest\">{{Cite web| title = Queen Mary 2, the largest and most expensive ocean liner ever built celebrates tenth birthday| author = Jivanda, Tomas| work = The Independent| date = 2014-03-07| accessdate = 2019-01-24| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/pictures/queen-mary-2-the-largest-and-most-expensive-ocean-liner-ever-built-celebrates-tenth-birthday-9175906.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McDaniel|first1=Colleen|title=New Cruise Ships in 2014|url=http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/articles.cfm?ID=1567 | website=www.cruisecritic.com |publisher=Cruise Critic|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> As of 2020, ''Queen Mary 2'' is the only purpose built passenger ship designed as an ocean liner, as opposed to a [[cruise ship]].<ref name=\"usat_Peek\">{{Cite web| title = Peek inside the last of the great ocean liners| author = Sloan, Gene| work = USA TODAY| date = 2017-03-06| accessdate = 2018-08-17| url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2017/03/06/last-great-ocean-liners/98345830/}}</ref>\n\nThe ship was officially named ''Queen Mary 2'' by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in 2004 after the first {{RMS|Queen Mary}} of 1936. ''Queen Mary'' had in turn been named after [[Mary of Teck]], consort of [[George V|King George V]]. With the retirement of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' in 2008, ''Queen Mary 2'' is the only transatlantic ocean liner in regular service between [[Southampton]], England, and [[New York City]], United States. The ship is also used for cruising, including an annual world cruise.<ref>[http://www.cunard.com/Ships/Queen-Mary-2/ Queen Mary 2 Cruises] ''Cunard'' Retrieved 21 January 2012</ref>\n\nShe was designed by a team of British naval architects led by [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]], and was constructed in France by [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]]. At the time of her construction, ''Queen Mary 2'' was the longest, at {{convert|345.03|m|ft|2|order=flip|abbr=on}}, and largest, with a [[gross tonnage]] of {{GT|148,528}}, [[passenger ship]] ever built. She no longer holds these records after the construction of [[Royal Caribbean International]]'s {{GT|154,407}} {{MS|Freedom of the Seas|3=2}} (a [[cruise ship]]) in April 2006, but remains the largest [[ocean liner]] ever built.\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' was intended for regular scheduled crossings of the Atlantic Ocean, the final cost was approximately $300,000 per berth. The cost was increased by the high quality of materials; having been designed as an ocean liner, she required 40% more steel than a standard cruise ship.<ref name=\"Sealetter Travel Inc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html | title = The History, Construction and Design of ''Queen Mary 2'' | publisher = Sealetter Travel Inc | access-date = 26 March 2006 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110516115948/http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html | archive-date = 16 May 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' has a maximum speed of just over {{convert|30|kn|km/h mph|lk=in}} and a cruising speed of {{convert|26|kn|km/h mph|lk=in}}, which is faster than a contemporary cruise ship. Instead of the common [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] configuration, ''Queen Mary 2'' uses [[integrated electric propulsion]] to achieve her top speed. Diesel engines, augmented by [[gas turbine]]s, are used to generate electricity for electric motors for propulsion and for on-board use.\n\n''Queen Mary 2'''s facilities include fifteen restaurants and bars, five swimming pools, a casino, a ballroom, a theatre, and the first [[planetarium]] at sea.\n\n==Characteristics==\n''Queen Mary 2'' is the flagship of Cunard Line. She was constructed to replace the then  ageing ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'', which was the Cunard flagship from 1969 to 2004 and the last major ocean liner built before ''Queen Mary 2''. ''Queen Mary 2'' had the [[Royal Mail Ship]] (RMS) prefix conferred on her by the [[Royal Mail]] when she entered service in 2004, as a gesture to Cunard's history.<ref>{{cite news | title = Royal Mail employee's Courier newspaper | publisher = Royal Mail | date = August 2007}}</ref>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' is not a [[steamship]] like many of her predecessors, but is powered primarily by four [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel engine]]s, with two additional [[gas turbine]]s providing extra power when required; this [[integrated electric propulsion]] configuration is used to produce the power to drive her four electric propulsion pods as well as the ship's hotel services.<ref name = \"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/> The spaces for these prime movers are also split, and controls are also backed up, with the intention of preventing a single failure from disabling the ship.<ref name = Mathisen/>\n\nLike her predecessor ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' she is built for crossing the Atlantic Ocean, and is also regularly used for cruising. In the winter season she cruises from New York to the Caribbean on twelve or thirteen day tours. ''Queen Mary 2''&apos;s {{convert|30|kn|km/h mph|adj=on}} open ocean speed sets the ship apart from cruise ships, such as {{MS|Oasis of the Seas}}, which has a service speed of {{convert|22.6|kn|km/h mph}}; ''Queen Mary 2''&apos;s normal service speed is {{convert|26|kn|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.com/Documents/Press%20Kits/USA/Queen%20Mary%202/QM2%20Technical.pdf|title=Queen Mary 2 Technical|accessdate=2013-01-08 |publisher=Cunard}}</ref> While the hull of a cruise ship will typically have a [[Hull (watercraft)#Metrics|block coefficient]] of 0.73 (1.0 would represent a rectangular block) ''Queen Mary 2'' is more fine-lined, with a block coefficient of 0.61.<ref name =Mathisen>{{cite web|last=Mathisen|first=Oivind|title=A Ship for the Sea|url=http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-magazine/feature-magazine-articles/67-articles/15.html|work=Cruise Industry News Quarterly Magazine: Winter 2003\u20132004|publisher=Cruise Industry News|accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:QM2-1.jpg|thumb|''Queen Mary 2'' under construction, her [[radar]] [[mast (sailing)|mast]] in the right foreground]]\n{{Building and ship comparison to the Pentagon2|{{RMS|Queen Mary 2}} (pink)}}\nCunard completed a design for a new class of {{GT|84,000}}, 2,000 passenger liners on 8 June 1998, but revised them upon comparing those specifications with [[Carnival Cruise Line]]'s {{GT|100,000}} [[Destiny-class cruise ship|''Destiny''-class]] cruise ships and [[Royal Caribbean International]]'s {{GT|137,276}} [[Voyager-class cruise ship|''Voyager'' class]].<ref name=\"Great Ocean Liners\"/>\n\nIn December 1998, Cunard released details of ''Project Queen Mary'', the project to develop a liner that would complement ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. [[Harland and Wolff]] of [[Northern Ireland]], [[Aker Solutions|Aker Kv\u00e6rner]] of Norway, [[Fincantieri]] of Italy, [[Meyer Werft]] of Germany, and [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]] of France were invited to bid on the project. The contract was finally signed with Chantiers de l'Atlantique, a subsidiary of [[Alstom]], on 6 November 2000. This was the same yard that built Cunard's former rivals, the {{SS|Normandie}} and {{SS|France|1961|6}} of the [[Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale Transatlantique]].<ref name=\"Great Ocean Liners\">{{cite web|url=http://thegreatoceanliners.com/qm2.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426110202/http://thegreatoceanliners.com/qm2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-04-26|title=Queen Mary 2|accessdate=2009-11-07|publisher=The Great Ocean Liners}}</ref>\n\nThe ''QM2's'' [[keel]] was laid down on 4 July 2002, in the construction dock at [[Saint-Nazaire]], [[France]], with the hull number ''G32''. Approximately 3,000 craftsmen spent around eight million working hours on the ship, and around 20,000 people were directly or indirectly involved in her design, construction, and fitting out. In total, 300,000 pieces of steel were assembled into 94 \"blocks\" off the dry dock, which were then positioned and welded together to complete the hull and superstructure.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldshipny.com/qm2pt1.htm | title = Construction of the Largest Liner in the World, Part One, July 4, 2002 ~ March 16, 2003 | publisher = World Ship Society | accessdate = 2009-07-16 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080419083557/http://www.worldshipny.com/qm2pt1.htm |archivedate = 19 April 2008}}</ref>\nAfter floating out on 21 March 2003, the ''Queen Mary 2'' was fitted out in the large fitting out basin (\"Bassin C\"), the first ship to use this huge dry dock since the shipyard built large tankers in the 1970s, such as the [[MV Gastor]]. Her sea trials were conducted during 25\u201329 September and 7\u201311 November 2003,<ref>{{cite book | title = Queen Mary 2: The Birth of a Legend | author = Plisson, Philip | publisher = Harry N. Abrams, Inc | year = 2004 | isbn = 0-8109-5613-6}}</ref> between Saint-Nazaire and the offshore islands of [[\u00cele d'Yeu]] and Belle-\u00cele.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} \n\n===2003 dry dock accident===\nThe final stages of construction were marred by a fatal accident on 15 November 2003, when a gangway collapsed under a group of shipyard workers and their relatives who had been invited to visit the vessel. In total, 32 people were injured and 16 were killed, after a {{convert|15|m|ft|adj=on}} fall into the drydock.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20031116/quennmary2gangwaycollapse_20031116?s_name=&no_ads= | publisher = CTV News | title = Toll climbs in Queen Mary 2 shipyard accident'' | date = 2003-11-16}}</ref>\n\nConstruction was completed on schedule.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} On 22 December 2003, ''Queen Mary 2'' left Saint-Nazaire and arrived in Southampton, England, on 26 December 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/photo_gallery/3349657.stm|title=In pictures: Queen Mary 2 arrives|date=26 December 2003|work=BBC News|access-date=23 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529065714/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/photo_gallery/3349657.stm|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 January 2004, the liner was officially named by Queen [[Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/dorset/3375225.stm|title=Queen launches Queen Mary 2|publisher=BBC|date=2004-01-08|url-status=dead|access-date=9 January 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123232909/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/dorset/3375225.stm|archive-date=23 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>Davidson, Carla. \"[http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2005/4/2005_4_14.shtml Long Live the Queens]\",''American Heritage'', August/September 2005. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060507091822/http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2005/4/2005_4_14.shtml |date=7 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Exterior===\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 in Trondheim 2007.jpg|thumb|right|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Trondheim]], 2007]]\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 lin Cape Town 2011 001.jpg|thumb|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Cape Town]], showing the [[Stern#Others|Costanzi stern]]]]\n\n''Queen Mary 2'''s principal naval architect was [[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival]]'s in-house designer, [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010205111900/http://www.cunard.co.uk/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 February 2001 |title=Cunard press pack:''Future Engineers 2008'' |date=October 2008 |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-23 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He intended many aspects of the ship's design to resemble notable aspects of former ocean liners, such as ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' and the ship's predecessor ''Queen Mary''. These include the three thick black lines  known as \"''hands'' that wrap around either edge of the ship's bridge screen, and at the stern end of the superstructure, which are to recall the appearance of the crossovers of the forward decks on the first ''Queen Mary''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham |first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham |year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|page=22 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' has {{convert|14164|m2|ft2}} of exterior deck space, with wind screens to shield passengers in rough seas. Three of her four swimming pools are outdoors. One of the pools on Deck 12 is covered with a retractable [[magrodome]]. There are indoor pools on Deck 7, in the Canyon Ranch Spa Club, and on Deck 12.\n\nIn common with liners such as {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, there is a continuous wrap-around [[promenade deck]] (Deck 7). This passes behind the bridge screen and allows passengers to circumnavigate the deck while protected from the winds; one circuit is  {{convert|620|m|-1|abbr=on}} long. The flanking promenades are created by the need to step the [[Superstructure#Ships|superstructure]] to allow space for [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]]s. By [[SOLAS Convention|SOLAS]] standards, these should have been lower on the hull ({{convert|15|m|0|abbr=on}} above the waterline), but for the sake of appearance as well as to avoid the danger of large waves damaging the boats, Payne convinced SOLAS officials to exempt ''Queen Mary 2'' from this requirement, and the boats are {{convert|25|m|0|abbr=on}} above the waterline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cybercruises.com/queenmary2two.htm |title=''Queen Mary 2'' |author=Arturo Paniagua Mazorra  |date=14 September 2004 |publisher= |accessdate=2009-11-23}}</ref>\n\nPayne's original intention was for a stern profile with a spoon shape, similar to most previous liners, but the mounting of the [[azimuth thruster|propeller pods]] required a flat [[transom (nautical)|transom]]. The compromise was a [[Stern#Other types of stern|Costanzi stern]]&nbsp;\u2013 a combination of the two, which provides the transom required for azimuthal pod propulsors and has better seaholding characteristics in a following swell.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham|first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham|year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|page=21 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> In common with many modern ships, ''Queen Mary 2'' has a [[bulbous bow]] to reduce [[drag (physics)|drag]] and thereby increase speed, range, and [[fuel efficiency]].<ref name=\"professional mariner\">[http://www.professionalmariner.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=420C4D38DC9C4E3A903315CDDC65AD72&nm=Archives&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=B01E9F24E41844049504B323C52C78FB \"Queen Mary 2:]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Built to keep alive the traditions of the great ocean liners\" ''Professional Mariner'' (2003) Retrieved 11 December 2009</ref>\n[[File:Hull blasting with DOCKMASTER.jpg|thumb|left|[[Bulbous bow]] of ''Queen Mary 2'']]\n\nWhile of a design similar to that of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'', ''Queen Mary 2'''s funnel has a slightly different shape, because a taller funnel would have made it impossible for the ship to pass under the [[Verrazano-Narrows Bridge]] in [[New York City]] at high tide. The final design permits a minimum of {{convert|13|ft|m}} of clearance under the bridge.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barron|first=James|title=This Ship Is So Big, The Verrazano Cringes|newspaper=The New York Times|location=New York|date=18 April 2004|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407E7DC103BF93BA25757C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink+|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nAs ''Queen Mary 2'' is too large to dock in many ports, passengers are often ferried to and from the ship in [[Ship's tender|tenders]], which can also be used as lifeboats. These are stored at sea in [[davit]]s alongside the lifeboats. To transport passengers ashore the tenders pull up to one of four loading stations, each of which has a large hull door that opens hydraulically to form a boarding platform, complete with railings and decking.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' is a [[Panamax#Post-Panamax ships|post-Panamax]] ship. As a result, she must circumnavigate South America to transit between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans. The decision not to constrain her width to transit the [[Panama Canal]] was taken as ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' only transited once a year, during the world cruise. Cunard decided to pass up the convenience of the occasional passage in favour of a greater passenger capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wearecunard.com/2009/01/transiting-the-panama-canal-%E2%80%93-from-east-to-west-or-west-to-east/ |title=Transiting the panama canal-- From East to West or West to East? |author=Alistair Greener |date=22 January 2009 |publisher=Cunard (blog) |accessdate=2009-11-23}}</ref>\n\n===Interior===\nAs is the case with many modern passenger ships, many of the major public rooms on board ''Queen Mary 2'' are on the lowest public decks of the ship, with the passenger cabins stacked above.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/>  This is the opposite of the traditional practice on ocean liners, but the design allowed for larger rooms to be contained within the stronger hull, as well as for more passenger cabins to have private balconies higher up on the ship, where they are less affected by large waves.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} Payne attempted to create a central axis to the two main public room decks (similar in fashion to the ''Normandie''), but a full vista is broken by various public rooms that span the full beam of the ship.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} The dining rooms were placed further aft, though not directly at the stern, where the fore-and-aft [[Euler angles#Tait\u2013Bryan angles|pitching]] of the ship is most noticeable, and might cause discomfort to dining passengers.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nDeck 2, the lowest passenger deck, contains the Illuminations theatre, cinema and planetarium (the first at sea);<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunard|title=Cunard Frequently asked questions: What is Illuminations on Queen Mary 2?|url=https://ask.cunard.com/help/fleet/qm_illuminations |publisher=Cunard Line|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> Royal Court Theatre; Grand Lobby; \"Empire Casino\"; \"Golden Lion Pub\"; and the lower level of the \"Britannia Restaurant\". Deck 3 holds the upper levels of \"Illuminations\", the \"Royal Court theatre\" and the \"Britannia Restaurant\", as well as a small shopping arcade, \"Veuve Cliquot champagne bar\", the \"Chart Room\", \"Sir Samuel's\" wine bar, the \"Queen's Room\", and the \"G32\" Nightclub. The other main public deck is Deck 7, on which are the \"Canyon Ranch Spa\", \"Carinthia Lounge\", \"King's Court\", the \"Queen's Grill Lounge\", and the \"Queen's Grill\" and \"Princess Grill\" restaurants for higher-fare passengers. The public rooms on Deck 8 include the [[\u00e0 la carte]] \"Verandah Restaurant\" an 8,000-volume library<ref name=\"QM2Library\">{{cite journal |last=Burbank |first=Richard D. |year=2005 |title=The ''Queen Mary 2'' Library |journal=Libraries & Culture |volume=40 |issue=4 |pages=547\u2013561 |url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/libraries_and_culture/v040/40.4burbank.html |doi=10.1353/lac.2005.0064}}</ref> (the largest of any cruise ship<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sottili|first1=Carol|title=Which cruise ship library is right for you?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/which-cruise-ship-library-is-right-for-you/2016/06/08/b8ba713a-ff45-11e5-9203-7b8670959b88_story.html|accessdate=13 June 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>), a book shop and the upper part of the Canyon Ranch Spa. Also on Deck 8 is a large outdoor pool and terrace at the stern.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\">[http://www.cunard.com/QMary2_2008_Flash/deckplans.html QM2 Deck Plans] Cunard. Retrieved 27 November 2009</ref> The [[kennel]]s, located aft on starboard side of Deck 12, are available only for transatlantic crossings. They can accommodate up to twenty two dogs (the kennels will also take cats) in small and large cages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5547& |title=Cunard unleashes new amenities for pampered pets |date=15 February 2006 |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503043042/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5547& |archivedate=3 May 2009 }}</ref>\n[[File:QM2 Grand Lobby.JPG|thumb|right|The lower two decks of the Grand Lobby on ''Queen Mary 2'']]\n\nThe King's Court area on the ship is open twenty four hours a day, serving as a buffet restaurant for breakfast and lunch. The overall space is divided into quarters, with each section decorated according to the theme of the four separate alternate dining venues that are \"created\" each evening through lighting, tableware, and menus: Lotus, which specialises in [[Asian cuisine]]; the Carvery, a British style grille; La Piazza, with [[Italian cuisine|Italian food]]; and the Chef's Galley, which offers an interactive experience to food preparation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/Documents/Press%20Kits/Queen%20Mary%202/Queen_Mary_2_Public_Rooms.pdf |title=QUEEN MARY 2 |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html |title=Mazorra, Arturo Paniagua; ''Sealetter Cruise Magazine'': The History, Construction and Design of Queen Mary 2 |publisher=Sealetter.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516115948/http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html |archive-date=16 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe passengers' dining arrangements on board are dictated by the type of accommodation in which they choose to travel.  Around 85% of passengers are in ''Britannia'' class, and, therefore, dine in the main restaurant. However, passengers can choose to upgrade to either a \"junior suite\", and dine in the \"Princess Grill\"', or a suite, and dine in the \"Queens' Grill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/uploads/QM2FactSheet.pdf |title=''Cunard'':QM2 Fact Sheet |publisher=Cunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/columnist/gaynor/2005-08-16-column_x.htm |title=Gaynor, Louisa Frey: The Queen (Mary 2) rules the Atlantic |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2005-08-17 |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> Those in the two latter categories are grouped together by Cunard as \"Grill Passengers\", and they are permitted to use the \"Queens' Grill Lounge\" and a private outdoor area on deck 11 with its own whirlpool.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/><ref>''Liverpool Daily Post'' \"Queen Mary 2 Liverpool visit: The ship that offers her passengers \u2018trip of a lifetime\u2019\" 21 October 2009</ref> This feature is also present on both ''Queen Victoria'' and ''Queen Elizabeth''. However, all other public areas can be used by all passengers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.com/uploads/QVPUBLICROOMS.pdf  |title=Queen Victoria Public Rooms |date= |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref>\n\nAs the Britannia Restaurant takes up the full width of the ship on two decks, a 'tween deck, called Deck 3L, was devised to allow passengers to walk from the Grand Lobby to the Queen's Room without traversing the dining room mid-meal. The deck consists of two corridors that run beneath the upper balcony of the restaurant on Deck 3, and above the main dining area on Deck 2. This is why the balcony of the Britannia has tiers that step up towards the hull. This arrangement is illustrated on the hull where there is a stack of three rows of windows in the area where the main restaurant sits, the two upper and lower most rows illuminate the dining room, while the centre row serves Deck 3L. There is a similar arrangement through the Royal Court Theatre. As well, the passages that run on either side of Illuminations on Deck 3 ramp upwards to compensate for the change in deck elevation between the entrance to Illuminations and an elevator bank forward of the room.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/>\n[[File:Queen Mary 2 bronze sculpture by John McKenna.jpg|John McKenna's bronze sculpture panel on the grand lobby staircase|thumb|left]]\nMore than 5000 commissioned works of art are visible in ''Queen Mary 2'''s public rooms, corridors, staterooms and lobbies, having been created by 128 artists from sixteen different countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=547&article_id=1566 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040808221124/http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=547&article_id=1566 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2004-08-08 |title=The art of cruising in luxury |publisher=Nqsouthern.com |accessdate=2011-06-27 }}</ref> Two of the most notable pieces are Barbara Broekman's [[tapestry]], an abstract depiction of an ocean liner, bridge, and New York skyline which spans the full height of the Britannia Restaurant, and the British sculptor [[John McKenna (sculptor)|John McKenna's]] sheet bronze relief [[mural]] in the Grand Lobby, a seven square metre portrait of the ship fabricated in bronze inspired by the Art Deco mural in the main dining room of the original ''Queen Mary''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onk.nl/en/qm2.htm  |title=Queen Mary 2 |date= |publisher=Onderneming & Kunst |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> The 10th Deck Pavillion features a glass ellipse sculpture by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] called \"Blue Sun Setting in the Ocean\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barwyszkla.pl/szklo-w-architekturze-tomasz-urbanowicz/|title=Szk\u0142o w architekturze - Tomasz Urbanowicz|last=Fabia\u0144ska|first=Patrycja|date=2013-07-01|year=2013|editor-last=Bochacz|editor-first=Andrzej|website=Barwy Szk\u0142a|language=pl-PL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Technical aspects==\n\n===Power plant and propulsion system===\n''Queen Mary 2'''s power plant comprises four sixteen-cylinder [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 16V46CR ''EnviroEngine'' marine [[diesel engine]]s, generating a combined {{convert|67200|kW|hp|abbr=on|lk=on}} at 514 rpm, and two [[General Electric LM2500]]+ [[gas turbine]]s, provide a further {{convert|50000|kW|hp|abbr=on}}; these drive [[electric generator]]s, which in turn provide the power to drive four {{convert|21500|kW|hp|abbr=on}} [[Alstom]] [[electric motor|electrical motors]] located inside the podded propulsors (and thus entirely outside the vessel's hull).<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>  Such an arrangement, known as [[integrated electric propulsion]] (IEP), provides for economical cruising at low speed combined with an ability to sustain much higher speeds when required, and has been common in [[naval ship|naval vessels]] for several decades.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\nThe propulsors are [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] Mermaid [[Azimuth thruster|azimuth thruster type podded propulsion units]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsion/electrical_pod/default.jsp |title=Electrical Pod |accessdate=2007-12-03 |publisher=Rolls Royce Marine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020171710/http://www.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsion/electrical_pod/default.jsp |archivedate=20 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsors/podded/index.jsp |title=Azimuthing electrical podded propulsor |publisher=Rolls-Royce |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> each with one forward-facing low-vibration [[propeller]] with separately bolted blades. The forward pair of thrusters is fixed, but the aft pair can [[azimuth thruster|swivel]] through 360\u00b0, removing the need for a [[rudder]].<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/> ''Queen Mary 2'' is the first quadruple-propeller passenger ship completed since the [[SS France (1961)|SS ''France'']] in 1961.<ref>{{cite book |title=Enso-Gutzeit Oy laivanvarustajana: Oy Finnlines Ltd ja Merivienti Oy 1947\u20131982 |last=Karonen |first=Petri |year=1992 |publisher=Enso-Gutzeit |location=Imatra |isbn=952-9690-00-2 |pages=106\u2013109 |url= |language=Finnish }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' carries eight spare blades on the foredeck, immediately forward of the bridge screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beyondships.com/QM2-art-Watling.html|title=What makes QM2 go?}}</ref>  In addition to the primary thrusters, the ship is also fitted with three [[manoeuvring thruster|bow thrusters]], with a power output of 3.2&nbsp;MW each. These allow the ship to turn in its own length while in port, to conduct more complex docking manoeuvres.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n[[File:QM2-propeller-spares.jpg|thumb|Three of the eight spare propeller blades mounted on the foredeck]]\nUnusually, ''Queen Mary 2'''s gas turbines are not housed along with her diesels in the [[engine room]] deep in her hull, but instead are in a soundproofed enclosure directly beneath the funnel. This arrangement allowed the vessel's designers to supply the oxygen-hungry turbines with air intakes without having to run air ducts the height of the ship, which would have wasted valuable interior space.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n===Navigation===\n''Queen Mary 2'' has a fully integrated bridge system designed by British firm [[Kelvin Hughes]], which controls the ship's navigation systems, radar, dynamic positioning system, and engine monitoring system. Kelvin Hughes supplied many of the ship's components, including the [[Electronic Chart Display and Information System]] (ECDIS) and eight multifunction display units.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/200108/content/kelvin-hughes-bridge-209053 |title=Kelvin Hughes Bridge Chosen For ''Queen Mary 2'' |magazine=Maritime Reporter and Engineering News |date=August 2001 |page=45 |publisher=New Wave Media}}</ref>\n\n===Water supply===\nFresh water aboard ''Queen Mary 2'' is supplied by three seawater [[desalination]] plants. The plants, each with a capacity of {{convert|630000|L|USgal}} per day, use [[Multiple-effect distillation|multiple effect]] plate (MEP) distillation technology. The plants' energy is supplied primarily by steam and cooling water from the ship's gas turbines and diesel engines, or if needed by steam from the ship's two oil-fired boilers. The traditional [[multiple-effect distillation]] technology has been improved for the ship's plant, so that [[Fouling#Micro fouling|scaling]] of plates is reduced, vastly reducing maintenance required. The desalinated water has a very low salt content of less than five parts per million. Average total water production is {{convert|1100000|L|USgal}} per day with a capacity of {{convert|1890000|L|USgal}} so that there is ample spare capacity. The ship could easily be supplied by only two of the three plants.<ref name=\"Alstom\">{{cite book | title= ''Queen Mary 2'': The Genesis of a Queen |publisher=Alstom Chantiers de l'Atlantique, A Publication of the Naval Architect | year = 2004 | pages = 50\u201355}}</ref> Potable water tanks have a capacity of {{convert|3830000|L|USgal}}, enough for more than three days of supply.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\">Cunard. RMS Queen Mary 2 Technical Specification. Flyer made available to passengers of the ''Queen Mary 2''.</ref> If the engines are running on low load (when the ship is running at a slow speed) the engine jacket cooling water temperature is insufficient to heat the seawater to run the desalination plants. In that case steam from oil-fired boilers is used to heat the sea water. This is uneconomical as generating steam is expensive. It may be cheaper, therefore, to buy water in a particular port than to produce it on board. The seawater intakes are located in the hull of the ship. Concentrated salt solution ([[brine]]) is discharged to the sea closer to the ship's stern together with cooling water from the engines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infotechfrance.com/cgi-local/affichage_signet_secteur.pl?UNI_ID=8&RUB_ID=54&SS_ID=6746&SEC_ID=25 |title=UBIFRANCE Orelis' technology to recycle Queen Mary 2's waste water |date=16 April 2004  |publisher= |accessdate=26 November 2009}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> An additional plant was added during the 2016 refit.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Environmental performance===\n{{See also|Environmental impact of shipping}}\n\nWhen designing ''Queen Mary 2'', the designers considered that tighter environmental regulations would be implemented while the ship was in service, such as energy efficiency, the reuse of treated wastewater for non-potable uses and zero discharge of solid waste into the sea.<ref name=\"professional mariner\"/><ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/>\n\nAccording to Cunard, the ship exceeds some requirements of the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution From Ships ([[MARPOL 73/78]]) of the [[International Maritime Organization]]. It discharges waste into the sea only in areas more than {{convert|12|nmi|mi|abbr=on}} from any coast, even though MARPOL allows discharge of treated organic waste and treated bilge water closer to the shore. Discharges of potentially harmful substances, in particular the residual oil content of treated bilge water and air emissions, are monitored regularly to ensure compliance with environmental standards.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/> In areas where air pollution from [[sulfur dioxide]], which causes [[acid rain]], is a concern, the ship switches to low-sulfur fuel to minimise air pollution.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[carbon offset]] company [[Climate Care]], passenger ships release more carbon dioxide into the atmosphere per passenger mile than long haul flights. Cunard attempted to reduce the [[carbon footprint]] of ''Queen Mary 2'' by improving engine efficiency and reducing friction while the ship is in motion. In November 2008, the ship was given a refit in [[Hamburg]], part of which involved the repainting of the hull in paint which is designed to reduce drag and improve fuel economy.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2006/dec/20/cruises.green |title=Is cruising any greener than flying? |date=20 December 2006 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref> According to [[Blohm+Voss]], her 2016 refit included the installation of \"scrubbers\" and exhaust gas filters to reduce emissions.<ref>{{cite press release|last=Brasse|first=Michael|date=23 May 2016|title=Master refit: The Queen Mary 2 docks at Blohm+Voss on May 27, 2016|url=http://www.blohmvoss.com/var/blohmvoss/storage/original/application/ea05ca9e3bab8c78463d07ae6006ba57.pdf|location=Hamburg, DE|publisher=Blohm+Voss GmbH|access-date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Service history==\n<!-- IMAGES IN THIS SECTION: Please do not add unnecessary images here - images should only be used to illustrate the text better; this is not a gallery. If you wish to add an image, please consider bringing it up on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 in san francisco bay.jpg|thumb|left|''Queen Mary 2 ''in [[San Francisco Bay]] in 2007]]\nOn 12 January 2004 ''Queen Mary 2'' set sail on her [[maiden voyage]] from [[Southampton]], [[England]], to [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], in the United States, carrying 2,620 passengers. She was under the command of captain Ronald Warwick, who had previously commanded ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. Warwick is the son of William (Bill) Warwick, who had also been a senior Cunard officer and the first captain of ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. The ship returned to Southampton late from her maiden voyage after bow doors covering the thrusters failed to shut in Portugal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/passengers-threaten-mutiny-on-crippled-queen-mary-2-340386.html |title=Passengers threaten mutiny on crippled 'Queen Mary 2' |author=Elaine Barker |date=23 January 2006 |work=The Independent |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] ''Queen Mary 2'' sailed to [[Athens]] and docked at [[Piraeus]] for two weeks for use as a floating hotel, serving the then Prime Minister of the United Kingdom [[Tony Blair]] and his wife [[Cherie Blair|Cherie]], French President [[Jacques Chirac]], then United States President [[George W. Bush]], and the United States Olympic men's basketball team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=549&article_id=2619 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041001102749/http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=549&article_id=2619 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2004-10-01 |title=''Queen Mary 2'' will be floating fortress |publisher=Nqsouthern.com |accessdate=2011-06-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-08-16/sports/18275842_1_olympics-queen-mary-athens |last=Smith |first=Tim |title=Watch out aboard Queen Mary because ship is sinking |work=NY Daily News |date=2004-08-16 |accessdate=2011-06-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527150820/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-08-16/sports/18275842_1_olympics-queen-mary-athens |archive-date=27 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to Cunard, ''Queen Mary 2'''s passengers have also included jazz musician [[Dave Brubeck]] and singers [[Rod Stewart]], [[Carly Simon]], and [[James Taylor]].<ref>[http://www.cunard.com/cunard-experience/media-centre/stars-aboard/queen-mary-2/ Stars on board Queen Mary 2]</ref>\n\nOne 2005 transatlantic crossing saw ''Queen Mary 2'' carrying, in a locked steamer trunk, the first United States copy of [[J. K. Rowling]]'s book ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', autographed by the author. In a promotional press release for the event, Cunard said that this marked the first time a book had been transported to its international launch aboard an ocean liner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5160&Page=3 |title=World's most famous ocean liner carries first J.K. Rowling-signed US copy of ''Harry Potter and the Half Blood Prince'' |date=7 November 2005 |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210084553/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5160&Page=3 |archivedate=10 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006 ''Queen Mary 2'' embarked on a circumnavigation of South America. Upon departure from Fort Lauderdale, one of her [[azimuth thruster|propeller pod]]s was damaged when it struck a channel wall, forcing the ship to sail at a reduced speed, which resulted in Commodore Warwick's decision to skip several calls on its voyage to [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Many of her passengers threatened to stage a [[sit-in]] protest because of the missed calls, before Cunard offered to refund the voyage costs. ''Queen Mary 2'' continued to operate at a reduced service speed and several itinerary changes were necessary until repairs had been completed after the ship returned to Europe in June, where ''Queen Mary 2'' paid a visit to dry dock and the damaged propeller pod was unseated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1509030/Cunard-foils-QM2-mutiny-with-full-refund-offer.html |title=Cunard foils QM2 mutiny with full refund offer |author1=Andrew Downe |author2=Amy Iggulden |date=28 Jan 2006|work=The Telegraph |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> In November, ''Queen Mary 2'' was drydocked once more at the [[Blohm+Voss]] yard in [[Hamburg]] (drydock [[Elbe 17]]) for the reinstallation of the repaired propeller pod. At the same time, sprinkler systems were installed in all of the vessel's balconies to comply with new safety regulations which had come into effect since the MS ''[[Star Princess (2001)|Star Princess]]'' fire. Additionally, both bridge wings were extended by two metres to improve visibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blohmvoss-repair.com/pdf/buv_rep_allg_in.pdf|title=Blohmvoss Repair Schedule-2006|publisher=Blohmvoss|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708073658/http://www.blohmvoss-repair.com/pdf/buv_rep_allg_in.pdf|archivedate=8 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Mary II at Liverpool 1.jpg|thumb|left|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Pier Head]], [[Liverpool]], England during a 2009 visit]]\n\nAfter completing the journey around South America, on 23 February 2006, ''Queen Mary 2'' met her namesake, the original {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, which is permanently docked at [[Long Beach, California]]. Escorted by a flotilla of smaller ships, the two ''Queens'' exchanged a \"whistle salute\" which was heard throughout the city of Long Beach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cruiseline.co.uk/qm2-cruises/p-id/cruise-news/queen-mary-2-meets-namesake-queen-mary-on-february-22-marking-a-cunard-milestone/ |title=Queen Mary 2 Meets Namesake Queen Mary on February 22 Marking a Cunard Milestone |date=12 January 2006 |publisher=The Cruise Line Ltd. |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911094454/http://www.cruiseline.co.uk/qm2-cruises/p-id/cruise-news/queen-mary-2-meets-namesake-queen-mary-on-february-22-marking-a-cunard-milestone/ |archivedate=11 September 2009 }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' met the other serving Cunard liners {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' on 13 January 2008 near the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City harbour, with a celebratory fireworks display; ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' and ''Queen Victoria'' made a tandem crossing of the Atlantic for the meeting. This marked the first time three Cunard ''Queens'' have been present in the same location. Cunard stated this would be the last time these three ships would ever meet,<ref name=\"cunard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/rendezvous |title=Royal Rendezvous : The Luxury Cruise Ships of Cunard : Cunard Cruise Line |publisher=Cunard |date=2011-03-03 |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> due to ''Queen Elizabeth 2'''s impending retirement from service in late 2008.<ref name=\"Cunard Press Release\">{{cite web|url= http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=6656&Active=News | publisher=Cunard Line|title= QE2 to leave Cunard fleet and be sold to Dubai World to begin a new life at the palm |year=2007|accessdate=2007-06-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706160214/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=6656&Active=News <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=2007-07-06}}</ref> However this would prove not to be the case, as the three ''Queens'' met in Southampton on 22 April 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/7361808.stm  |title=Royal gathering of sea 'Queens' |author=Eleanor Williams |date=22 April 2008  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/7360081.stm  |title=Three 'Queens' in final meeting |date=22 April 2008  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-27}}[]</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' rendezvoused with ''Queen Elizabeth 2''  in Dubai on Saturday 21 March 2009, after the latter ship's retirement,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chriscunard.com/qe2/qe2-history/#retirement |title=QE2 Retirement |publisher=chriscunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> while both ships were berthed at [[Port Rashid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chriscunard.com/qe2/qe2-dubai/ |title=QE2 and QM2 in Dubai |publisher=Chriscunard.com |date=2009-03-21 |accessdate=2019-07-11 }}</ref> With the withdrawal of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' from Cunard's fleet and its docking in Dubai, ''Queen Mary 2'' became the only ocean liner left in active passenger service.\n\nOn 3 August 2007 three men were stopped by police while escorting and piloting a replica of the [[Turtle (submersible)|first American combat submarine]] within {{convert|200|ft}} of ''Queen Mary 2'', which was docked at the cruise ship terminal in [[Red Hook, Brooklyn]]. The replica was created by New York artist [[Duke Riley|Philip \"Duke\" Riley]] and two out-of-town residents, one of whom claimed to be a descendant of [[David Bushnell]], who had invented it. The [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] issued Riley a citation for having an unsafe vessel, and for violating the security zone around ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref>[[#QM2|Makeshift submarine found in East River]]</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://nymag.com/arts/books/features/robert-sullivan-my-american-revolution-2012-9/|title=Permanent Revolution|magazine=New York magazine|date=10 Sep 2012}}</ref>\nOn 19 October 2011, ''Queen Mary 2'' had her registry changed to [[Hamilton, Bermuda]], from her previous home port of Southampton, to allow the ship to host on-board weddings. This marked the first time in its 171-year history that Cunard has not had a ship registered within the UK.<ref>[http://www.cruisecritic.com/news/news.cfm?ID=4634 It's Official: Cunard Re-flags Cruise Ships in Bermuda, Launches Weddings at Sea], cruisecritic.com, 19 October 2011</ref> Bermuda is a member of the [[Red Ensign Group]] and the ship continues to fly the undefaced Red Ensign rather than the Bermuda Red Ensign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bermudashipping.bm/useful-information/faqs |title=FAQs \u2013 Bermuda Shipping and Maritime Registry|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===World cruises===\n[[File:qm2 sydney.jpg|thumb|400px|''Queen Mary 2'' in [[Sydney]], 20 February 2007]]\nOn 10 January 2007, ''Queen Mary 2'' started her first world cruise, circumnavigating the globe in 81 days. On 20 February, she met her fleet-mate, ''Queen Elizabeth 2'', also on her 2007 world cruise, in [[Sydney]] harbour.<!-- http://www.cunard.com/CruiseItinerary.asp?cruiseid=2802&LeftNav=Planner&Active=&Sub=&OB=&Region= No longer useful--> <!--http://www.cunard.com/CruiseItinerary.asp?cruiseid=2803&LeftNav=Planner&Active=&Sub=&OB=&Region= No longer useful--><ref>{{cite news|title=QM2 sails into Sydney|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/travel/qm2sailsintosydney/2007/02/20/1171733718604.html|accessdate=5 October 2013|newspaper=The Age Company Ltd.|date=20 February 2007}}</ref> This is the first time two Cunard ''Queens'' had been together in Sydney since the original ''Queen Mary'' and ''Queen Elizabeth'' served as troop ships in 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatoceanliners.net/queenelizabeth.html |title=''Queen Elizabeth'' 1940\u20131973 |publisher=The Great Ocean Liners |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213153036/http://www.greatoceanliners.net/queenelizabeth.html |archivedate=13 February 2009 }}</ref> Despite the early arrival time of 5:42&nbsp;am, the ''Queen Mary 2'''s presence attracted so many viewers that the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] and [[Anzac Bridge]] were blocked.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/sorry-sydney-for-ship-shocker/2007/02/21/1171733803476.html |title=Sydney in meltdown as hordes crowd to see giant ships |author1=David Braithwaite |author2=Andrew Clennell |author3=Deborah Snow |date=21 February 2007|work=Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> With 1,600 passengers leaving the ships in Sydney, Cunard estimated the stopovers injected more than $3&nbsp;million into the local economy.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/travel/super-ships-choke-city/2007/02/20/1171733718091.html Super ships choke city] ''Sydney Morning Herald'' 20 February 2007 Retrieved 11 December 2009</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2012, the ship embarked on a three-month world cruise from Southampton, travelling south and then east around Africa, a first ever circumnavigation of Australia, to Japan, then back to Southampton along the south coastline of Eurasia and through the Suez Canal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seascanner.com/reise.php?reise=32316|title=World Cruise Cruise with RMS Queen Mary 2 on 10/01/2012 (M203)|work=seascanner.com}}</ref>\n\n===Anniversary voyage===\nIn October 2009, ''Queen Mary 2'''s fifth year in service was celebrated with an 8-night voyage around the British Isles. The voyage included maiden visits to [[Greenock]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8314297.stm |title=Huge cruise liner visiting city (Greenock) |date=19 October 2009  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref> and [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/8315670.stm |title=Town welcomes huge cruise liner (Liverpool) |date=20 October 2009  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref>\n\n===The Boston Cup===\nCarried aboard ''Queen Mary 2'' is the Boston Cup. Sometimes referred to as ''The Britannia Cup'', this artifact was created for Sir [[Samuel Cunard]] in [[Boston]], United States, to commemorate the arrival of his first vessel {{RMS|Britannia}}.<ref name=chrisboston>{{cite web |url=https://www.chriscunard.com/history-fleet/the-boston-cup/ |title=The Boston Cup |work=Chris' Cunard Page |accessdate=2010-02-16 }}</ref> Cunard had selected Boston as the American port for his Atlantic service, which resulted in a strong connection between Boston and the Cunard Line.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham |first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham |year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|pages=46\u201349 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> It is believed that the cup was presented to Sir Samuel Cunard sometime in 1840, but for much of its life it was missing. It was discovered in an antique shop in 1967 and returned to Cunard, where it was placed aboard ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. In 2004, when ''Queen Mary 2'' became the flagship, the Boston Cup was placed aboard ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref name=chrisboston /> It is in a glass case, aft of the Chart Room lounge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wearecunard.com/2009/07/cunard-celebrates-a-special-anniversary/ |title=Cunard Celebrates a Special Anniversary |publisher=Wearecunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007 the [[National Geographic Channel]] broadcast an episode of the documentary series ''[[Megastructures]]'' about ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref>[http://www.natgeochannel.co.uk/programmes/megastructures/schedule Megastructures: List of Episodes] ''National Geographic Channel UK'' Retrieved 12 December 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406171409/http://www.natgeochannel.co.uk/programmes/megastructures/schedule |date=6 April 2009 }}</ref> The vessel also featured in the pilot episode of the documentary TV series ''[[Mighty Ships]]''.\n\n===Propulsion failures===\nThe propulsor pods fitted to ''Queen Mary 2'' have been prone to failure, attributed to the motors' thrust bearings, which continued to show a tendency to fail even after numerous attempts at redesign. In January 2009, Carnival, through its Cunard division, sued Rolls-Royce in the United States. The line alleged that the Mermaid pod propulsion systems fitted to ''Queen Mary 2'' were inherently defective in design, and that Rolls-Royce knew about the design deficiencies and deliberately conspired to mislead, deceive and defraud in the course of winning the contract.<ref name=\"fail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ebearing.com/news2009/011601.htm |title=Specifications:Carnival Sues Rolls-Royce Over Queen Mary... |accessdate=2011-01-19 |date=2009-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710165803/http://www.ebearing.com/news2009/011601.htm |archive-date=10 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In January 2011, the court awarded Carnival US$24&nbsp;million (approximately UK\u00a315&nbsp;million at the time of verdict).<ref name=\"fail2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldsaltblog.com/2011/01/08/the-tale-of-the-mermaid-pods-carnival-awarded-24-million-in-lawsuit-with-rolls-royce/ |title=The Tale of the Mermaid Pods |accessdate=2011-01-19 |date=2009-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Cunard Royal Rendezvous===\nTwo years after the first Cunard Royal Rendezvous on the same date ''Queen Mary 2'' met up with {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and the then brand-new {{MS|Queen Elizabeth}} for another Royal Rendezvous in New York City on 13 January 2011. {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and {{MS|Queen Elizabeth|3=2}} made a tandem crossing of the Atlantic for the event. All three ships met in front of the statue of Liberty at 6:45&nbsp;pm for [[Fireworks by Grucci|Grucci]] fireworks. The Empire State Building was lit up in red to mark the event.<ref name=\"cunard1\"/>\n\nOn 5 June 2012, the three Queens met again, but this time in [[Southampton]] to celebrate the [[Diamond jubilee]] of [[Queen regnant|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/5207-3711-cunard-line-announces-2012-2013-deployment.html |title=Cunard Line Announces 2012\u20132013 Deployment \u2013 Cruise Industry News &#124; Cruise News |publisher=Cruise Industry News |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Atlantic rowing===\n''Queen Mary 2'' has rendezvoused with [[ocean rowing]] teams in the middle of the Atlantic.  On 30 July 2010 she met up with ''Artemis Investments'', whose rowing crew were [[Don Lennox (rower)|Don Lennox]], [[Livar Nysted]], [[Ray Carroll]], [[Leven Brown]].  Carroll had been a former engineer and was patched through via [[marine VHF radio]] and ''Queen Mary 2's'' [[public address system]] to speak to the captain and crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://maritimematters.com/2010/07/qm2s-mid-atlantic-rendezvous/|title=QM2's Mid-Atlantic Rendezvous|work=Maritime Matters|date=30 July 2010|first=Martin|last=Cox|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/29368|title=World record holder Carroll returns to home soil|work=Galway Advertiser|date=5 August 2010|first=Linley|last=Mackenzie|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/all-oar-nothing-how-four-men-conquered-the-atlantic-1-1368113|title=All oar nothing: How four men conquered the Atlantic|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=30 July 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> On 26 September 2013 ''Queen Mary 2'' resupplied solo-rower Myl\u00e8ne Paquette and her vessel ''Hermel'' with a replacement [[satellite phone]], [[drogue]] anchor and groceries. ''Queen Mary 2'' changed her course by 20 degrees and only added 14 miles to the overall distance of the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2433659|title=Cruise ship to the rescue! Queen Mary 2 delivers supplies to solo woman rower|first=Sarah|last=Gordon|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=26 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mylenepaquette.com/en/to-the-captain-of-the-queen-mary-2-and-his-wife/|title=Letter to the Captain of the Queen Mary 2 and his wife|first=Myl\u00e8ne|last=Paquette|date=27 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005031803/http://www.mylenepaquette.com/en/to-the-captain-of-the-queen-mary-2-and-his-wife/|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24290017|title=Queen Mary 2 comes to aid of Canadian rower Mylene Paquette|work=BBC News Online|date=26 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shipmonk.co.uk/2013/09/29/i-want-to-sail-the-atlantic-single-handed-says-queen-mary-2-captain-after-helping-lone-rower/|title=I want to sail the Atlantic single-handed, says ''Queen Mary 2'' captain after helping lone rower|first=Dave|last=Monk|accessdate=29 September 2013|quote=We made a 20-degree alteration to the south and it only added fourteen miles to our overall distance.|work=Shipmonk}}</ref>\n\n===Engine fire===\nA small fire broke out in the gas turbine engine room (located high on the ship behind the Queen Mary 2 sign<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondships.com/QM2-art-Watling.html|title=Queen Mary 2 \u2013 Interview with Chief Engineer Brian Watling|work=beyondships.com}}</ref>) on the evening of 5 October 2011. The fire was started in one of the ship's gas turbines. No injuries were reported, and crew on board the ship safely extinguished the fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.usatoday.com/cruises/post/2011/10/queen-mary-2-fire/551219/1|title=Travel News, Tips, and Guides - USATODAY.com|work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n===Plant incident===\nOn 23 September 2010, an incident occurred in ''Queen Mary 2'''s aft [[Power conditioner|harmonic filter]] room. This resulted in the shutdown of all four propulsion motors and a loss of electrical power throughout the ship. Within an hour, the ship's main generators were restarted and the ship was able to resume passage. Later investigations found that an explosion was caused by electrical arcing within the aft harmonic filter igniting leaked dielectric fluid vapour.<ref>[http://www.maib.gov.uk/publications/investigation_reports/2011/qm2.cfm Report on the investigation of the catastrophic failure of a capacitor in the aft harmonic filter room on board RMS Queen Mary 2 while approaching Barcelona ], Marine Accident Investigation Branch. 2010-09-23.</ref>\n\n===200th transatlantic voyage===\nOn 6 July 2013 ''Queen Mary 2'' departed New York en route to Southampton on her 200th transatlantic voyage. On board speakers were [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne OBE]]\u2014the ship's designer\u2014and presenter and newsreader [[Nick Owen]], who presented talks about the ship's design.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Mary 2 Celebrates 200th Transatlantic Crossing |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/88530/queen-mary-2-celebrates-200th-transatlantic-crossing/ |publisher=World Maritime News |date=9 July 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===10th birthday celebrations===\n[[File:Red ensign QM2 1July2014.JPG|thumb|Undefaced [[Red Ensign]] flown by RMS ''Queen Mary 2'' in New York, July 2014.]]\nOn 6 May 2014, all three Queens met up for the first time in [[Lisbon]], Portugal. The three ships sailed abreast of each other from Lisbon to Southampton. On 9 May 2014 ''Queen Elizabeth'' and ''Queen Victoria'' led ''Queen Mary 2'' up the Southampton channel where they docked in formation at the QEII terminal and performed a birthday salute to ''Queen Mary 2''.  The anniversary included a tour of the ship by His Royal Highness The Duke of Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite news|title=Back at the helm: Duke of Edinburgh visits the Bridge (and even keeps smiling while touring the ship's LAUNDRY) to celebrate Queen Mary 2's 10th anniversary|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2624078/Cunards-Queen-Mary-2-celebrates-10th-anniversary-Duke-Edinburgh.html|accessdate=7 July 2014|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cunard 175th anniversary===\nOn 25 May 2015, all three Queens met, once again, at [[Liverpool]], in order to celebrate the 175th anniversary of the shipping line. After arriving at Liverpool the previous day, ''Queen Mary 2'' made a brief excursion to the entrance of the [[River Mersey]] to welcome her two fleetmates into port in the early afternoon. The three Cunarders then sailed, in formation, towards Liverpool. The ships spent several hours together, before the departure of ''Queen Mary 2'' to [[Saint Peter Port]], [[Guernsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32872777|title=Cunard shipping marks 175 years in Liverpool|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/three-queens-liverpool-2015-key-9094540|title=Three Queens Liverpool 2015: Key times for all the weekend events |work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/campaigns/anniversary-cruises/175-celebration/|title=Anniversary cruises 2015|publisher=Cunard|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2015, ''Queen Mary 2'' began a ''175th Anniversary Crossing'' in Southampton. She sailed first to Liverpool, leaving that city after a fireworks display on 4 July, the actual anniversary date of Cunard's first transatlantic voyage. ''Queen Mary 2'' followed the route of the original ship ''Britannia'', calling first at Halifax, Nova Scotia. After a day there, she headed first upriver into the harbor, using her bow thrusters and swivel-pod motors to negotiate the tight turnaround to come back down close to the cityfront. A 21-gun salute and bagpipe band honored the ship.\n\nFrom Halifax, the ship sailed to Boston and was there for a full day at the cruise terminal (Boston was the terminus of the original crossing in 1840). In the evening the ship backed out into [[Boston Harbor]], where a fireworks display was presented before ''Queen Mary 2'' sailed away.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. festivities set as Queen Mary 2 celebrates 175 years of Cunard crossings |url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-trb-new-york-cunard-light-show-20150706-story.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=7 July 2015}}</ref> After a night and day at sea, the vessel entered New York Harbor early the morning of 14 July and docked at the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal. Later in the evening the vessel sailed to the lower harbor, between the Statue of Liberty and the Battery, for the ''Forever Cunard Queen Mary 2 Light Show.''<ref>{{cite web|title=FORever cunard queen mary 2 light show|url=http://www.quantumtheatricalservices.com/queen-mary-2-light-show|publisher=Quantum Theatricals|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20161001 Queen Mary Aerial 2.jpg|thumb|left|240px|The RMS Queen Mary 2 visiting [[Sydney Harbour (Nova Scotia)|Sydney Harbour]], [[Cape Breton Island]] on October 1st, 2016.]]\n=== 2016 refit ===\nIn June 2016, ''Queen Mary 2'' was put through a $132&nbsp;million/\u00a390&nbsp;million renovation at [[Blohm+Voss]] over 25 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Machan |first1=Teresa |title=First look at Cunard's new-look RMS Queen Mary 2 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/articles/first-look-at-cunards-new-look-rms-queen-mary-2/ |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sloan |first1=Gene |title=Peek inside the last great ocean liners, from Queen Mary to the SS United States |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2018/09/04/queen-mary-ss-united-states-iconic-ocean-liners/764185002/ |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=USA Today |language=en}}</ref> Major changes include the addition of fifteen single occupancy staterooms, thirty additional balcony staterooms, and ten more animal cages for an enlarged kennels.<ref name=\"refit\">{{cite press release | url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cunard-flagship-queen-mary-2-151500362.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130015047/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cunard-flagship-queen-mary-2-151500362.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=30 January 2016 | title=Cunard flagship Queen Mary 2 to undergo major refurbishment in early summer 2016, befitting the world's most iconic ocean liner | publisher=CNW Group | date=15 July 2015 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Atlantic rescue===\nOn 10 June 2017, Queen Mary 2, commanded by Captain Christopher Wells, came to the rescue of a stranded solo yachtsman, 73-year-old Mervyn Wheatley, whose craft ''Tamarind'' had been disabled by a strong storm while participating in the [[Observer Single-handed Trans-Atlantic Race]]. British and Canadian coastguards coordinated this long-range rescue after they detected Tamarind's distress beacon. ''Queen Mary 2'' was guided to Wheatley's position by a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] aircraft.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jun/11/mervyn-wheatley-73-queen-mary-2-liner-rescue-north-atlantic-storm The Guardian 11 June 2017]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Plowman-Aust Cruise Ships}}\n*{{Saunders-Giants of the Seas}}\n*{{Smith-Cruise Ships-2010}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.cunard.com/en-us/cruise-ships/queen-mary-2/9 Cunard: ''Queen Mary 2'', Official website]\n* [http://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/310627000 Location tracking] at MarineTraffic\n* [http://chriscunard.com/qm2/ ''Queen Mary 2'' (QM2) on Chris' Cunard Page]\n* [http://www.galutschek.at/ships/qm2/ Video Clips of QM2 at Newport and Boston]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/cruise-ships/14805/Cunard-Queen-Mary-2.html ''\"Queen Mary 2\"'']&nbsp;\u2014\u2013 review by Douglas Ward in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', London.\n\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{Cunard ships}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen Mary 2}}\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Chantiers de l'Atlantique]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Cunard Line]]\n[[Category:2003 ships]]\n[[Category:Passenger ships of Bermuda]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British 21st-century transatlantic ocean liner}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English | date = June 2018}}\n{{about|the ship|the monarch|Mary II of England|other uses|Queen Mary (ship)|and|Queen Mary (disambiguation)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image = RMS_Queen_Mary_2_(6973549904).jpg\n|Ship image size = 300px\n|Ship caption = ''Queen Mary 2'' in 2012\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship flag=[[File:Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name=''Queen Mary 2''\n|Ship namesake=[[Mary of Teck]], consort of [[King George V]]\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival]]<ref name = Lloyds>{{Cite ship register|register=LR|id=9241061|shipname=Queen Mary 2|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship operator=[[Cunard Line]]\n|Ship ordered=6 November 2000\n|Ship builder=[[STX Europe]] [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]], [[Saint-Nazaire]], France\n|Ship original cost=UK [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]460&nbsp;million <small>([[euro|\u20ac]]731&nbsp;million, US  $687&nbsp;million)</small>\n|Ship yard number=G32<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunardproductionservices.com/page679/page695/page695.html |title=Queen Mary 2: G32 nightclub |author=Cunard Production Services |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514074143/http://www.cunardproductionservices.com/page679/page695/page695.html |archivedate=14 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=4 July 2002<ref name=qm2techinfo>{{cite web|title=QUEEN MARY 2 TECHNICAL INFORMATION|url=http://www.cunard.com/documents/press%20kits/queen%20mary%202/queen_mary_2_technical.pdf|work=Cunard.com|publisher=Cunard|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n|Ship launched=21 March 2003<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship completed=22 December 2003<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=9241061|shipname=Queen Mary 2 |accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Ship christened=8 January 2004<ref name=qm2techinfo /> by [[Elizabeth II]]\n|Ship maiden voyage=12 January 2004<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship registry=* {{flagicon|Great Britain}} [[Southampton|Southampton, U.K.]] (2004\u20132011)\n* {{flagicon|Bermuda}} [[Hamilton, Bermuda]] (2011\u2013present)\n|Ship status= In service\n|Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: ZCEF6\n*{{IMO Number|9241061}}\n*{{MMSI Number|310627000}}\n}}\n|-\n| Designer:\n|[[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]]\n|-\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Ocean liner]]\n|Ship tonnage={{GT|149,215}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship displacement=79,287 tonnes<ref name = CGMIX>United States Coast Guard Maritime Information Exchange, [https://cgmix.uscg.mil/psix/psixsearch.aspx Search for \"Queen Mary 2\"], Retrieved 2016-07-18</ref>\n|Ship length={{convert|345.03|m|ft|0|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship beam=*{{convert|41|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}} waterline,<ref name = Lloyds />\n*{{convert|147.5|ft|abbr=on}} extreme (bridge wings)<ref name=qm2techinfo />\n|Ship height={{convert|236.2|ft|abbr=on}} [[keel]] to (top of) funnel\n|Ship draught={{convert|10.3|m|ft|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name = Lloyds />\n|Ship decks=14 passenger, 18 total decks<ref name=\"CunardFacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/cruise-ships/queen-mary-2/ |title=''Queen Mary 2'' \u2013 Ship Facts |publisher=[[Cunard Line]] |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2011-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/ |title=Queen Mary 2: A ship of superlatives |date= |publisher=[[Cunard Line]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|Ship power=* 4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 16V46C-CR (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}16,800{{nbsp}}kW)\n* 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[General Electric]] [[General Electric LM2500|LM2500+]] (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}25,060{{nbsp}}kW)\n|Ship propulsion=[[Integrated electric propulsion]]; [[diesel generators]] & [[gas turbine]]s used to generate electricity to drive four [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]]/[[Alstom]] Mermaid propulsion units (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}21.5{{nbsp}}MW)\n|Ship speed={{convert|30|kn}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Queen Mary 2 |url=http://www.maritimematters.com/queenmary2.html |publisher=Maritime Matters |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030805160525/http://www.maritimematters.com/queenmary2.html |archivedate=5 August 2003 }}</ref>\n|Ship capacity=* 2,695 passengers (after 2016 refit)\n* 2,620 passengers (original design)\n|Ship crew=1,253 officers and crew\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Queen Mary 2''''' (also referred to as the '''''QM2''''') is a British [[transatlantic crossing|transatlantic]] [[ocean liner]]. She has served as the [[flagship]] of [[Cunard Line]] since succeeding ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' in 2004.<ref name=\"largest\">{{Cite web| title = Queen Mary 2, the largest and most expensive ocean liner ever built celebrates tenth birthday| author = Jivanda, Tomas| work = The Independent| date = 2014-03-07| accessdate = 2019-01-24| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/pictures/queen-mary-2-the-largest-and-most-expensive-ocean-liner-ever-built-celebrates-tenth-birthday-9175906.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McDaniel|first1=Colleen|title=New Cruise Ships in 2014|url=http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/articles.cfm?ID=1567 | website=www.cruisecritic.com |publisher=Cruise Critic|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> As of 2020, ''Queen Mary 2'' is the only purpose built passenger ship designed as an ocean liner, as opposed to a [[cruise ship]].<ref name=\"usat_Peek\">{{Cite web| title = Peek inside the last of the great ocean liners| author = Sloan, Gene| work = USA TODAY| date = 2017-03-06| accessdate = 2018-08-17| url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2017/03/06/last-great-ocean-liners/98345830/}}</ref>\n\nThe ship was officially named ''Queen Mary 2'' by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in 2004 after the first {{RMS|Queen Mary}} of 1936. ''Queen Mary'' had in turn been named after [[Mary of Teck]], consort of [[George V|King George V]]. With the retirement of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' in 2008, ''Queen Mary 2'' is the only transatlantic ocean liner in regular service between [[Southampton]], England, and [[New York City]], United States. The ship is also used for cruising, including an annual world cruise.<ref>[http://www.cunard.com/Ships/Queen-Mary-2/ Queen Mary 2 Cruises] ''Cunard'' Retrieved 21 January 2012</ref>\n\nShe was designed by a team of British naval architects led by [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]], and was constructed in France by [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]]. At the time of her construction, ''Queen Mary 2'' was the longest, at {{convert|345.03|m|ft|2|order=flip|abbr=on}}, and largest, with a [[gross tonnage]] of {{GT|148,528}}, [[passenger ship]] ever built. She no longer holds these records after the construction of [[Royal Caribbean International]]'s {{GT|154,407}} {{MS|Freedom of the Seas|3=2}} (a [[cruise ship]]) in April 2006, but remains the largest [[ocean liner]] ever built.\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' was intended for regular scheduled crossings of the Atlantic Ocean, the final cost was approximately $300,000 per berth. The cost was increased by the high quality of materials; having been designed as an ocean liner, she required 40% more steel than a standard cruise ship.<ref name=\"Sealetter Travel Inc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html | title = The History, Construction and Design of ''Queen Mary 2'' | publisher = Sealetter Travel Inc | access-date = 26 March 2006 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110516115948/http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html | archive-date = 16 May 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' has a maximum speed of just over {{convert|30|kn|km/h mph|lk=in}} and a cruising speed of {{convert|26|kn|km/h mph|lk=in}}, which is faster than a contemporary cruise ship. Instead of the common [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] configuration, ''Queen Mary 2'' uses [[integrated electric propulsion]] to achieve her top speed. Diesel engines, augmented by [[gas turbine]]s, are used to generate electricity for electric motors for propulsion and for on-board use.\n\n''Queen Mary 2'''s facilities include fifteen restaurants and bars, five swimming pools, a casino, a ballroom, a theatre, and the first [[planetarium]] at sea.\n\n==Characteristics==\n''Queen Mary 2'' is the flagship of Cunard Line. She was constructed to replace the then  ageing ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'', which was the Cunard flagship from 1969 to 2004 and the last major ocean liner built before ''Queen Mary 2''. ''Queen Mary 2'' had the [[Royal Mail Ship]] (RMS) prefix conferred on her by the [[Royal Mail]] when she entered service in 2004, as a gesture to Cunard's history.<ref>{{cite news | title = Royal Mail employee's Courier newspaper | publisher = Royal Mail | date = August 2007}}</ref>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' is not a [[steamship]] like many of her predecessors, but is powered primarily by four [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel engine]]s, with two additional [[gas turbine]]s providing extra power when required; this [[integrated electric propulsion]] configuration is used to produce the power to drive her four electric propulsion pods as well as the ship's hotel services.<ref name = \"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/> The spaces for these prime movers are also split, and controls are also backed up, with the intention of preventing a single failure from disabling the ship.<ref name = Mathisen/>\n\nLike her predecessor ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' she is built for crossing the Atlantic Ocean, and is also regularly used for cruising. In the winter season she cruises from New York to the Caribbean on twelve or thirteen day tours. ''Queen Mary 2''&apos;s {{convert|30|kn|km/h mph|adj=on}} open ocean speed sets the ship apart from cruise ships, such as {{MS|Oasis of the Seas}}, which has a service speed of {{convert|22.6|kn|km/h mph}}; ''Queen Mary 2''&apos;s normal service speed is {{convert|26|kn|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.com/Documents/Press%20Kits/USA/Queen%20Mary%202/QM2%20Technical.pdf|title=Queen Mary 2 Technical|accessdate=2013-01-08 |publisher=Cunard}}</ref> While the hull of a cruise ship will typically have a [[Hull (watercraft)#Metrics|block coefficient]] of 0.73 (1.0 would represent a rectangular block) ''Queen Mary 2'' is more fine-lined, with a block coefficient of 0.61.<ref name =Mathisen>{{cite web|last=Mathisen|first=Oivind|title=A Ship for the Sea|url=http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-magazine/feature-magazine-articles/67-articles/15.html|work=Cruise Industry News Quarterly Magazine: Winter 2003\u20132004|publisher=Cruise Industry News|accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:QM2-1.jpg|thumb|''Queen Mary 2'' under construction, her [[radar]] [[mast (sailing)|mast]] in the right foreground]]\n{{Building and ship comparison to the Pentagon2|{{RMS|Queen Mary 2}} (pink)}}\nCunard completed a design for a new class of {{GT|84,000}}, 2,000 passenger liners on 8 June 1998, but revised them upon comparing those specifications with [[Carnival Cruise Line]]'s {{GT|100,000}} [[Destiny-class cruise ship|''Destiny''-class]] cruise ships and [[Royal Caribbean International]]'s {{GT|137,276}} [[Voyager-class cruise ship|''Voyager'' class]].<ref name=\"Great Ocean Liners\"/>\n\nIn December 1998, Cunard released details of ''Project Queen Mary'', the project to develop a liner that would complement ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. [[Harland and Wolff]] of [[Northern Ireland]], [[Aker Solutions|Aker Kv\u00e6rner]] of Norway, [[Fincantieri]] of Italy, [[Meyer Werft]] of Germany, and [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]] of France were invited to bid on the project. The contract was finally signed with Chantiers de l'Atlantique, a subsidiary of [[Alstom]], on 6 November 2000. This was the same yard that built Cunard's former rivals, the {{SS|Normandie}} and {{SS|France|1961|6}} of the [[Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale Transatlantique]].<ref name=\"Great Ocean Liners\">{{cite web|url=http://thegreatoceanliners.com/qm2.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426110202/http://thegreatoceanliners.com/qm2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-04-26|title=Queen Mary 2|accessdate=2009-11-07|publisher=The Great Ocean Liners}}</ref>\n\nThe ''QM2's'' [[keel]] was laid down on 4 July 2002, in the construction dock at [[Saint-Nazaire]], [[France]], with the hull number ''G32''. Approximately 3,000 craftsmen spent around eight million working hours on the ship, and around 20,000 people were directly or indirectly involved in her design, construction, and fitting out. In total, 300,000 pieces of steel were assembled into 94 \"blocks\" off the dry dock, which were then positioned and welded together to complete the hull and superstructure.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldshipny.com/qm2pt1.htm | title = Construction of the Largest Liner in the World, Part One, July 4, 2002 ~ March 16, 2003 | publisher = World Ship Society | accessdate = 2009-07-16 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080419083557/http://www.worldshipny.com/qm2pt1.htm |archivedate = 19 April 2008}}</ref>\nAfter floating out on 21 March 2003, the ''Queen Mary 2'' was fitted out in the large fitting out basin (\"Bassin C\"), the first ship to use this huge dry dock since the shipyard built large tankers in the 1970s, such as the [[MV Gastor]]. Her sea trials were conducted during 25\u201329 September and 7\u201311 November 2003,<ref>{{cite book | title = Queen Mary 2: The Birth of a Legend | author = Plisson, Philip | publisher = Harry N. Abrams, Inc | year = 2004 | isbn = 0-8109-5613-6}}</ref> between Saint-Nazaire and the offshore islands of [[\u00cele d'Yeu]] and Belle-\u00cele.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} \n\n===2003 dry dock accident===\nThe final stages of construction were marred by a fatal accident on 15 November 2003, when a gangway collapsed under a group of shipyard workers and their relatives who had been invited to visit the vessel. In total, 32 people were injured and 16 were killed, after a {{convert|15|m|ft|adj=on}} fall into the drydock.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20031116/quennmary2gangwaycollapse_20031116?s_name=&no_ads= | publisher = CTV News | title = Toll climbs in Queen Mary 2 shipyard accident'' | date = 2003-11-16}}</ref>\n\nConstruction was completed on schedule.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} On 22 December 2003, ''Queen Mary 2'' left Saint-Nazaire and arrived in Southampton, England, on 26 December 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/photo_gallery/3349657.stm|title=In pictures: Queen Mary 2 arrives|date=26 December 2003|work=BBC News|access-date=23 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529065714/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/photo_gallery/3349657.stm|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 January 2004, the liner was officially named by Queen [[Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/dorset/3375225.stm|title=Queen launches Queen Mary 2|publisher=BBC|date=2004-01-08|url-status=dead|access-date=9 January 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123232909/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/dorset/3375225.stm|archive-date=23 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>Davidson, Carla. \"[http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2005/4/2005_4_14.shtml Long Live the Queens]\",''American Heritage'', August/September 2005. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060507091822/http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2005/4/2005_4_14.shtml |date=7 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Exterior===\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 in Trondheim 2007.jpg|thumb|right|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Trondheim]], 2007]]\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 lin Cape Town 2011 001.jpg|thumb|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Cape Town]], showing the [[Stern#Others|Costanzi stern]]]]\n\n''Queen Mary 2'''s principal naval architect was [[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival]]'s in-house designer, [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010205111900/http://www.cunard.co.uk/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 February 2001 |title=Cunard press pack:''Future Engineers 2008'' |date=October 2008 |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-23 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He intended many aspects of the ship's design to resemble notable aspects of former ocean liners, such as ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' and the ship's predecessor ''Queen Mary''. These include the three thick black lines  known as \"''hands'' that wrap around either edge of the ship's bridge screen, and at the stern end of the superstructure, which are to recall the appearance of the crossovers of the forward decks on the first ''Queen Mary''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham |first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham |year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|page=22 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' has {{convert|14164|m2|ft2}} of exterior deck space, with wind screens to shield passengers in rough seas. Three of her four swimming pools are outdoors. One of the pools on Deck 12 is covered with a retractable [[magrodome]]. There are indoor pools on Deck 7, in the Canyon Ranch Spa Club, and on Deck 12.\n\nIn common with liners such as {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, there is a continuous wrap-around [[promenade deck]] (Deck 7). This passes behind the bridge screen and allows passengers to circumnavigate the deck while protected from the winds; one circuit is  {{convert|620|m|-1|abbr=on}} long. The flanking promenades are created by the need to step the [[Superstructure#Ships|superstructure]] to allow space for [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]]s. By [[SOLAS Convention|SOLAS]] standards, these should have been lower on the hull ({{convert|15|m|0|abbr=on}} above the waterline), but for the sake of appearance as well as to avoid the danger of large waves damaging the boats, Payne convinced SOLAS officials to exempt ''Queen Mary 2'' from this requirement, and the boats are {{convert|25|m|0|abbr=on}} above the waterline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cybercruises.com/queenmary2two.htm |title=''Queen Mary 2'' |author=Arturo Paniagua Mazorra  |date=14 September 2004 |publisher= |accessdate=2009-11-23}}</ref>\n\nPayne's original intention was for a stern profile with a spoon shape, similar to most previous liners, but the mounting of the [[azimuth thruster|propeller pods]] required a flat [[transom (nautical)|transom]]. The compromise was a [[Stern#Other types of stern|Costanzi stern]]&nbsp;\u2013 a combination of the two, which provides the transom required for azimuthal pod propulsors and has better seaholding characteristics in a following swell.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham|first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham|year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|page=21 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> In common with many modern ships, ''Queen Mary 2'' has a [[bulbous bow]] to reduce [[drag (physics)|drag]] and thereby increase speed, range, and [[fuel efficiency]].<ref name=\"professional mariner\">[http://www.professionalmariner.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=420C4D38DC9C4E3A903315CDDC65AD72&nm=Archives&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=B01E9F24E41844049504B323C52C78FB \"Queen Mary 2:]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Built to keep alive the traditions of the great ocean liners\" ''Professional Mariner'' (2003) Retrieved 11 December 2009</ref>\n[[File:Hull blasting with DOCKMASTER.jpg|thumb|left|[[Bulbous bow]] of ''Queen Mary 2'']]\n\nWhile of a design similar to that of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'', ''Queen Mary 2'''s funnel has a slightly different shape, because a taller funnel would have made it impossible for the ship to pass under the [[Verrazano-Narrows Bridge]] in [[New York City]] at high tide. The final design permits a minimum of {{convert|13|ft|m}} of clearance under the bridge.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barron|first=James|title=This Ship Is So Big, The Verrazano Cringes|newspaper=The New York Times|location=New York|date=18 April 2004|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407E7DC103BF93BA25757C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink+|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nAs ''Queen Mary 2'' is too large to dock in many ports, passengers are often ferried to and from the ship in [[Ship's tender|tenders]], which can also be used as lifeboats. These are stored at sea in [[davit]]s alongside the lifeboats. To transport passengers ashore the tenders pull up to one of four loading stations, each of which has a large hull door that opens hydraulically to form a boarding platform, complete with railings and decking.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n''Queen Mary 2'' is a [[Panamax#Post-Panamax ships|post-Panamax]] ship. As a result, she must circumnavigate South America to transit between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans. The decision not to constrain her width to transit the [[Panama Canal]] was taken as ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' only transited once a year, during the world cruise. Cunard decided to pass up the convenience of the occasional passage in favour of a greater passenger capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wearecunard.com/2009/01/transiting-the-panama-canal-%E2%80%93-from-east-to-west-or-west-to-east/ |title=Transiting the panama canal-- From East to West or West to East? |author=Alistair Greener |date=22 January 2009 |publisher=Cunard (blog) |accessdate=2009-11-23}}</ref>\n\n===Interior===\nAs is the case with many modern passenger ships, many of the major public rooms on board ''Queen Mary 2'' are on the lowest public decks of the ship, with the passenger cabins stacked above.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/>  This is the opposite of the traditional practice on ocean liners, but the design allowed for larger rooms to be contained within the stronger hull, as well as for more passenger cabins to have private balconies higher up on the ship, where they are less affected by large waves.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} Payne attempted to create a central axis to the two main public room decks (similar in fashion to the ''Normandie''), but a full vista is broken by various public rooms that span the full beam of the ship.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} The dining rooms were placed further aft, though not directly at the stern, where the fore-and-aft [[Euler angles#Tait\u2013Bryan angles|pitching]] of the ship is most noticeable, and might cause discomfort to dining passengers.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nDeck 2, the lowest passenger deck, contains the Illuminations theatre, cinema and planetarium (the first at sea);<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunard|title=Cunard Frequently asked questions: What is Illuminations on Queen Mary 2?|url=https://ask.cunard.com/help/fleet/qm_illuminations |publisher=Cunard Line|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> Royal Court Theatre; Grand Lobby; \"Empire Casino\"; \"Golden Lion Pub\"; and the lower level of the \"Britannia Restaurant\". Deck 3 holds the upper levels of \"Illuminations\", the \"Royal Court theatre\" and the \"Britannia Restaurant\", as well as a small shopping arcade, \"Veuve Cliquot champagne bar\", the \"Chart Room\", \"Sir Samuel's\" wine bar, the \"Queen's Room\", and the \"G32\" Nightclub. The other main public deck is Deck 7, on which are the \"Canyon Ranch Spa\", \"Carinthia Lounge\", \"King's Court\", the \"Queen's Grill Lounge\", and the \"Queen's Grill\" and \"Princess Grill\" restaurants for higher-fare passengers. The public rooms on Deck 8 include the [[\u00e0 la carte]] \"Verandah Restaurant\" an 8,000-volume library<ref name=\"QM2Library\">{{cite journal |last=Burbank |first=Richard D. |year=2005 |title=The ''Queen Mary 2'' Library |journal=Libraries & Culture |volume=40 |issue=4 |pages=547\u2013561 |url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/libraries_and_culture/v040/40.4burbank.html |doi=10.1353/lac.2005.0064}}</ref> (the largest of any cruise ship<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sottili|first1=Carol|title=Which cruise ship library is right for you?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/which-cruise-ship-library-is-right-for-you/2016/06/08/b8ba713a-ff45-11e5-9203-7b8670959b88_story.html|accessdate=13 June 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>), a book shop and the upper part of the Canyon Ranch Spa. Also on Deck 8 is a large outdoor pool and terrace at the stern.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\">[http://www.cunard.com/QMary2_2008_Flash/deckplans.html QM2 Deck Plans] Cunard. Retrieved 27 November 2009</ref> The [[kennel]]s, located aft on starboard side of Deck 12, are available only for transatlantic crossings. They can accommodate up to twenty two dogs (the kennels will also take cats) in small and large cages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5547& |title=Cunard unleashes new amenities for pampered pets |date=15 February 2006 |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503043042/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5547& |archivedate=3 May 2009 }}</ref>\n[[File:QM2 Grand Lobby.JPG|thumb|right|The lower two decks of the Grand Lobby on ''Queen Mary 2'']]\n\nThe King's Court area on the ship is open twenty four hours a day, serving as a buffet restaurant for breakfast and lunch. The overall space is divided into quarters, with each section decorated according to the theme of the four separate alternate dining venues that are \"created\" each evening through lighting, tableware, and menus: Lotus, which specialises in [[Asian cuisine]]; the Carvery, a British style grille; La Piazza, with [[Italian cuisine|Italian food]]; and the Chef's Galley, which offers an interactive experience to food preparation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/Documents/Press%20Kits/Queen%20Mary%202/Queen_Mary_2_Public_Rooms.pdf |title=QUEEN MARY 2 |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html |title=Mazorra, Arturo Paniagua; ''Sealetter Cruise Magazine'': The History, Construction and Design of Queen Mary 2 |publisher=Sealetter.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516115948/http://www.sealetter.com/Jun-04/qm2.html |archive-date=16 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe passengers' dining arrangements on board are dictated by the type of accommodation in which they choose to travel.  Around 85% of passengers are in ''Britannia'' class, and, therefore, dine in the main restaurant. However, passengers can choose to upgrade to either a \"junior suite\", and dine in the \"Princess Grill\"', or a suite, and dine in the \"Queens' Grill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/uploads/QM2FactSheet.pdf |title=''Cunard'':QM2 Fact Sheet |publisher=Cunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/columnist/gaynor/2005-08-16-column_x.htm |title=Gaynor, Louisa Frey: The Queen (Mary 2) rules the Atlantic |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2005-08-17 |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> Those in the two latter categories are grouped together by Cunard as \"Grill Passengers\", and they are permitted to use the \"Queens' Grill Lounge\" and a private outdoor area on deck 11 with its own whirlpool.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/><ref>''Liverpool Daily Post'' \"Queen Mary 2 Liverpool visit: The ship that offers her passengers \u2018trip of a lifetime\u2019\" 21 October 2009</ref> This feature is also present on both ''Queen Victoria'' and ''Queen Elizabeth''. However, all other public areas can be used by all passengers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cunard.com/uploads/QVPUBLICROOMS.pdf  |title=Queen Victoria Public Rooms |date= |publisher=Cunard |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref>\n\nAs the Britannia Restaurant takes up the full width of the ship on two decks, a 'tween deck, called Deck 3L, was devised to allow passengers to walk from the Grand Lobby to the Queen's Room without traversing the dining room mid-meal. The deck consists of two corridors that run beneath the upper balcony of the restaurant on Deck 3, and above the main dining area on Deck 2. This is why the balcony of the Britannia has tiers that step up towards the hull. This arrangement is illustrated on the hull where there is a stack of three rows of windows in the area where the main restaurant sits, the two upper and lower most rows illuminate the dining room, while the centre row serves Deck 3L. There is a similar arrangement through the Royal Court Theatre. As well, the passages that run on either side of Illuminations on Deck 3 ramp upwards to compensate for the change in deck elevation between the entrance to Illuminations and an elevator bank forward of the room.<ref name=\"Cunard:QM2 Deck Plans\"/>\n[[File:Queen Mary 2 bronze sculpture by John McKenna.jpg|John McKenna's bronze sculpture panel on the grand lobby staircase|thumb|left]]\nMore than 5000 commissioned works of art are visible in ''Queen Mary 2'''s public rooms, corridors, staterooms and lobbies, having been created by 128 artists from sixteen different countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=547&article_id=1566 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040808221124/http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=547&article_id=1566 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2004-08-08 |title=The art of cruising in luxury |publisher=Nqsouthern.com |accessdate=2011-06-27 }}</ref> Two of the most notable pieces are Barbara Broekman's [[tapestry]], an abstract depiction of an ocean liner, bridge, and New York skyline which spans the full height of the Britannia Restaurant, and the British sculptor [[John McKenna (sculptor)|John McKenna's]] sheet bronze relief [[mural]] in the Grand Lobby, a seven square metre portrait of the ship fabricated in bronze inspired by the Art Deco mural in the main dining room of the original ''Queen Mary''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onk.nl/en/qm2.htm  |title=Queen Mary 2 |date= |publisher=Onderneming & Kunst |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> The 10th Deck Pavillion features a glass ellipse sculpture by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] called \"Blue Sun Setting in the Ocean\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barwyszkla.pl/szklo-w-architekturze-tomasz-urbanowicz/|title=Szk\u0142o w architekturze - Tomasz Urbanowicz|last=Fabia\u0144ska|first=Patrycja|date=2013-07-01|year=2013|editor-last=Bochacz|editor-first=Andrzej|website=Barwy Szk\u0142a|language=pl-PL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>format\n\n==Technical aspects==\n\n===Power plant and propulsion system===\n''Queen Mary 2'''s power plant comprises four sixteen-cylinder [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 16V46CR ''EnviroEngine'' marine [[diesel engine]]s, generating a combined {{convert|67200|kW|hp|abbr=on|lk=on}} at 514 rpm, and two [[General Electric LM2500]]+ [[gas turbine]]s, provide a further {{convert|50000|kW|hp|abbr=on}}; these drive [[electric generator]]s, which in turn provide the power to drive four {{convert|21500|kW|hp|abbr=on}} [[Alstom]] [[electric motor|electrical motors]] located inside the podded propulsors (and thus entirely outside the vessel's hull).<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>  Such an arrangement, known as [[integrated electric propulsion]] (IEP), provides for economical cruising at low speed combined with an ability to sustain much higher speeds when required, and has been common in [[naval ship|naval vessels]] for several decades.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\nThe propulsors are [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] Mermaid [[Azimuth thruster|azimuth thruster type podded propulsion units]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsion/electrical_pod/default.jsp |title=Electrical Pod |accessdate=2007-12-03 |publisher=Rolls Royce Marine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020171710/http://www.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsion/electrical_pod/default.jsp |archivedate=20 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rolls-royce.com/marine/products/propulsors/podded/index.jsp |title=Azimuthing electrical podded propulsor |publisher=Rolls-Royce |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> each with one forward-facing low-vibration [[propeller]] with separately bolted blades. The forward pair of thrusters is fixed, but the aft pair can [[azimuth thruster|swivel]] through 360\u00b0, removing the need for a [[rudder]].<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/> ''Queen Mary 2'' is the first quadruple-propeller passenger ship completed since the [[SS France (1961)|SS ''France'']] in 1961.<ref>{{cite book |title=Enso-Gutzeit Oy laivanvarustajana: Oy Finnlines Ltd ja Merivienti Oy 1947\u20131982 |last=Karonen |first=Petri |year=1992 |publisher=Enso-Gutzeit |location=Imatra |isbn=952-9690-00-2 |pages=106\u2013109 |url= |language=Finnish }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' carries eight spare blades on the foredeck, immediately forward of the bridge screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beyondships.com/QM2-art-Watling.html|title=What makes QM2 go?}}</ref>  In addition to the primary thrusters, the ship is also fitted with three [[manoeuvring thruster|bow thrusters]], with a power output of 3.2&nbsp;MW each. These allow the ship to turn in its own length while in port, to conduct more complex docking manoeuvres.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n[[File:QM2-propeller-spares.jpg|thumb|Three of the eight spare propeller blades mounted on the foredeck]]\nUnusually, ''Queen Mary 2'''s gas turbines are not housed along with her diesels in the [[engine room]] deep in her hull, but instead are in a soundproofed enclosure directly beneath the funnel. This arrangement allowed the vessel's designers to supply the oxygen-hungry turbines with air intakes without having to run air ducts the height of the ship, which would have wasted valuable interior space.<ref name=\"Queen Mary 2 Technical\"/>\n\n===Navigation===\n''Queen Mary 2'' has a fully integrated bridge system designed by British firm [[Kelvin Hughes]], which controls the ship's navigation systems, radar, dynamic positioning system, and engine monitoring system. Kelvin Hughes supplied many of the ship's components, including the [[Electronic Chart Display and Information System]] (ECDIS) and eight multifunction display units.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/200108/content/kelvin-hughes-bridge-209053 |title=Kelvin Hughes Bridge Chosen For ''Queen Mary 2'' |magazine=Maritime Reporter and Engineering News |date=August 2001 |page=45 |publisher=New Wave Media}}</ref>\n\n===Water supply===\nFresh water aboard ''Queen Mary 2'' is supplied by three seawater [[desalination]] plants. The plants, each with a capacity of {{convert|630000|L|USgal}} per day, use [[Multiple-effect distillation|multiple effect]] plate (MEP) distillation technology. The plants' energy is supplied primarily by steam and cooling water from the ship's gas turbines and diesel engines, or if needed by steam from the ship's two oil-fired boilers. The traditional [[multiple-effect distillation]] technology has been improved for the ship's plant, so that [[Fouling#Micro fouling|scaling]] of plates is reduced, vastly reducing maintenance required. The desalinated water has a very low salt content of less than five parts per million. Average total water production is {{convert|1100000|L|USgal}} per day with a capacity of {{convert|1890000|L|USgal}} so that there is ample spare capacity. The ship could easily be supplied by only two of the three plants.<ref name=\"Alstom\">{{cite book | title= ''Queen Mary 2'': The Genesis of a Queen |publisher=Alstom Chantiers de l'Atlantique, A Publication of the Naval Architect | year = 2004 | pages = 50\u201355}}</ref> Potable water tanks have a capacity of {{convert|3830000|L|USgal}}, enough for more than three days of supply.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\">Cunard. RMS Queen Mary 2 Technical Specification. Flyer made available to passengers of the ''Queen Mary 2''.</ref> If the engines are running on low load (when the ship is running at a slow speed) the engine jacket cooling water temperature is insufficient to heat the seawater to run the desalination plants. In that case steam from oil-fired boilers is used to heat the sea water. This is uneconomical as generating steam is expensive. It may be cheaper, therefore, to buy water in a particular port than to produce it on board. The seawater intakes are located in the hull of the ship. Concentrated salt solution ([[brine]]) is discharged to the sea closer to the ship's stern together with cooling water from the engines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infotechfrance.com/cgi-local/affichage_signet_secteur.pl?UNI_ID=8&RUB_ID=54&SS_ID=6746&SEC_ID=25 |title=UBIFRANCE Orelis' technology to recycle Queen Mary 2's waste water |date=16 April 2004  |publisher= |accessdate=26 November 2009}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> An additional plant was added during the 2016 refit.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Environmental performance===\n{{See also|Environmental impact of shipping}}\n\nWhen designing ''Queen Mary 2'', the designers considered that tighter environmental regulations would be implemented while the ship was in service, such as energy efficiency, the reuse of treated wastewater for non-potable uses and zero discharge of solid waste into the sea.<ref name=\"professional mariner\"/><ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/>\n\nAccording to Cunard, the ship exceeds some requirements of the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution From Ships ([[MARPOL 73/78]]) of the [[International Maritime Organization]]. It discharges waste into the sea only in areas more than {{convert|12|nmi|mi|abbr=on}} from any coast, even though MARPOL allows discharge of treated organic waste and treated bilge water closer to the shore. Discharges of potentially harmful substances, in particular the residual oil content of treated bilge water and air emissions, are monitored regularly to ensure compliance with environmental standards.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/> In areas where air pollution from [[sulfur dioxide]], which causes [[acid rain]], is a concern, the ship switches to low-sulfur fuel to minimise air pollution.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[carbon offset]] company [[Climate Care]], passenger ships release more carbon dioxide into the atmosphere per passenger mile than long haul flights. Cunard attempted to reduce the [[carbon footprint]] of ''Queen Mary 2'' by improving engine efficiency and reducing friction while the ship is in motion. In November 2008, the ship was given a refit in [[Hamburg]], part of which involved the repainting of the hull in paint which is designed to reduce drag and improve fuel economy.<ref name=\"QM2tecspec\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2006/dec/20/cruises.green |title=Is cruising any greener than flying? |date=20 December 2006 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref> According to [[Blohm+Voss]], her 2016 refit included the installation of \"scrubbers\" and exhaust gas filters to reduce emissions.<ref>{{cite press release|last=Brasse|first=Michael|date=23 May 2016|title=Master refit: The Queen Mary 2 docks at Blohm+Voss on May 27, 2016|url=http://www.blohmvoss.com/var/blohmvoss/storage/original/application/ea05ca9e3bab8c78463d07ae6006ba57.pdf|location=Hamburg, DE|publisher=Blohm+Voss GmbH|access-date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Service history==\n<!-- IMAGES IN THIS SECTION: Please do not add unnecessary images here - images should only be used to illustrate the text better; this is not a gallery. If you wish to add an image, please consider bringing it up on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n[[File:RMS Queen Mary 2 in san francisco bay.jpg|thumb|left|''Queen Mary 2 ''in [[San Francisco Bay]] in 2007]]\nOn 12 January 2004 ''Queen Mary 2'' set sail on her [[maiden voyage]] from [[Southampton]], [[England]], to [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], in the United States, carrying 2,620 passengers. She was under the command of captain Ronald Warwick, who had previously commanded ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. Warwick is the son of William (Bill) Warwick, who had also been a senior Cunard officer and the first captain of ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. The ship returned to Southampton late from her maiden voyage after bow doors covering the thrusters failed to shut in Portugal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/passengers-threaten-mutiny-on-crippled-queen-mary-2-340386.html |title=Passengers threaten mutiny on crippled 'Queen Mary 2' |author=Elaine Barker |date=23 January 2006 |work=The Independent |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] ''Queen Mary 2'' sailed to [[Athens]] and docked at [[Piraeus]] for two weeks for use as a floating hotel, serving the then Prime Minister of the United Kingdom [[Tony Blair]] and his wife [[Cherie Blair|Cherie]], French President [[Jacques Chirac]], then United States President [[George W. Bush]], and the United States Olympic men's basketball team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=549&article_id=2619 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041001102749/http://www.nqsouthern.com/digitalpublication/digitalpublications/index.cfm?dpid=89&section_id=549&article_id=2619 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2004-10-01 |title=''Queen Mary 2'' will be floating fortress |publisher=Nqsouthern.com |accessdate=2011-06-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-08-16/sports/18275842_1_olympics-queen-mary-athens |last=Smith |first=Tim |title=Watch out aboard Queen Mary because ship is sinking |work=NY Daily News |date=2004-08-16 |accessdate=2011-06-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527150820/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-08-16/sports/18275842_1_olympics-queen-mary-athens |archive-date=27 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to Cunard, ''Queen Mary 2'''s passengers have also included jazz musician [[Dave Brubeck]] and singers [[Rod Stewart]], [[Carly Simon]], and [[James Taylor]].<ref>[http://www.cunard.com/cunard-experience/media-centre/stars-aboard/queen-mary-2/ Stars on board Queen Mary 2]</ref>\n\nOne 2005 transatlantic crossing saw ''Queen Mary 2'' carrying, in a locked steamer trunk, the first United States copy of [[J. K. Rowling]]'s book ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', autographed by the author. In a promotional press release for the event, Cunard said that this marked the first time a book had been transported to its international launch aboard an ocean liner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5160&Page=3 |title=World's most famous ocean liner carries first J.K. Rowling-signed US copy of ''Harry Potter and the Half Blood Prince'' |date=7 November 2005 |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210084553/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=5160&Page=3 |archivedate=10 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006 ''Queen Mary 2'' embarked on a circumnavigation of South America. Upon departure from Fort Lauderdale, one of her [[azimuth thruster|propeller pod]]s was damaged when it struck a channel wall, forcing the ship to sail at a reduced speed, which resulted in Commodore Warwick's decision to skip several calls on its voyage to [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Many of her passengers threatened to stage a [[sit-in]] protest because of the missed calls, before Cunard offered to refund the voyage costs. ''Queen Mary 2'' continued to operate at a reduced service speed and several itinerary changes were necessary until repairs had been completed after the ship returned to Europe in June, where ''Queen Mary 2'' paid a visit to dry dock and the damaged propeller pod was unseated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1509030/Cunard-foils-QM2-mutiny-with-full-refund-offer.html |title=Cunard foils QM2 mutiny with full refund offer |author1=Andrew Downe |author2=Amy Iggulden |date=28 Jan 2006|work=The Telegraph |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> In November, ''Queen Mary 2'' was drydocked once more at the [[Blohm+Voss]] yard in [[Hamburg]] (drydock [[Elbe 17]]) for the reinstallation of the repaired propeller pod. At the same time, sprinkler systems were installed in all of the vessel's balconies to comply with new safety regulations which had come into effect since the MS ''[[Star Princess (2001)|Star Princess]]'' fire. Additionally, both bridge wings were extended by two metres to improve visibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blohmvoss-repair.com/pdf/buv_rep_allg_in.pdf|title=Blohmvoss Repair Schedule-2006|publisher=Blohmvoss|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708073658/http://www.blohmvoss-repair.com/pdf/buv_rep_allg_in.pdf|archivedate=8 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Mary II at Liverpool 1.jpg|thumb|left|''Queen Mary 2'' at [[Pier Head]], [[Liverpool]], England during a 2009 visit]]\n\nAfter completing the journey around South America, on 23 February 2006, ''Queen Mary 2'' met her namesake, the original {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, which is permanently docked at [[Long Beach, California]]. Escorted by a flotilla of smaller ships, the two ''Queens'' exchanged a \"whistle salute\" which was heard throughout the city of Long Beach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cruiseline.co.uk/qm2-cruises/p-id/cruise-news/queen-mary-2-meets-namesake-queen-mary-on-february-22-marking-a-cunard-milestone/ |title=Queen Mary 2 Meets Namesake Queen Mary on February 22 Marking a Cunard Milestone |date=12 January 2006 |publisher=The Cruise Line Ltd. |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911094454/http://www.cruiseline.co.uk/qm2-cruises/p-id/cruise-news/queen-mary-2-meets-namesake-queen-mary-on-february-22-marking-a-cunard-milestone/ |archivedate=11 September 2009 }}</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' met the other serving Cunard liners {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' on 13 January 2008 near the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City harbour, with a celebratory fireworks display; ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' and ''Queen Victoria'' made a tandem crossing of the Atlantic for the meeting. This marked the first time three Cunard ''Queens'' have been present in the same location. Cunard stated this would be the last time these three ships would ever meet,<ref name=\"cunard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.com/rendezvous |title=Royal Rendezvous : The Luxury Cruise Ships of Cunard : Cunard Cruise Line |publisher=Cunard |date=2011-03-03 |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> due to ''Queen Elizabeth 2'''s impending retirement from service in late 2008.<ref name=\"Cunard Press Release\">{{cite web|url= http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=6656&Active=News | publisher=Cunard Line|title= QE2 to leave Cunard fleet and be sold to Dubai World to begin a new life at the palm |year=2007|accessdate=2007-06-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706160214/http://www.cunard.com/AboutCunard/NewsReleases.asp?Cat=&View=ViewArticle&Mode=News&ContentID=6656&Active=News <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=2007-07-06}}</ref> However this would prove not to be the case, as the three ''Queens'' met in Southampton on 22 April 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/7361808.stm  |title=Royal gathering of sea 'Queens' |author=Eleanor Williams |date=22 April 2008  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hampshire/7360081.stm  |title=Three 'Queens' in final meeting |date=22 April 2008  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-27}}[]</ref> ''Queen Mary 2'' rendezvoused with ''Queen Elizabeth 2''  in Dubai on Saturday 21 March 2009, after the latter ship's retirement,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chriscunard.com/qe2/qe2-history/#retirement |title=QE2 Retirement |publisher=chriscunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref> while both ships were berthed at [[Port Rashid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chriscunard.com/qe2/qe2-dubai/ |title=QE2 and QM2 in Dubai |publisher=Chriscunard.com |date=2009-03-21 |accessdate=2019-07-11 }}</ref> With the withdrawal of ''Queen Elizabeth 2'' from Cunard's fleet and its docking in Dubai, ''Queen Mary 2'' became the only ocean liner left in active passenger service.\n\nOn 3 August 2007 three men were stopped by police while escorting and piloting a replica of the [[Turtle (submersible)|first American combat submarine]] within {{convert|200|ft}} of ''Queen Mary 2'', which was docked at the cruise ship terminal in [[Red Hook, Brooklyn]]. The replica was created by New York artist [[Duke Riley|Philip \"Duke\" Riley]] and two out-of-town residents, one of whom claimed to be a descendant of [[David Bushnell]], who had invented it. The [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] issued Riley a citation for having an unsafe vessel, and for violating the security zone around ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref>[[#QM2|Makeshift submarine found in East River]]</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://nymag.com/arts/books/features/robert-sullivan-my-american-revolution-2012-9/|title=Permanent Revolution|magazine=New York magazine|date=10 Sep 2012}}</ref>\nOn 19 October 2011, ''Queen Mary 2'' had her registry changed to [[Hamilton, Bermuda]], from her previous home port of Southampton, to allow the ship to host on-board weddings. This marked the first time in its 171-year history that Cunard has not had a ship registered within the UK.<ref>[http://www.cruisecritic.com/news/news.cfm?ID=4634 It's Official: Cunard Re-flags Cruise Ships in Bermuda, Launches Weddings at Sea], cruisecritic.com, 19 October 2011</ref> Bermuda is a member of the [[Red Ensign Group]] and the ship continues to fly the undefaced Red Ensign rather than the Bermuda Red Ensign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bermudashipping.bm/useful-information/faqs |title=FAQs \u2013 Bermuda Shipping and Maritime Registry|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===World cruises===\n[[File:qm2 sydney.jpg|thumb|400px|''Queen Mary 2'' in [[Sydney]], 20 February 2007]]\nOn 10 January 2007, ''Queen Mary 2'' started her first world cruise, circumnavigating the globe in 81 days. On 20 February, she met her fleet-mate, ''Queen Elizabeth 2'', also on her 2007 world cruise, in [[Sydney]] harbour.<!-- http://www.cunard.com/CruiseItinerary.asp?cruiseid=2802&LeftNav=Planner&Active=&Sub=&OB=&Region= No longer useful--> <!--http://www.cunard.com/CruiseItinerary.asp?cruiseid=2803&LeftNav=Planner&Active=&Sub=&OB=&Region= No longer useful--><ref>{{cite news|title=QM2 sails into Sydney|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/travel/qm2sailsintosydney/2007/02/20/1171733718604.html|accessdate=5 October 2013|newspaper=The Age Company Ltd.|date=20 February 2007}}</ref> This is the first time two Cunard ''Queens'' had been together in Sydney since the original ''Queen Mary'' and ''Queen Elizabeth'' served as troop ships in 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatoceanliners.net/queenelizabeth.html |title=''Queen Elizabeth'' 1940\u20131973 |publisher=The Great Ocean Liners |accessdate=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213153036/http://www.greatoceanliners.net/queenelizabeth.html |archivedate=13 February 2009 }}</ref> Despite the early arrival time of 5:42&nbsp;am, the ''Queen Mary 2'''s presence attracted so many viewers that the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] and [[Anzac Bridge]] were blocked.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/sorry-sydney-for-ship-shocker/2007/02/21/1171733803476.html |title=Sydney in meltdown as hordes crowd to see giant ships |author1=David Braithwaite |author2=Andrew Clennell |author3=Deborah Snow |date=21 February 2007|work=Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=2009-11-26}}</ref> With 1,600 passengers leaving the ships in Sydney, Cunard estimated the stopovers injected more than $3&nbsp;million into the local economy.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/travel/super-ships-choke-city/2007/02/20/1171733718091.html Super ships choke city] ''Sydney Morning Herald'' 20 February 2007 Retrieved 11 December 2009</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2012, the ship embarked on a three-month world cruise from Southampton, travelling south and then east around Africa, a first ever circumnavigation of Australia, to Japan, then back to Southampton along the south coastline of Eurasia and through the Suez Canal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seascanner.com/reise.php?reise=32316|title=World Cruise Cruise with RMS Queen Mary 2 on 10/01/2012 (M203)|work=seascanner.com}}</ref>\n\n===Anniversary voyage===\nIn October 2009, ''Queen Mary 2'''s fifth year in service was celebrated with an 8-night voyage around the British Isles. The voyage included maiden visits to [[Greenock]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8314297.stm |title=Huge cruise liner visiting city (Greenock) |date=19 October 2009  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref> and [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/8315670.stm |title=Town welcomes huge cruise liner (Liverpool) |date=20 October 2009  |work=BBC News |accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref>\n\n===The Boston Cup===\nCarried aboard ''Queen Mary 2'' is the Boston Cup. Sometimes referred to as ''The Britannia Cup'', this artifact was created for Sir [[Samuel Cunard]] in [[Boston]], United States, to commemorate the arrival of his first vessel {{RMS|Britannia}}.<ref name=chrisboston>{{cite web |url=https://www.chriscunard.com/history-fleet/the-boston-cup/ |title=The Boston Cup |work=Chris' Cunard Page |accessdate=2010-02-16 }}</ref> Cunard had selected Boston as the American port for his Atlantic service, which resulted in a strong connection between Boston and the Cunard Line.<ref>{{cite book |title=Queen May 2:The Greatest Ocean Liner of our Time |last=Maxtone-Graham |first=John |authorlink=John Maxtone-Graham |year=2004 |publisher=Bulfinch Press |location= |isbn= 0-8212-2885-4|pages=46\u201349 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> It is believed that the cup was presented to Sir Samuel Cunard sometime in 1840, but for much of its life it was missing. It was discovered in an antique shop in 1967 and returned to Cunard, where it was placed aboard ''Queen Elizabeth 2''. In 2004, when ''Queen Mary 2'' became the flagship, the Boston Cup was placed aboard ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref name=chrisboston /> It is in a glass case, aft of the Chart Room lounge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wearecunard.com/2009/07/cunard-celebrates-a-special-anniversary/ |title=Cunard Celebrates a Special Anniversary |publisher=Wearecunard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-27}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007 the [[National Geographic Channel]] broadcast an episode of the documentary series ''[[Megastructures]]'' about ''Queen Mary 2''.<ref>[http://www.natgeochannel.co.uk/programmes/megastructures/schedule Megastructures: List of Episodes] ''National Geographic Channel UK'' Retrieved 12 December 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406171409/http://www.natgeochannel.co.uk/programmes/megastructures/schedule |date=6 April 2009 }}</ref> The vessel also featured in the pilot episode of the documentary TV series ''[[Mighty Ships]]''.\n\n===Propulsion failures===\nThe propulsor pods fitted to ''Queen Mary 2'' have been prone to failure, attributed to the motors' thrust bearings, which continued to show a tendency to fail even after numerous attempts at redesign. In January 2009, Carnival, through its Cunard division, sued Rolls-Royce in the United States. The line alleged that the Mermaid pod propulsion systems fitted to ''Queen Mary 2'' were inherently defective in design, and that Rolls-Royce knew about the design deficiencies and deliberately conspired to mislead, deceive and defraud in the course of winning the contract.<ref name=\"fail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ebearing.com/news2009/011601.htm |title=Specifications:Carnival Sues Rolls-Royce Over Queen Mary... |accessdate=2011-01-19 |date=2009-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710165803/http://www.ebearing.com/news2009/011601.htm |archive-date=10 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In January 2011, the court awarded Carnival US$24&nbsp;million (approximately UK\u00a315&nbsp;million at the time of verdict).<ref name=\"fail2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldsaltblog.com/2011/01/08/the-tale-of-the-mermaid-pods-carnival-awarded-24-million-in-lawsuit-with-rolls-royce/ |title=The Tale of the Mermaid Pods |accessdate=2011-01-19 |date=2009-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Cunard Royal Rendezvous===\nTwo years after the first Cunard Royal Rendezvous on the same date ''Queen Mary 2'' met up with {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and the then brand-new {{MS|Queen Elizabeth}} for another Royal Rendezvous in New York City on 13 January 2011. {{MS|Queen Victoria|3=2}} and {{MS|Queen Elizabeth|3=2}} made a tandem crossing of the Atlantic for the event. All three ships met in front of the statue of Liberty at 6:45&nbsp;pm for [[Fireworks by Grucci|Grucci]] fireworks. The Empire State Building was lit up in red to mark the event.<ref name=\"cunard1\"/>\n\nOn 5 June 2012, the three Queens met again, but this time in [[Southampton]] to celebrate the [[Diamond jubilee]] of [[Queen regnant|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/5207-3711-cunard-line-announces-2012-2013-deployment.html |title=Cunard Line Announces 2012\u20132013 Deployment \u2013 Cruise Industry News &#124; Cruise News |publisher=Cruise Industry News |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Atlantic rowing===\n''Queen Mary 2'' has rendezvoused with [[ocean rowing]] teams in the middle of the Atlantic.  On 30 July 2010 she met up with ''Artemis Investments'', whose rowing crew were [[Don Lennox (rower)|Don Lennox]], [[Livar Nysted]], [[Ray Carroll]], [[Leven Brown]].  Carroll had been a former engineer and was patched through via [[marine VHF radio]] and ''Queen Mary 2's'' [[public address system]] to speak to the captain and crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://maritimematters.com/2010/07/qm2s-mid-atlantic-rendezvous/|title=QM2's Mid-Atlantic Rendezvous|work=Maritime Matters|date=30 July 2010|first=Martin|last=Cox|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/29368|title=World record holder Carroll returns to home soil|work=Galway Advertiser|date=5 August 2010|first=Linley|last=Mackenzie|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/all-oar-nothing-how-four-men-conquered-the-atlantic-1-1368113|title=All oar nothing: How four men conquered the Atlantic|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=30 July 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> On 26 September 2013 ''Queen Mary 2'' resupplied solo-rower Myl\u00e8ne Paquette and her vessel ''Hermel'' with a replacement [[satellite phone]], [[drogue]] anchor and groceries. ''Queen Mary 2'' changed her course by 20 degrees and only added 14 miles to the overall distance of the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2433659|title=Cruise ship to the rescue! Queen Mary 2 delivers supplies to solo woman rower|first=Sarah|last=Gordon|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=26 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mylenepaquette.com/en/to-the-captain-of-the-queen-mary-2-and-his-wife/|title=Letter to the Captain of the Queen Mary 2 and his wife|first=Myl\u00e8ne|last=Paquette|date=27 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005031803/http://www.mylenepaquette.com/en/to-the-captain-of-the-queen-mary-2-and-his-wife/|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24290017|title=Queen Mary 2 comes to aid of Canadian rower Mylene Paquette|work=BBC News Online|date=26 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shipmonk.co.uk/2013/09/29/i-want-to-sail-the-atlantic-single-handed-says-queen-mary-2-captain-after-helping-lone-rower/|title=I want to sail the Atlantic single-handed, says ''Queen Mary 2'' captain after helping lone rower|first=Dave|last=Monk|accessdate=29 September 2013|quote=We made a 20-degree alteration to the south and it only added fourteen miles to our overall distance.|work=Shipmonk}}</ref>\n\n===Engine fire===\nA small fire broke out in the gas turbine engine room (located high on the ship behind the Queen Mary 2 sign<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondships.com/QM2-art-Watling.html|title=Queen Mary 2 \u2013 Interview with Chief Engineer Brian Watling|work=beyondships.com}}</ref>) on the evening of 5 October 2011. The fire was started in one of the ship's gas turbines. No injuries were reported, and crew on board the ship safely extinguished the fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.usatoday.com/cruises/post/2011/10/queen-mary-2-fire/551219/1|title=Travel News, Tips, and Guides - USATODAY.com|work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n===Plant incident===\nOn 23 September 2010, an incident occurred in ''Queen Mary 2'''s aft [[Power conditioner|harmonic filter]] room. This resulted in the shutdown of all four propulsion motors and a loss of electrical power throughout the ship. Within an hour, the ship's main generators were restarted and the ship was able to resume passage. Later investigations found that an explosion was caused by electrical arcing within the aft harmonic filter igniting leaked dielectric fluid vapour.<ref>[http://www.maib.gov.uk/publications/investigation_reports/2011/qm2.cfm Report on the investigation of the catastrophic failure of a capacitor in the aft harmonic filter room on board RMS Queen Mary 2 while approaching Barcelona ], Marine Accident Investigation Branch. 2010-09-23.</ref>\n\n===200th transatlantic voyage===\nOn 6 July 2013 ''Queen Mary 2'' departed New York en route to Southampton on her 200th transatlantic voyage. On board speakers were [[Stephen Payne (naval architect)|Stephen Payne OBE]]\u2014the ship's designer\u2014and presenter and newsreader [[Nick Owen]], who presented talks about the ship's design.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Mary 2 Celebrates 200th Transatlantic Crossing |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/88530/queen-mary-2-celebrates-200th-transatlantic-crossing/ |publisher=World Maritime News |date=9 July 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===10th birthday celebrations===\n[[File:Red ensign QM2 1July2014.JPG|thumb|Undefaced [[Red Ensign]] flown by RMS ''Queen Mary 2'' in New York, July 2014.]]\nOn 6 May 2014, all three Queens met up for the first time in [[Lisbon]], Portugal. The three ships sailed abreast of each other from Lisbon to Southampton. On 9 May 2014 ''Queen Elizabeth'' and ''Queen Victoria'' led ''Queen Mary 2'' up the Southampton channel where they docked in formation at the QEII terminal and performed a birthday salute to ''Queen Mary 2''.  The anniversary included a tour of the ship by His Royal Highness The Duke of Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite news|title=Back at the helm: Duke of Edinburgh visits the Bridge (and even keeps smiling while touring the ship's LAUNDRY) to celebrate Queen Mary 2's 10th anniversary|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2624078/Cunards-Queen-Mary-2-celebrates-10th-anniversary-Duke-Edinburgh.html|accessdate=7 July 2014|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cunard 175th anniversary===\nOn 25 May 2015, all three Queens met, once again, at [[Liverpool]], in order to celebrate the 175th anniversary of the shipping line. After arriving at Liverpool the previous day, ''Queen Mary 2'' made a brief excursion to the entrance of the [[River Mersey]] to welcome her two fleetmates into port in the early afternoon. The three Cunarders then sailed, in formation, towards Liverpool. The ships spent several hours together, before the departure of ''Queen Mary 2'' to [[Saint Peter Port]], [[Guernsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32872777|title=Cunard shipping marks 175 years in Liverpool|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/three-queens-liverpool-2015-key-9094540|title=Three Queens Liverpool 2015: Key times for all the weekend events |work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cunard.co.uk/campaigns/anniversary-cruises/175-celebration/|title=Anniversary cruises 2015|publisher=Cunard|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2015, ''Queen Mary 2'' began a ''175th Anniversary Crossing'' in Southampton. She sailed first to Liverpool, leaving that city after a fireworks display on 4 July, the actual anniversary date of Cunard's first transatlantic voyage. ''Queen Mary 2'' followed the route of the original ship ''Britannia'', calling first at Halifax, Nova Scotia. After a day there, she headed first upriver into the harbor, using her bow thrusters and swivel-pod motors to negotiate the tight turnaround to come back down close to the cityfront. A 21-gun salute and bagpipe band honored the ship.\n\nFrom Halifax, the ship sailed to Boston and was there for a full day at the cruise terminal (Boston was the terminus of the original crossing in 1840). In the evening the ship backed out into [[Boston Harbor]], where a fireworks display was presented before ''Queen Mary 2'' sailed away.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. festivities set as Queen Mary 2 celebrates 175 years of Cunard crossings |url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-trb-new-york-cunard-light-show-20150706-story.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=7 July 2015}}</ref> After a night and day at sea, the vessel entered New York Harbor early the morning of 14 July and docked at the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal. Later in the evening the vessel sailed to the lower harbor, between the Statue of Liberty and the Battery, for the ''Forever Cunard Queen Mary 2 Light Show.''<ref>{{cite web|title=FORever cunard queen mary 2 light show|url=http://www.quantumtheatricalservices.com/queen-mary-2-light-show|publisher=Quantum Theatricals|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20161001 Queen Mary Aerial 2.jpg|thumb|left|240px|The RMS Queen Mary 2 visiting [[Sydney Harbour (Nova Scotia)|Sydney Harbour]], [[Cape Breton Island]] on October 1st, 2016.]]\n=== 2016 refit ===\nIn June 2016, ''Queen Mary 2'' was put through a $132&nbsp;million/\u00a390&nbsp;million renovation at [[Blohm+Voss]] over 25 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Machan |first1=Teresa |title=First look at Cunard's new-look RMS Queen Mary 2 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/articles/first-look-at-cunards-new-look-rms-queen-mary-2/ |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sloan |first1=Gene |title=Peek inside the last great ocean liners, from Queen Mary to the SS United States |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2018/09/04/queen-mary-ss-united-states-iconic-ocean-liners/764185002/ |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=USA Today |language=en}}</ref> Major changes include the addition of fifteen single occupancy staterooms, thirty additional balcony staterooms, and ten more animal cages for an enlarged kennels.<ref name=\"refit\">{{cite press release | url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cunard-flagship-queen-mary-2-151500362.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130015047/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cunard-flagship-queen-mary-2-151500362.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=30 January 2016 | title=Cunard flagship Queen Mary 2 to undergo major refurbishment in early summer 2016, befitting the world's most iconic ocean liner | publisher=CNW Group | date=15 July 2015 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Atlantic rescue===\nOn 10 June 2017, Queen Mary 2, commanded by Captain Christopher Wells, came to the rescue of a stranded solo yachtsman, 73-year-old Mervyn Wheatley, whose craft ''Tamarind'' had been disabled by a strong storm while participating in the [[Observer Single-handed Trans-Atlantic Race]]. British and Canadian coastguards coordinated this long-range rescue after they detected Tamarind's distress beacon. ''Queen Mary 2'' was guided to Wheatley's position by a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] aircraft.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jun/11/mervyn-wheatley-73-queen-mary-2-liner-rescue-north-atlantic-storm The Guardian 11 June 2017]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Plowman-Aust Cruise Ships}}\n*{{Saunders-Giants of the Seas}}\n*{{Smith-Cruise Ships-2010}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.cunard.com/en-us/cruise-ships/queen-mary-2/9 Cunard: ''Queen Mary 2'', Official website]\n* [http://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/310627000 Location tracking] at MarineTraffic\n* [http://chriscunard.com/qm2/ ''Queen Mary 2'' (QM2) on Chris' Cunard Page]\n* [http://www.galutschek.at/ships/qm2/ Video Clips of QM2 at Newport and Boston]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/cruise-ships/14805/Cunard-Queen-Mary-2.html ''\"Queen Mary 2\"'']&nbsp;\u2014\u2013 review by Douglas Ward in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', London.\n\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{Cunard ships}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen Mary 2}}\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Chantiers de l'Atlantique]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Cunard Line]]\n[[Category:2003 ships]]\n[[Category:Passenger ships of Bermuda]]\n", "name_user": "Kablammo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInterior:- misplaced edit summary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Mary_2"}
{"title_page": "Particles of the Kagoshima dialects", "text_new": "The [[grammatical particle]]s ({{lang|ja|\u52a9\u8a5e}} ''joshi'') used in the [[Kagoshima dialect]]s of Japanese have many features in common with those of other dialects spoken in [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]], with some being unique to the Kagoshima dialects. Like [[japanese particles|standard Japanese particles]], they act as suffixes, adpositions or words immediately following the noun, verb, adjective or phrase that they modify, and are used to indicate the relationship between the various elements of a sentence.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://japanese.about.com/blparticles.htm | title=Japanese Particles | publisher=About.com | year=2009 | accessdate=2009-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timwerx.net/language/particles.htm | title=Japanese Particles | first=Tim R. | last=Matheson | publisher=Tim's Takamatsu | year=2008 | accessdate=2009-10-29}}</ref>\n\nUnlike central Japanese dialects, particles in the Kagoshima dialects are bound [[clitic]]s, as they have the effect of resyllabifying the last word they attach to. So, for example, the standard forms {{lang|ja|\u672c\u3092}} ''hon o'' \"book {{gcl|ACC}}\", {{lang|ja|\u66f8\u304d\u3092}} ''kaki o'' \"writing {{gcl|ACC}}\" and {{lang|ja|\u307e\u308a\u3092}} ''mari o'' \"ball {{gcl|ACC}}\" would be realized as {{IPA|/hoNno/}}, {{IPA|/kakjo/}} and {{IPA|/majo/}} ( \u2190 {{IPA|/ma\u027djo/}}) in most of northern and central Kagoshima, and {{IPA|/hoNnu/}}, {{IPA|/kakju/~/kaku/}} and {{IPA|/maju/}} ( \u2190 {{IPA|/ma\u027dju/}}) in parts of Kagoshima's southern mainland.<ref>Shibatani (1990), p. 210</ref>\n\nResyllabification has also led to the reanalysis of some particles in a few dialects. For instance, the topic particle ''(w)a'' has been completely superseded by the form ''na'' in [[Izumi, Kagoshima|Izumi]],<ref name=\"Izumi\">{{cite web | url=http://sky.geocities.jp/ryohusyokyoryu/izumigo.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202234707/http://sky.geocities.jp/ryohusyokyoryu/izumigo.html | archivedate=2013-12-02 | script-title=ja:\u5317\u85a9\u51fa\u6c34\u8a9e\u3092\u8a71\u3057\u3066\u307f\u3088\u3046\uff01 | language=Japanese |trans-title=Let's learn the Hokusatsu district Izumi dialect! | accessdate=2012-04-22}}</ref> which in most mainland dialects is merely a variant of ''(w)a'' after a moraic nasal.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Resyllabification rules ==\n\nWhen a word is followed by a particle that starts with a vowel (such as the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'', the accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' or the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''), the final syllable of that word will be fused with the particle and be subject to Kagoshima's [[kagoshima dialect#Coalescence|vowel coalescence rules]] as well as other sound changes occurring in the regional dialect. As a simple example, when the word {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308c}} {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}} ''kore'' \"this\" is followed by the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} {{IPA|/a/}}, it becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308a\u3083}} {{IPA|/ko\u027dja/}} ''korya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\". A secondary sound change in Mainland Kagoshima then causes the medial {{IPA|/\u027dj/}} ''ry'' to become {{IPA|/j/}} ''y'', giving the common form {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3084}} {{IPA|/koja/}} ''koya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\".\n\nTwo main exceptions to this rule exist:\n\n# If a word's underlying form ends in a moraic nasal (i.e. {{IPA|/N/}}), an [[Epenthesis|epenthetic]] {{IPA|/n/}} is inserted between the word and the particle. For example, {{lang|ja|\u672c}} {{IPA|/hoN/}} ''hon'' \"book\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u672c\u306f}} {{IPA|/hoNna/}} ''honna'' when fused with the topic particle.\n# If a word's underlying form ends in a long vowel or sequence of vowels, then an epenthetic consonant is sometimes inserted between the word and the topic particle. In the case of topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and the accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'', the epenthetic consonant is {{IPA|/w/}}. In the case of the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', the epenthetic consonant is {{IPA|/n/}}. This rule is not consistently applied across all dialects of Kagoshima.\n\nThe following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the mainland Kagoshima dialects.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in mainland Kagoshima\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n| {{IPA|/koi/}}\n| {{IPA|/koja/}}\n| {{IPA|/kojo/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n|-\n| writing\n| {{IPA|/kaki/}}\n| {{IPA|/kaQ/}}\n| {{IPA|/kakja/}} or {{IPA|/kaka/}}<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/kakjo/}} or {{IPA|/kaku/}}<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/kaki/}}\n|-\n| ball\n| {{IPA|/ma\u027di/}}\n| {{IPA|/mai/}}\n| {{IPA|/maja/}}\n| {{IPA|/majo/}}\n| {{IPA|/ma\u027di/}}\n|-\n| song\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/utao/}}\n| {{IPA|/ute/}}\n|-\n| hitting\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/uQ/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255a/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255o/}}, {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255u/}} or {{IPA|/ut\u0361su/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n|-\n| person<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hita/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hite/}}\n|-\n| study<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoa/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoi/}}\n|-\n| book\n| {{IPA|/hoN/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoN/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNna/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNno/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNni/}}\n|}\n\nThe rules of resyllabification differ only slightly in peripheral areas. The following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the Sato dialect of the [[Koshikijima Islands]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in the Sato village of Koshikijima<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\">{{cite web | first=Kuroki | last=Kunihiko | title=\u4e0a\u7511\u5cf6\u8af8\u65b9\u8a00\u306e(\u5f62\u614b) \u97f3\u97fb\u985e\u578b\u8ad6 | url=http://hotarugaikegengokenkyuuzyo.web.fc2.com/Nihongo_Gakkai_2013_06_02.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref name=\"SatoGrammar\">{{cite web | first1=Mori | last1=Yuta | first2=Hiratsuka | last2=Yusuke | first3=Kuroki | last3=Kunihiko | title=\u7511\u5cf6\u91cc\u65b9\u8a00\u8a18\u8ff0\u6587\u6cd5\u66f8 | trans-title=Descriptive grammar of the Sato dialect of Koshikijima | url=https://www.academia.edu/11954027/%E7%94%91%E5%B3%B6%E9%87%8C%E6%96%B9%E8%A8%80%E8%A8%98%E8%BF%B0%E6%96%87%E6%B3%95%E6%9B%B8 | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n| {{IPA|/koi/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027daa/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027dee/}}\n|-\n| thing\n| {{IPA|/mono/}}\n| {{IPA|/mono/}}\n| {{IPA|/monaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/monee/}}\n|-\n| song\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/utaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/utjaa/}}\n|-\n| hitting\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255aa/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255ii/}}\n|-\n| ticket\n| {{IPA|/\u0278uda/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278uda/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278udaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278udjaa/}}\n|-\n| river\n| {{IPA|/kawa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawjaa/}}\n|-\n| lye\n| {{IPA|/aaku/}}\n| {{IPA|/aaku/}}\n| {{IPA|/aakaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/aakii/}}\n|}\n\n* Note: The accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'') is not listed above because the Sato dialect replaced it with the particle {{lang|ja|\u3070}} ''ba''. For example, the accusative form of ''koi'' \"this\" is simply ''koi ba''.<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n\nAnd the following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the [[Tanegashima]] dialects.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in Tanegashima<ref name=\"NozomiKodama\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama | title=\u7a2e\u5b50\u5cf6\u4e8c\u578b\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u306e\u5883\u754c\u7279\u5fb4\uff0d\u81ea\u767a\u8ac7\u8a71\u97f3\u58f0\u8cc7\u6599\u306e\u5206\u6790 | trans-title=On the Edge Feature of Tanegashima Two-pattern Accent: Prosodic Analysis based on Corpora of Spontaneous Speech | url=http://lg.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/13-02.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/kore/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/kora/}} or {{IPA|/korja/}}\n| {{IPA|/korjo/}}\n| \n|-\n| person\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hitaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/hitoo/}}\n| \n|-\n| sugar\n| {{IPA|/satoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/satoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/satoowa/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| now\n| {{IPA|/ima/}}\n| {{IPA|/ima/}}\n| {{IPA|/imoo/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| time\n| {{IPA|/toki/}}\n| {{IPA|/toki/}}\n| {{IPA|/tokjaa/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| candy\n| {{IPA|/ame/}}\n| {{IPA|/ame/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/ameo/}}\n| \n|-\n| oil\n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekiju/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekiju/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekijoo/}}\n| \n|-\n| mountain\n| {{IPA|/jama/}}\n| {{IPA|/jamaa/}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA|/jamaai/}}\n|-\n| care\n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iN/}}\n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iN/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iNno/}}\n| \n|}\n\n* Note: Blank entries indicate that examples could not be found or inferred from the source.\n\n=== Historical attestation ===\n\nThe phenomenon of resyllabification (or particle fusion) is first attested for the Kagoshima dialect in the 18th-century works of [[Gonza]], a Japanese castaway from [[Satsuma, Kagoshima|Satsuma]] who was taken to [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia around 1733-1734. Under the supervision of assistant librarian Andrei Bogdanov, Gonza helped produce several reference works on the Japanese language in Russian, including an introductory, a grammar and a dictionary.<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\">{{cite web | first=Nobuko | last=Kibe | title=18\u4e16\u7d00\u85a9\u6469\u306e\u6f02\u6d41\u6c11\u30b4\u30f3\u30b6\u306e\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | trans-title=On the accent of the 18th-century Satsuma drifter Gonza | url=https://db3.ninjal.ac.jp/SJL/getpdf.php?number=1910970840cs | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> These works provide the oldest glimpse into the Kagoshima dialect.\n\nFor the most part, the works of Gonza show that the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' followed the same rules as they do today, fusing with the final syllable of the preceding word and being subject to the same exceptions that exist today. The accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''wo'', however, was independent and shows fusion in only a couple recorded examples.<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"display: inline-table;\"\n|+ Topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Thief || n\u00fasda || {{lang|ja|\u76d7\u4eba\u306f}}<br />''nusuto wa''\n|-\n| Cow, heifer || \u00fasha || {{lang|ja|\u725d\u725b\u306f}}<br />''meushi wa''\n|-\n| Autumn || aky\u00e0|| {{lang|ja|\u79cb\u306f}}<br />''aki wa''\n|-\n| Night || yor\u00e0 || {{lang|ja|\u591c\u306f}}<br />''yoru wa''\n|-\n| I || \u00f3ra || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u306f}}<br />''ore wa''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" /><br />(recorded as ''n'' after a long vowel)\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Country || k\u00fani || {{lang|ja|\u56fd\u306b}}<br />''kuni ni''\n|-\n| Person || ft\u00e8 || {{lang|ja|\u4eba\u306b}}<br />''hito ni''\n|-\n| Garden || n\u00edwe || {{lang|ja|\u5ead\u306b}}<br />''niwa ni''\n|-\n| One generation || \u00edchden || {{lang|ja|\u4e00\u4ee3\u306b}}<br />''ichidai ni''\n|-\n| I || \u00f3re || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u306b}}<br />''ore ni''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''wo''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Write a character || \u0292\u00f3 kak || {{lang|ja|\u5b57\u3092\u66f8\u304f}}<br />''ji o kaku''\n|-\n| What || n\u00e1nyu || {{lang|ja|\u4f55\u3092}}<br />''nani o''\n|-\n| Country || k\u00fan wo || {{lang|ja|\u56fd\u3092}}<br />''kuni o''\n|-\n| Me || \u00f3i wo || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u3092}}<br />''ore o''\n|}\n\n== Syntactic case-marking particles ==\n\n=== Ablative ===\n==== kara ====\nLike standard Japanese, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' and its regional variants {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3042}} ''kaa'' and {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' are used to indicate a time or place from which something begins. In this sense, it can generally be translated to \"from\" in English.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4eca'''\u304b\u3042'''}} (''Ima '''kaa''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|ima{{=}}kaa\n|now{{=}}ABL\n|'From now'}}\n\nUnlike standard Japanese, this particle is not used to mark a reason. Instead, the Kagoshima particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' is used for that purpose. For example, in the standard Japanese sentence {{lang|ja|\u753a'''\u304b\u3089'''\u53d6\u3063\u3066\u304f\u308b\u3082\u306e\u3067\u3059\u304b\u3089}} ''machi '''kara''' totte kuru mono desu '''kara''''' \"'''because''' it was bought '''from''' town\",<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" /> the first instance remains {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' in Kagoshima while the second would become {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'':\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u753a'''\u304b\u3042'''\u53d6\u3063\u304f\u3093\u3082\u3093\u3058\u3083\u3093\u3067}} (''mak'''kaa''' tokkun mon jan de'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|ma\u0294{{=}}kaa to\u0294-ku-n{{=}}mon ja-n{{=}}de\n|town{{=}}ABL take-come-NPST{{=}}NMZ COP{{=}}NPST{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Because it was bought from town'}}\n\nIn a few Kagoshima dialects, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' can be used in two additional ways that are different from standard Japanese.\n\n(1) In the first, it can be used to indicate the mean used to arrive to a situation (such as the mean of transportation), overlapping with the standard particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' \"by\" in this sense. For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8239'''\u304b\u3089'''\u6765\u305f}} (''fune '''kara''' kita'')<ref>{{cite web | title=29 \u8239[\u3067]\uff08\u6765\u305f\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-29.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|fune{{=}}kara k-ita\n|boat{{=}}ABL come-PST\n|'(He) came by boat'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u30d0\u30b9'''\u304b\u3089'''\u884c\u304f\u3067\u3048}} (''basu '''kara''' iku dee'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|basu{{=}}kara ik-u{{=}}dee\n|bus{{=}}ABL go-NPST{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Since (I) go by bus'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' does not replace the other usages of {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' \"by\". For instance, it cannot be used to mark the tool used to achieve an action. So in the sentence \"to write ''with'' a brush\", {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' would be used.<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n\n(2) In the second, it can be used to mark the agent in an [[Passive voice#Adversative passive|adversative-passive]] sentence, replacing the standard particle {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni''. For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u72ac'''\u304b\u3089'''\u3048\u304b\u3051\u3089\u308b\u305f}} (''in '''kara''' ekakeraruta'')<ref>{{cite web | title=27 \u72ac[\u306b]\uff08\u8ffd\u3044\u304b\u3051\u3089\u308c\u305f) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-27.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|in{{=}}kara ekake-raru-ta\n|dog{{=}}ABL chase-PAS-PST\n|'(I) was chased by a dog'}}\n\n=== Accusative ===\n==== o (1) ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' is a case particle that marks the direct object in a sentence. Depending on the word that precedes, it can also be pronounced {{lang|ja|\u3046}} ''u''.\n\nLike the particles {{lang|ja|\u3042}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', when {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject resyllabification. For instance, {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3044}} ''koi'' \"this\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3088}} ''koyo'' \"this={{gcl|ACC}}\".\n\nExample:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u307b\u3093'''\u306e'''\u8aad\u3093}} (''hon'''no''' yon'')\n|hon{{=}}o yo-n\n|book{{=}}ACC read-NPST\n|'(I) read a book.'}}\n\n==== oba and ba ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3092\u3070}} ''oba'' or {{lang|ja|\u3070}} ''ba'' marks a topicalized direct object. This form historically derives from a contraction of the [[accusative case|accusative]] marker ''wo'' and the topic particle ''\u0278a'' (modern day ''wa'').<ref name=\"Shibatani\" /> In several Western Ky\u016bsh\u016b dialects, ''ba'' has completely replaced the particle ''o'' as the accusative marker. However, the use of the particle ''ba'' within the Satsug\u016b dialect is restricted mainly to the Koshikijima Islands<ref name=\"koshikijima\">{{cite web | url=http://www.koshikijima.net/hougen/hougen.html |  title=\u7511\u5cf6\u306e\u65b9\u8a00\uff08\u6587\u4f8b\u96c6\uff09 | publisher=K&I PROJECT | accessdate=2010-01-28}}</ref> and is not as widespread elsewhere. Considered an archaism in Standard Japanese,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tangorin.com/general/woba|title=woba\u3010\u3092\u3070\u3011|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Tangorin.com|accessdate=2009-12-08}}</ref> the form ''oba'', pronounced ''uba'' in Southern Kagoshima, is more frequently used instead.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~hi5k-stu/bbs/bbs0210.htm | author=massangeana | title=\u8a00\u8449\u306e\u4e16\u754c\u30fb\u4f1d\u8a00\u677f\u30002002\u5e7410\u6708: \u3044\u308d\u3044\u308d | date=2002-10-25 | accessdate=2009-12-08}}</ref> In contrast with the particle ''o'', ''oba'' can be described as an emphatic accusative; that is, it places more emphasis on the direct object.\n\nExamples:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u307f\u3063'''\u3092\u3070'''\u98f2\u3093\u3060}} (''mi\u0294 '''oba''' nonda'')\n|mi\u0294{{=}}o{{=}}ba no-nda\n|water{{=}}ACC{{=}}TOP drink-PST\n|'(I) drank water.'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u672c'''\u3070'''\u8aad\u3093}} (''hon '''ba''' yon'')\n|hon{{=}}ba yo-n\n|book{{=}}ACC.TOP read-NPST\n|'(I) read a book.'}}\n\n=== Comparative ===\n==== yokka ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3088\u3063\u304b}} ''yokka''<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> or its variant {{lang|ja|\u3088\u304b}} ''yoka''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is used in place of standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3088\u308a}} ''yori'' and, like it, it has two main functions. The first is that it can be used to indicate the origin of something, akin to \"from\" or \"beginning from\" in English. The second is that it can be used to make comparisons, roughly translating to \"more than\" or \"rather than\". In southern Koshikijima and northern Tanegashima, the variant {{lang|ja|\u3088\u3044\u304b}} ''yoika'' is used, while in northern Koshikijima, the forms {{lang|ja|\u3088\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''yokyaa'' and {{lang|ja|\u3086\u3046\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''yuukyaa'' are observed.<ref>{{cite web | title=31 \u305d\u308c[\u3088\u308a]\uff08\u3042\u306e\u65b9\u304c\u826f\u3044\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-31.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> Etymologically, the particle is considered a contraction of {{lang|ja|\u3088\u308a}} ''yori'' and {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka''.<ref name=\"naiyokka\">{{cite web | title=\u306a\u3044\u3088\u3063\u304b\u30fb\u306a\u3044\u3088\u3063\u3082 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%aa%e3%81%84%e3%82%88%e3%81%a3%e3%81%8b%e3%83%bb%e3%81%aa%e3%81%84%e3%82%88%e3%81%a3%e3%82%82/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55'''\u3088\u3063\u304b'''}} (''nai '''yokka''''')<ref name=\"naiyokka\" />\n|nai{{=}}yokka\n|what{{=}}COMP\n|'More than anything'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u82b1'''\u3088\u3063\u304b'''\u56e3\u5b50}} (''hana '''yokka''' dango'')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" />\n|hana{{=}}yokka dango\n|flower{{=}}COMP dumpling\n|'Dumplings rather than flowers', 'Substance over form'}}\n\n=== Dative and locative ===\n==== i ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and its variant {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni'' can be used to mark a location (like \"in\" or \"at\" in English), indicate a direction (like \"to\" or \"towards\"), mark an indirect object, or mark the agent in a [[Passive voice|passive]] sentence. Its usage is very similar to those of the particles {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni'' \"in/at/to\" and {{lang|ja|\u3078}} ''e'' \"to/towards\" in standard Japanese.\n\nLike the particles {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'', when {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject to vowel coalescence.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304a'''\u308c'''\u8cb8\u305b}} (''Or'''e''' kase'')<ref>{{cite web | title=25 \u304a\u308c[\u306b]\uff08\u8cb8\u305b\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-25.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|ore{{=}}i kas-e\n|1{{=}}DAT lend-IMP\n|'Lend it to me'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u305d'''\u3051'''\u884c\u304b\u3093\u304b}} (''asok'''e''' ikan ka'')\n|asoko{{=}}i ik-an{{=}}ka\n|over_there{{=}}DAT go-NEG{{=}}Q\n|\"How about we go over there\"}}\n\n==== ina ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3044\u306a}} ''ina'' (or {{lang|ja|\u3044\u306b\u3083\u3042}} ''inyaa'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> generally means \"for\", \"in\", \"to\" or \"in order to\". Etymologically, it is a combination of the particles {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' and {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and is cognate with the standard Japanese construction {{lang|ja|\u306b\u306f}} ''ni wa''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u660e\u65e5\u305a'''\u3044\u306a'''}} (''ashita zu'''ina''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\" />\n|ashita{{=}}zui{{=}}ina\n|tomorrow{{=}}until{{=}}DAT.TOP\n|\"By tomorrow\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3053'''\u3051\u306b\u3083\u3042'''\u3059\u3063\u3053\u3081\u306e\u53d7\u304b\u3063\u3068\u3044}} (''kok'''enyaa''' sukkome no ukattoi'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|koko{{=}}inyaa sukkome{{=}}no uka-tte{{=}}o-i\n|here{{=}}DAT.TOP scalpel_sawtail{{=}}NOM float-CONJ{{=}}PROG-INF\n|\"There are Scalpel Sawtail fish floating (in) here\"}}\n\n=== Genitive and nominative ===\nIn [[Old Japanese]], the particles {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' and {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' had overlapping functions as [[genitive]] and [[nominative]] markers, and were ultimately distinguished by their degree of [[politeness]].<ref name=\"Shibatani\">Shibatani (1990), pp. 205-206</ref> The Kagoshima dialects, like other Western [[Japanese dialects#Ky\u016bsh\u016b|Ky\u016bsh\u016b]] dialects and [[Ryukyuan languages|Ryukyuan]] varieties, are notable in that this original distinction is largely maintained, although some regional variation in usage occurs.\n\n==== ga ====\nIn Kagoshima, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' is considered somewhat more derogatory and occurs mainly with a human subject or possessor.<ref>{{cite book | title=Rethinking Japan: Literature, Visual Arts & Linguistics | authors=Adriana Boscaro, Franco Gatti and Massimo Raveri | publisher=Routledge | year=1991 | page=320 | isbn=978-0-904404-78-4}}</ref>.\n\nExamples:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4ffa'''\u304c'''\u5bb6}} (''oi '''ga''' e'')\n|oi{{=}}ga e\n|1{{=}}GEN home\n|'My house', 'my family'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4ffa'''\u304c'''\u3066\u306d\u3052}} (''oi '''ga''' tenege'')<ref>{{cite web | title=13 [\u304a\u308c\u306e]\uff08\u624b\u62ed\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-13.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|oi{{=}}ga tenege\n|1{{=}}GEN handtowel\n|'My handtowel'}}\n\n==== no ====\nIn contrast with the particle {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'', the particle {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' (or {{lang|ja|\u3093}} ''n'') is considered more neutral or polite.<ref name=\"Shibatani\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5148\u751f'''\u306e'''\u3066\u306d\u3052}} (''sense '''no''' tenege'')<ref>{{cite web | title=14 \u5148\u751f[\u306e](\u624b\u62ed) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-14.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|sense{{=}}no tenege\n|teacher{{=}}GEN handtowel\n|'The teacher's handtowel'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' is sometimes reduced to {{lang|ja|\u3093}} ''n''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u673a'''\u3093'''\u4e2d}} (''tsukue'''n''' naka'')\n|tsukue{{=}}n naka\n|desk{{=}}GEN inside\n|'inside the desk'}}\n\n=== Lative ===\n==== see ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305b\u3048}} ''see'' and its many regional variations (e.g. {{lang|ja|\u305b}} ''se'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3044}} ''sai'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3048}} ''sae'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3093}} ''san'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u306d}} ''sane'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3081}} ''same'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3081\u3048}} ''samee'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u307f\u3083\u3042}} ''samyaa'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u30b5\u884c | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7sagyou.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121127/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7sagyou.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=19 \u6771\u306e\u65b9[\u3078]\uff08\u884c\u3051\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-19.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=\u3055\u3044\uff08\u3055\u3048\uff09 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%95%e3%81%84%e3%83%bb%e3%81%95%e3%81%88/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> marks direction. It can roughly be translated as \"in\" or \"to\" in English and is comparable in usage to {{lang|ja|\u3078}} ''e'' in standard Japanese. Etymologically, the particle is said to originate from the expression {{lang|ja|\u69d8\u306b}} ''sama ni'' \"by way of, in the state of\".<ref>{{cite web | title=\u305b\u3047 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%9b%e3%81%87/ | language=ja | access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u6771\u4eac'''\u305b\u3048'''}} (''tokyo '''see''''')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\">{{cite web | title=\u304b\u3054\u3063\u307e\u306e\u8a71 - \u95a2\u6771\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u4eba\u4f1a\u9023\u5408\u4f1a | website=Kagoshima Kenjinkai | url=http://www.kagoshimakenjinkai.ne.jp/kaggoma.html | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama |title=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u77ed\u3044\u9577\u6bcd\u97f3 | trans-title=Phonologically Long Vowels in Kagoshima Japanese | url=http://lg.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/18-03.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n|tokyo{{=}}see\n|Tokyo{{=}}LAT\n|'In/to Tokyo'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u6307\u5bbf'''\u305b\u3048'''\u3001\u884c\u3063\u304d\u305f\u3002}} (''ibusus'''see''', ikkita.'')\n|ibusu\u0294{{=}}see i\u0294{{=}}ki-ta\n|Ibusuki{{=}}LAT go{{=}}come-PST\n|'(I) came back from Ibusuki'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e0b'''\u305b\u3048'''\u884c\u305f\u3002}} (''shita '''see''' ita.'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|shita{{=}}see i-ta\n|down{{=}}LAT go-PST\n|'(I) went down', '(I) went to the bottom'}}\n\n=== Nominalizing ===\n==== to ====\nOther than its standard usages, the particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} is also a nominalizing particle in the Kagoshima dialects. That is, it can be appended to a verb, an adjective or another utterance to transform it into a noun. This usage is similar to how {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' is used in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u305f\u3044\u304c'''\u3068'''}} (''Atai ga '''to''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u30bf\u884c | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7tagyou.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121138/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7tagyou.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|atai{{=}}ga{{=}}to\n|1{{=}}GEN{{=}}NMZ\n|'Mine'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b'''\u3068'''\u3068\u3075\u3068\u304b'''\u3068'''\u3068}} (''komanka '''to''' to futoka '''to''' to'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\" />\n|koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}to futo-ka{{=}}to{{=}}to\n|small-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}COM big-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}COM\n|'The small one and the big one'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305f\u3051\u3048'''\u3068'''\u304c\u826f\u304b}} (''takee '''to''' ga yoka'')<ref name=\"TeruoHirayama\">{{cite web | first=Teruo | last=Hirayama | title=\n\u30c8\u30ab\u30e9\u7fa4\u5cf6\u30fb\u5c4b\u4e45\u5cf6\u30fb\u7a2e\u5b50\u5cf6\u306e\u65b9\u8a00 | trans-title=Dialects of the Tokara Islands, Yakushima and Tanegashima | url=https://db3.ninjal.ac.jp/SJL/getpdf.php?number=0690820960 | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> (Example from Onoaida, Yakushima)\n|taka{{=}}i{{=}}to{{=}}ga yo-ka\n|tall{{=}}ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}NOM good-ADJ\n|'The tall one is good'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} can also be used at the end of declarative sentences to add mild emphasis.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u884c\u3063'''\u3068'''\u3088}} (''It'''to''' yo'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\" />\n|i\u0294{{=}}to{{=}}yo\n|go.NPST{{=}}EMP{{=}}EMP\n|\"I'm going\"}}\n\n==== ta ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305f}} ''ta'' or its variant {{lang|ja|\u305f\u3042}} ''taa'' is a combination of the nominalizing particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} ''to'' and the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a''. It can be combined with a verb or adjective to turn it into a noun, similar to how {{lang|ja|\u3082\u306e\u306f}} ''mono wa'' and {{lang|ja|\u306e\u306f}} ''no wa'' work in standard Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3044\u3051\uff1f\u4e00\u756a\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b'''\u305f'''\u3002}} (''doi ke? ibban komanka '''ta'''.'')\n|doi{{=}}ke? i\u0294.ban koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}a.\n|which{{=}}Q? one.number small-ADJ{{=}}NOM{{=}}TOP.\n|'Which one? The smallest one.'}}\n\n=== Purposive ===\n==== ke (2) ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke''<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\">{{cite web | title=\u898b\u306b(\u884c\u3063\u305f) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-21.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> can be used with verbs in their stem form to indicate purpose or intent. It normally occurs in the construction {{lang|ja|\uff5e\u3051\u884c\u3063}} ''~ ke i\u0294'' \"to go (do something)\". In parts of the Koshikijima islands, the variant {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''kyaa'' is used, while in Tanegashima, the variant {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3042}} ''kaa'' is observed.<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u898b'''\u3051'''\u884c\u3063\u305f}} (''mi '''ke''' itta.'')<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\" />\n|mi{{=}}ke i-tta\n|see{{=}}PURP go-PST\n|'(I) went to look'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u9b5a\u91e3\u308a\u304d\u3083\u3042\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3044}} (''io tsuri '''kyaa''' ikoo i.'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|io tsur-i{{=}}kyaa ik-oo{{=}}i\n|fish angle-INF{{=}}PURP go-HORT{{=}}EMP\n|\"Let's go fishing!\"}}\n\nNote that this particle can only be used with verbs. With nouns, the particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' is used instead.<ref name=\"NinjalSHIGOTO\">{{cite web | title=\u4ed5\u4e8b[\u306b]\uff08\u884c\u3063\u305f\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-22.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3057\u3054'''\u3066'''\u884c\u3063\u305f}} (''shigot'''e''' itta'')<ref name=\"NinjalSHIGOTO\" />\n|shigoto{{=}}i i-tta\n|work{{=}}DAT go-PST\n|'(I) went to work'}}\n\n== Binding particles ==\n\n=== Topic ===\n==== (w)a ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306f }} ''a'' or ''wa'' is a [[topic marker]]. That is, it marks the main thing being talked about in a sentence. Like the particles {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' and {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', when {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject resyllabification. For instance, {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3044}} ''koi'' \"this\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3084}} ''koya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\" when topicalized.\n\n=== \"If only\" ===\n==== seka ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305b\u304b}} ''seka''<ref name=\"Higashimorokata\" /><ref>{{cite web | title=\u305b\u304b | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%9b%e3%81%8b/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> (or {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3042\u304b}} ''saaka'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> translates to \"if only\" and is always followed by a verb in the conditional form. In this usage, it is functionally equivalent to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3048}} ''sae''.\n\nExample from Koshikijima:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8eca'''\u3055\u3042\u304b'''\u6301\u3063\u3068\u304a\u308c\u3070}} (''kuruma '''saaka''' mottooreba'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n|kuruma{{=}}saaka mo{{=}}tte{{=}}o{{=}}reba\n|car{{=}}if_only have{{=}}CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}COND\n|'If you have a car'}}\n\n== Conjunctive particles ==\n\n=== Concessive ===\n==== batten ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u3066\u3093}} ''batten''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is a conjunctive particle meaning \"but\" or \"although\". It is less commonly used than {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3093}} ''don''.\n\n==== don ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3093}} ''don''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is a conjunctive particle meaning \"but\" or \"although\". It is etymologically related to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3082}} ''domo'' \"even though\", most notably used in the expression {{lang|ja|\u3051\u308c\u3069\u3082}} ''keredomo'' \"but\".\n\n=== Consequential ===\n==== de ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' (sometimes {{lang|ja|\u3067\u3048}} ''dee'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> can be combined with verbs or adjectives to mean \"because\".<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> It is used in place of the standard Japanese particles {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' or {{lang|ja|\u306e\u3067}} ''node''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304d\u3085\u306f\u3066\u305d\u304b'''\u3067'''\u3082\u3046\u884c\u304b\u3093\u3002}} (''kyu wa tesoka '''de''' m\u014d ikan.'')\n|kyu{{=}}wa teso-ka{{=}}de m\u014d ik-an.\n|today{{=}}TOP tired-ADJ{{=}}CNSQ anymore go-NEG\n|\"I won't be going anymore because I'm too tired today.\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u96e8\u304c\u964d\u3063\u3068\u3063'''\u3067'''}} (''ame ga futtod'''de''''')<ref>{{cite web | title=33 \uff08\u96e8\u304c\uff09\u964d\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b[\u304b\u3089] | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-33.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|ame{{=}}ga fu-tte{{=}}o\u0294{{=}}de\n|rain{{=}}NOM fall{{=}}CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Because it is raining'}}\n\n== Adverbial particles ==\n\n=== \"Just\" ===\n==== bakkai ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044}} ''bakkai'', roughly translating to \"just\", is functionally the same as standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3070\u304b\u308a}} ''bakari'' (colloquially {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u304b\u308a}} ''bakkari'').<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%b0%e3%81%a3%e3%81%8b%e3%81%84/ | language=ja | access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\">{{cite web | title=\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\u3000\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u8f9e\u5178 | website=\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b | url=http://onjyodoi.sakura.ne.jp/jiten/jiten.html | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3081\u306b\u3063\u3042\u3081'''\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044'''\u964d\u3063\u3068\u3063\u3069}} (''meni\u0294 ame '''bakkai''' futtoddo'')<ref>{{cite web | title=49 \u96e8[\u3070\u304b\u308a]\uff08\u964d\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-49.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|me-ni\u0294 ame{{=}}bakkai fu-tte{{=}}o\u0294{{=}}do.\n|every-day rain{{=}}just fall-CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's just raining every day\"}}\n\n=== \"Roughly\" ===\n==== doma ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u307e}} ''doma''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> typically follows nouns and marks approximation. It can be translated as \"roughly\", \"approximately\" , \"just about\", \"around\" or \"or so\" in English. The closest standard Japanese equivalents would be {{lang|ja|\u3070\u304b\u308a\u306f}} ''bakari wa'', {{lang|ja|\u3050\u3089\u3044\u306f}} ''gurai wa'' and {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3069\u306f}} ''nado wa''.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /><ref name=\"KenteiDoma\">{{cite web | title=\u3069\u307e | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%a9%e3%81%be-2/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nEtymologically, {{lang|ja|\u3069\u307e}} ''doma'' stems from the word {{lang|ja|\u5171}} ''tomo'', meaning \"together with\" in standard Japanese, and the topic particle \u306f ''(w)a''.<ref name=\"KenteiDoma\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e94\u4eba'''\u3069\u307e'''}} (''go nin '''doma''''')<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />\n|go nin doma\n|five people roughly\n|'Roughly five people'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305d\u3052\u3093\u304b\u3063\u305f\u304f\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3093'''\u3069\u307e'''\u3044\u3089\u3093\u3002}} (''sogen kattakutta kan '''doma''' iran.'')\n|so{{=}}gen kattakutta kan doma iran.\n|this{{=}}like scribble.PST paper roughly want.NEG\n|'I do not want scribbled paper like this'}}\n\n=== \"For example\" ===\n==== nando ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3093\u3069}} ''nando''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and its variant {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3069}} ''nado'' roughly translates to \"for example\" or \"such as\" in English.\n\n=== \"Only\" ===\n==== shiko ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3053}} ''shiko'' roughly translates to \"only\" or \"to such extent\" in English. It is used in place of standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3060\u3051}} ''dake''<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> or {{lang|ja|\u307b\u3069}} ''hodo''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />. Etymologically, {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3053}} ''shiko'' may be related to standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3057\u304d}} ''shiki'', found in compounds like {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308c\u3057\u304d}} ''koreshiki'' \"only this much\", as well as {{lang|ja|\u3057\u304b}} ''shika'' \"only\", which is limited in standard Japanese to negative phrases.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069'''\u3057\u3053'''\u3067\u3093}} (''do'''shiko''' den'')\n|do{{=}}shiko de{{=}}n\n|what{{=}}extent is{{=}}however\n|'As many as one likes'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u3063\u305f'''\u3057\u3053'''\u6301\u3063\u3051}} (''atta '''shiko''' mokke'')\n|atta{{=}}shiko mo\u0294{{=}}ke\n|have.PST{{=}}extent bring{{=}}come.IMP\n|'Bring all that you have'}}\n\n=== Terminative (or limitative) ===\n\n==== gii ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304e\u3044}} ''gii'' or its variant {{lang|ja|\u304e}} ''gi'' is used to indicate a time or place as a limit<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and can be translated as \"until\" or \"up to\" in English. It is functionally similar to the particle {{lang|ja|\u307e\u3067}} ''made'' in Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> Etymologically, the particle originated from the noun {{lang|ja|\u5207\u308a}} ''kiri'' meaning \"end\" or \"bound\", which also gave way to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u304d\u308a}} ''kiri'' (sometimes {{lang|ja|\u304e\u308a}} ''giri''), meaning \"just\" or \"only\".<ref>{{cite web | title=\u5207\u308a | website=Jisho.org | url=https://jisho.org/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keyword=%E5%88%87%E3%82%8A | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e94\u6642'''\u304e'''}} (''go ji '''gi''''')\n|go ji{{=}}gi\n|five hour{{=}}TERM\n|\"Until 5 o'clock\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u30cf\u30a4\u3001\u3053\u3044'''\u304e\u3044'''\u3088\u3002}} (''hai, koi '''gii''' yo.'')\n|hai koi{{=}}gii{{=}}yo\n|yes this{{=}}TERM{{=}}EMP\n|'Yes, so far'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3044\u3063\u3068\u3063\u3001\u304b\u3054\u3063\u307e'''\u304e\u3043'''\u3044\u305f\u3063\u304f\u3063\u3067\u3002}} (''itto\u0294, kagomma '''gii''' itakudde'')<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3053\u3053\u304c\u5909\u3060\u3088\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u4eba\u306e\u65b9\u8a00 | website=NAVER \u307e\u3068\u3081 | url=https://matome.naver.jp/odai/2134812638271947601 | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|itto\u0294, kagomma{{=}}gii itaku\u0294{{=}}de\n| hold_on kagoshima{{=}}TERM go_and_return{{=}}CNSQ\n|\"It's because I'm going to Kagoshima and back\"}}\n\n==== zui ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' (also spelled {{lang|ja|\u3065\u3044}} ''dzui'' and sometimes reduced to the form {{lang|ja|\u3058}} ''ji'') is used to indicate a time or place as a limit<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and can be translated as \"to\", \"until\" or \"up to\" in English. It is functionally similar to the particle {{lang|ja|\u307e\u3067}} ''made'' in Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> In the [[Higashimorokata District, Miyazaki|Higashimorokata district]] of [[Miyazaki Prefecture|Miyazaki]], the form {{lang|ja|\u305a\u308a}} ''zuri'' is used.<ref name=\"Higashimorokata\">{{cite web | title=\u5bae\u5d0e\u770c\u6771\u8af8\u306e\u65b9\u8a00\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/97061395.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nEtymologically, the particle {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' originates from the noun {{lang|ja|\u51fa\u308a}} \"setting out (to)\", which was historically pronounced ''dzuri'' in Kagoshima and is equivalent to the form {{lang|ja|\u51fa}} ''de'' \"coming out\" in modern standard Japanese. This is evidenced by the fact that the verb {{lang|ja|\u51fa\u308b}} \"to go out; to exit; to set out\" and its nominal form are still pronounced \u305a\u3044 ''zui'' or ''dzui'' in the traditional Kagoshima dialects.<ref>{{cite web | title=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u7511\u5cf6\u91cc\u65b9\u8a00 | url=http://hougen.sakura.ne.jp/shuppan/2017/3-16.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u6642'''\u305a\u3044'''}} (''i'''zzui''''')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" />\n|i\u0294{{=}}zui\n|when{{=}}TERM\n|'Until when?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u51e6'''\u305a\u3044'''}} (''doko '''zui''''')\n|doko{{=}}zui\n|where{{=}}TERM\n|'Up to where?', 'How far?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5e02\u6765\u304b\u3089\u5e02\u6bd4\u91ce'''\u3065\u3044'''}} (''Ichiki kara Ichihino '''dzui''''')<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3044\u3061\u304d\u4e32\u6728\u91ce\u5e02 - \u6c11\u8a71\u7de8 | url=https://sitereports.nabunken.go.jp/files/attach/30/30471/22057_2_%E3%81%84%E3%81%A1%E3%81%8D%E4%B8%B2%E6%9C%A8%E9%87%8E%E5%B8%82%E9%83%B7%E5%9C%9F%E5%8F%B2%E6%96%99%E9%9B%861%E6%B0%91%E8%A9%B1%E3%83%BB%E7%A5%AD%E3%82%8A%E7%B7%A8.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03 | page=29}}</ref>\n|ichiki{{=}}kara ichihino{{=}}dzui\n|ichiki{{=}}ABL ichihino{{=}}TERM\n|'From Ichiki to Ichihino'}}\n\nIn Koshikijima, {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' can also be used in the sense of \"even\" or \"so far as\":\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u9bdb'''\u305a\u3044'''\u3053\u304a\u3060}} (''tai '''zui''' kooda'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n|tai{{=}}zui koo-da\n|sea_bream{{=}}TERM eat-PST\n|'(I) even ate sea bream', '(I) went so far as eating sea bream'}}\n\n== Sentence-final particles ==\n\n=== Emphatic ===\n\n==== (w)ai, (w)a and i ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3042\u3044}} ''ai'' or more rarely {{lang|ja|\u308f\u3044}} ''wai'' is a sentence-final particle used to emphasize the utterance and to indicate that the speaker is expressing their own view. This particle attaches to the preceding word (typically a verb in its non-past form) and often fuses with the vowel of the final syllable of that word. Functionally, this particle is similar in usage to the particle {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' in standard Japanese. In the Koshikijima islands, the variants {{lang|ja|\u3042}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'' are used.<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\" />\n\nEtymologically, the particle is said to originate from the historical pronoun {{lang|ja|\u6211}} ''ware'' \"I\" and to be cognate with the sentence-ending particles {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'', {{lang|ja|\u308f\u3044}} ''wai'' and {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3044}} ''bai'' used dialectally throughout Japan.<ref name=\"KenjiTomosada\">{{cite web | first=Kenji | last=Tomosada | title=The Japanese language and character particles, as seen in dialect: Character particles and sentence-ending particles | publisher=Prefectural University of Hiroshima | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/288873317_The_Japanese_language_and_character_particles_as_seen_in_dialect | access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u66f8\u4ed8\u3092\u5fd8\u308c\u305f\u3042'''\u3044'''}} (''kattsuke o wasuretaa'''i''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|kattsuke{{=}}o wasure-ta{{=}}ai\n|document{{=}}ACC forget-PST{{=}}EMP\n|\"(I) forgot the documents\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5371\u306d\u8eca\u3084\u3089'''\u3044'''}} (''anne kuima yara'''i''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|anna{{=}}i kuima ya-ru{{=}}ai\n|dangerous{{=}}ADJ car COP-NPST{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's a dangerous car\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305d\u3044\u3082\u826f\u304b\u3042\u3044\u306d}} (''soi mo yokaa'''i''' ne'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|soi{{=}}mo yo-ka{{=}}ai{{=}}ne\n|that{{=}}also good-ADJ{{=}}EMP{{=}}EMP\n|\"That is also good\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|abbreviations=CONJC:conjectural|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3089\u3001\u65e5\u304c\u6e1b\u3089\u3093\u3046\u3061\u623b\u3069\u3044\u3082\u305d}} (''dora, hi ga heran uchi modoimoso '''wai'''. '')<ref name=\"KenjiTomosada\" />\n|dora hi{{=}}ga her-an uchi{{=}}i modo-i-mos-o{{=}}wai\n|whatever sun{{=}}NOM decrease-CONJC home{{=}}DAT return-INF-POL-VOL{{=}}EMP\n|\"Whatever the case, let's return before the sun goes down\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8e74\u3063\u3068\u3089\u3042}} (''kettor'''aa''''')<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|ke-tte{{=}}o-ru{{=}}a\n|kick-SEQ{{=}}PROG-NPST{{=}}EMP\n|\"(I am) kicking\"}}\n\nAfter a verb in its [[Kagoshima verb conjugations#Volitional (Presumptive)|volitional form]] (also called the presumptive form), the particle is reduced to {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' and serves to add insistence to what is being said. Examples from [[Izumi, Kagoshima]] include {{lang|ja|\u98f2\u3082\u3044}} ''nomoi'' \"let's drink\", {{lang|ja|\u884c\u3053\u3044}} ''ikoi'' \"let's go\", {{lang|ja|\u898b\u308d\u3044}} ''miroi'' \"let's see\" and {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3085\u3044}} ''shui'' \"let's do (it)\".<ref name=\"NozomiKodamaIzumi\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama | title=\u51fa\u6c34\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u30e2\u30fc\u30e9\u58f0\u8abf\u5358\u4f4d\u3068\u30a4\u30f3\u30c8\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 | trans-title=Moraic TBU's and Intonation in Izumi (Kagoshima) Dialect | url=http://l118.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/09-01.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==== do ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069}} ''do'', sometimes lengthened to {{lang|ja|\u3069\u304a\u30fb\u3069\u30fc}} ''doo'', can follow a verb or an adjective and is used to indicate assertion or add emphasis to what is said. It is functionally similar to the particles {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' and {{lang|ja|\u305e}} ''zo'' in standard Japanese<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> as well as the particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u30fc}} ''doo'' used in most Ryukyuan languages such as Okinawan.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3088\u304b'''\u3069'''}} (''yoka '''do''''')\n|yo-ka{{=}}do\n|good-ADJ{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's good!\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304b\u3048\u308d'''\u3069'''}} (''kaero '''do''''')\n|kae-ro{{=}}do\n|return-VOL{{=}}EMP\n|\"I'm going home!\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4eca\u65e5\u306f\u3088\u304b\u5929\u6c17\u3058\u3083\u3063'''\u3069'''}} (''kyu wa yoka tenki jad'''do''''')\n|kyu{{=}}wa yo-ka tenki ja\u0294{{=}}do\n|today{{=}}TOP good-ADJ weather is{{=}}EMP\n|'The weather is quite fine today!'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3093\u3093\u307e\u304b\u3063\u305f'''\u3069\u30fc'''}} (''nnmakatta '''doo''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Intonation\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u6587\u7bc0\u3068\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u3001\u304a\u3088\u3073\u30a4\u30f3\u30c8\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7intonation.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121314/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7intonation.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|nnma-ka-tta{{=}}doo\n|delicious-ADJ-PST{{=}}EMP\n|\"It was delicious!\"}}\n\n==== gaa ====\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304c\u3042}} ''gaa'' or sometimes just {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' has two primary functions.\n\nThe first is that it can be used to mark an interjection or a [[tag question]], similar to \"eh?\", \"right?\" or \"isn't it?\" in English or {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3084\u3063\u305b\u3093'''\u304c\u3042'''}} (''yassen '''gaa''''')\n|yassen{{=}}gaa\n|hopeless{{=}}Q\n|\"It's hopeless, eh?\"}}\n\nThe second is that it can be used to indicate a suggestion or mark insistence when following a verb in its plain form. In this sense, it can be translated to \"let's (...)\", \"(we) should (...)\" or \"shall we (...)?\" in English.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e00\u7dd2\u306b\u884c\u304f'''\u304c'''}} (''issho ni iku '''ga''''')<ref name=\"\u5742\u7530\u52dd\" />\n|issho{{=}}ni i-ku{{=}}ga\n|together{{=}}DAT go-NPST{{=}}Q\n|\"Let's go together\", \"Shall we go together?\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304f'''\u304c'''}} (''ku '''ga''''')\n|ku{{=}}ga\n|eat.NPST{{=}}Q\n|\"Let's eat\", \"(We) should eat\"}}\n\n==== nee ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306d\u3048}} ''nee'' or sometimes just {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' is used to mark an interjection or a tag question, similar to \"eh?\", \"right?\" or \"isn't it?\" in English or {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' in standard Japanese. \n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3093\u3093\u307e\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3069'''\u306d\u3048'''}} (''nnmakatta doo '''nee''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Intonation\" />\n|nnma-ka-tta{{=}}do{{=}}nee\n|delicious-ADJ-PST{{=}}EMP{{=}}Q\n|\"It was delicious, don't you agree?\"}}\n\n==== o (2) ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304a\u30fb\u3092}} ''o'' or {{lang|ja|\u304a\u30fc\u30fb\u3092\u30fc}} ''oo'' is a sentence-final particle used to stress the utterance. It is similar in usage to the particles {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' and {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'' in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u65e9\u3088\u884c\u3063\u304d\u3083\u3044'''\u304a\u30fc'''}} (''hayo ikkyai '''oo''''')<ref name=\"Showa\">{{cite web | title=\u662d\u548c\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u7dcf\u4f1a\u7684\u7814\u7a76 \u65b9\u8a00\u6587\u672b\u8a5e(\u6587\u672b\u52a9\u8a5e)\u306e\u7814\u7a76 | url=http://hougen.sakura.ne.jp/shuppan/2017/3-16.pdf | trans-title=General Assembly Study of Showa Japanese: Study on dialect final particles | language=ja | access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> (Example from the Eastern Satsuma Peninsula)\n|haya{{=}}u i-ki{{=}}ya-i oo\n|fast{{=}}ADV go-INF{{=}}do.aux.POL-IMP EMP\n|'Please go quickly'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u826f\u304b\u5929\u6c17\u3062\u3083\u306a'''\u304a'''}} (''yoka tenki ja na '''o''''')<ref name=\"Showa\" /> (Example from Yakushima)\n|yo-ka tenki ja na o\n|good-ADJ weather COP EMP EMP\n|'The weather is quite nice'}}\n\nIn Tanegashima, this particle fuses with the preceding word. For example, the phrase {{lang|ja|\u826f\u304b\u304a}} ''yoka o'' \"it's good\" would become {{lang|ja|\u826f\u3053\u30fc}} ''yokoo''.<ref name=\"Showa\" />\n\n=== Question ===\n==== ka ====\nLike standard Japanese, the sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' (pronounced {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' in Makurazaki city) is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. Compared to the question particles {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke'' and {{lang|ja|\u306a}} ''na'', the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' is neutral and can be used with anyone regardless of age.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u6708'''\u304b'''\uff1f}} (''nan gak'''ka'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n|nan ga\u0294{{=}}ka\n|what month{{=}}Q\n|'What month?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3084\u3063\u305f\u308d\u304c\uff1f}} (''do yattaro '''ga'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n|do ya-tta-ro{{=}}ga\n|how COP-PST-INFER{{=}}Q\n|'How was it?'}}\n\n==== ke (1) ====\nThe sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke'' or sometimes {{lang|ja|\u3051\u3048}} ''kee'' (pronounced {{lang|ja|\u3052}} ''ge'' and {{lang|ja|\u3052\u3048}} ''gee'' in Makurazaki city) is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. While this particle is functionally equivalent to the question particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'', it is more specifically used when talking to someone who is younger.<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\">{{cite web | first1=Nobuko | last1=Kibe | first2=Tomoyo | last2=Otsuki | first3=Kumiko | last3=Sato | title=Intonational Variations at the End of Interrogative Sentences in Japanese Dialects: From the \u201cCorpus of Japanese Dialects\u201d | publisher=National Institute for Japanese Language and Linguistics (NINJAL) | url=https://pj.ninjal.ac.jp/corpus_center/en/lrec2018sss_kibe.pdf | access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3044'''\u3051'''\uff1f\u4e00\u756a\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b\u305f\u3002}} (''doi '''ke'''? ibban komanka ta.'')\n|doi{{=}}ke? i\u0294-ban koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}a.\n|which{{=}}Q? one-number small-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}TOP.\n|'Which one? The smallest one.'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u660e\u65e5\u4f11\u307f'''\u3051\u3048'''\uff1f}} (''ashita yasumi '''kee'''?'')<ref name=\"\u5742\u7530\u52dd\">{{cite book | title=\u304b\u3054\u3057\u307e\u5f01\u5165\u9580\u8b1b\u5ea7: \u57fa\u790e\u304b\u3089\u5fdc\u7528\u307e\u3067 | first=\u52dd| last=\u5742\u7530 | page=117 | year=2007 | publisher=\u56f3\u66f8\u51fa\u7248\u3000\u5357\u65b9\u65b0\u793e | isbn=4861241073}}</ref>\n|ashita yasumi{{=}}kee?\n|tomorrow holiday{{=}}Q?\n|'Is tomorrow a holiday?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u623b\u3063\u6765\u305f'''\u3052'''\uff1f}} (''modokkita '''ge'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" /> (Example from around Makurazaki city)\n|modo-\u0294{{=}}ki-ta{{=}}ge?\n|return-SEQ{{=}}come-PST{{=}}Q\n|'Have (they) come back?'}}\n\n==== na ====\nThe sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u306a}} ''na'' is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. While this particle is functionally equivalent to the question particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'', it is more specifically used when talking to someone who is older.<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u623b\u3063\u3066\u6765\u305f\u3082\u3093\u3062\u3083\u306a\u304c\u3069\u306a\uff1f}} (''Modotte kita mon janaga do na'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" /> (Example from around Makurazaki city)\n|modo-tte ki-ta{{=}}mon ja-naga{{=}}do{{=}}na\n|return-SEQ come-PST{{=}}NMLZ COP-NEG{{=}}EMP{{=}}Q\n|'Is it not the case that the person came back?'}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kagoshima dialect]]\n* [[Japanese particles]]\n* [[Japanese grammar#Particles|Japanese grammar: particles]]\n* [[Kansai dialect#Particles|Kansai dialect: particles]]\n* [[Okinawan language#Particles|Okinawan language: particles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japanese language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kagoshima dialect}}\n[[Category:Japanese dialects]]\n[[Category:Kagoshima Prefecture]]\n", "text_old": "The [[grammatical particle]]s ({{lang|ja|\u52a9\u8a5e}} ''joshi'') used in the [[Kagoshima dialect]]s of Japanese have many features in common with those of other dialects spoken in [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]], with some being unique to the Kagoshima dialects. Like [[japanese particles|standard Japanese particles]], they act as suffixes, adpositions or words immediately following the noun, verb, adjective or phrase that they modify, and are used to indicate the relationship between the various elements of a sentence.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://japanese.about.com/blparticles.htm | title=Japanese Particles | publisher=About.com | year=2009 | accessdate=2009-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timwerx.net/language/particles.htm | title=Japanese Particles | first=Tim R. | last=Matheson | publisher=Tim's Takamatsu | year=2008 | accessdate=2009-10-29}}</ref>\n\nUnlike central Japanese dialects, particles in the Kagoshima dialects are bound [[clitic]]s, as they have the effect of resyllabifying the last word they attach to. So, for example, the standard forms {{lang|ja|\u672c\u3092}} ''hon o'' \"book {{gcl|ACC}}\", {{lang|ja|\u66f8\u304d\u3092}} ''kaki o'' \"writing {{gcl|ACC}}\" and {{lang|ja|\u307e\u308a\u3092}} ''mari o'' \"ball {{gcl|ACC}}\" would be realized as {{IPA|/hoNno/}}, {{IPA|/kakjo/}} and {{IPA|/majo/}} ( \u2190 {{IPA|/ma\u027djo/}}) in most of northern and central Kagoshima, and {{IPA|/hoNnu/}}, {{IPA|/kakju/~/kaku/}} and {{IPA|/maju/}} ( \u2190 {{IPA|/ma\u027dju/}}) in parts of Kagoshima's southern mainland.<ref>Shibatani (1990), p. 210</ref>\n\nResyllabification has also led to the reanalysis of some particles in a few dialects. For instance, the topic particle ''(w)a'' has been completely superseded by the form ''na'' in [[Izumi, Kagoshima|Izumi]],<ref name=\"Izumi\">{{cite web | url=http://sky.geocities.jp/ryohusyokyoryu/izumigo.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202234707/http://sky.geocities.jp/ryohusyokyoryu/izumigo.html | archivedate=2013-12-02 | script-title=ja:\u5317\u85a9\u51fa\u6c34\u8a9e\u3092\u8a71\u3057\u3066\u307f\u3088\u3046\uff01 | language=Japanese |trans-title=Let's learn the Hokusatsu district Izumi dialect! | accessdate=2012-04-22}}</ref> which in most mainland dialects is merely a variant of ''(w)a'' after a moraic nasal.\n\n== Resyllabification rules ==\n\nWhen a word is followed by a particle that starts with a vowel (such as the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'', the accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' or the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''), the final syllable of that word will be fused with the particle and be subject to Kagoshima's [[kagoshima dialect#Coalescence|vowel coalescence rules]] as well as other sound changes occurring in the regional dialect. As a simple example, when the word {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308c}} {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}} ''kore'' \"this\" is followed by the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} {{IPA|/a/}}, it becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308a\u3083}} {{IPA|/ko\u027dja/}} ''korya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\". A secondary sound change in Mainland Kagoshima then causes the medial {{IPA|/\u027dj/}} ''ry'' to become {{IPA|/j/}} ''y'', giving the common form {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3084}} {{IPA|/koja/}} ''koya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\".\n\nTwo main exceptions to this rule exist:\n\n# If a word's underlying form ends in a moraic nasal (i.e. {{IPA|/N/}}), an [[Epenthesis|epenthetic]] {{IPA|/n/}} is inserted between the word and the particle. For example, {{lang|ja|\u672c}} {{IPA|/hoN/}} ''hon'' \"book\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u672c\u306f}} {{IPA|/hoNna/}} ''honna'' when fused with the topic particle.\n# If a word's underlying form ends in a long vowel or sequence of vowels, then an epenthetic consonant is sometimes inserted between the word and the topic particle. In the case of topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and the accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'', the epenthetic consonant is {{IPA|/w/}}. In the case of the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', the epenthetic consonant is {{IPA|/n/}}. This rule is not consistently applied across all dialects of Kagoshima.\n\nThe following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the mainland Kagoshima dialects.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in mainland Kagoshima\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n| {{IPA|/koi/}}\n| {{IPA|/koja/}}\n| {{IPA|/kojo/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n|-\n| writing\n| {{IPA|/kaki/}}\n| {{IPA|/kaQ/}}\n| {{IPA|/kakja/}} or {{IPA|/kaka/}}<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/kakjo/}} or {{IPA|/kaku/}}<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/kaki/}}\n|-\n| ball\n| {{IPA|/ma\u027di/}}\n| {{IPA|/mai/}}\n| {{IPA|/maja/}}\n| {{IPA|/majo/}}\n| {{IPA|/ma\u027di/}}\n|-\n| song\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/utao/}}\n| {{IPA|/ute/}}\n|-\n| hitting\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/uQ/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255a/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255o/}}, {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255u/}} or {{IPA|/ut\u0361su/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n|-\n| person<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hita/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hite/}}\n|-\n| study<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoa/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/beNkjoi/}}\n|-\n| book\n| {{IPA|/hoN/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoN/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNna/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNno/}}\n| {{IPA|/hoNni/}}\n|}\n\nThe rules of resyllabification differ only slightly in peripheral areas. The following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the Sato dialect of the [[Koshikijima Islands]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in the Sato village of Koshikijima<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\">{{cite web | first=Kuroki | last=Kunihiko | title=\u4e0a\u7511\u5cf6\u8af8\u65b9\u8a00\u306e(\u5f62\u614b) \u97f3\u97fb\u985e\u578b\u8ad6 | url=http://hotarugaikegengokenkyuuzyo.web.fc2.com/Nihongo_Gakkai_2013_06_02.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref name=\"SatoGrammar\">{{cite web | first1=Mori | last1=Yuta | first2=Hiratsuka | last2=Yusuke | first3=Kuroki | last3=Kunihiko | title=\u7511\u5cf6\u91cc\u65b9\u8a00\u8a18\u8ff0\u6587\u6cd5\u66f8 | trans-title=Descriptive grammar of the Sato dialect of Koshikijima | url=https://www.academia.edu/11954027/%E7%94%91%E5%B3%B6%E9%87%8C%E6%96%B9%E8%A8%80%E8%A8%98%E8%BF%B0%E6%96%87%E6%B3%95%E6%9B%B8 | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027de/}}\n| {{IPA|/koi/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027daa/}}\n| {{IPA|/ko\u027dee/}}\n|-\n| thing\n| {{IPA|/mono/}}\n| {{IPA|/mono/}}\n| {{IPA|/monaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/monee/}}\n|-\n| song\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/uta/}}\n| {{IPA|/utaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/utjaa/}}\n|-\n| hitting\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255i/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255aa/}}\n| {{IPA|/ut\u0361\u0255ii/}}\n|-\n| ticket\n| {{IPA|/\u0278uda/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278uda/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278udaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0278udjaa/}}\n|-\n| river\n| {{IPA|/kawa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/kawjaa/}}\n|-\n| lye\n| {{IPA|/aaku/}}\n| {{IPA|/aaku/}}\n| {{IPA|/aakaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/aakii/}}\n|}\n\n* Note: The accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'') is not listed above because the Sato dialect replaced it with the particle {{lang|ja|\u3070}} ''ba''. For example, the accusative form of ''koi'' \"this\" is simply ''koi ba''.<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n\nAnd the following table shows how particles change the final syllable of words in the [[Tanegashima]] dialects.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Resyllabification in Tanegashima<ref name=\"NozomiKodama\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama | title=\u7a2e\u5b50\u5cf6\u4e8c\u578b\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u306e\u5883\u754c\u7279\u5fb4\uff0d\u81ea\u767a\u8ac7\u8a71\u97f3\u58f0\u8cc7\u6599\u306e\u5206\u6790 | trans-title=On the Edge Feature of Tanegashima Two-pattern Accent: Prosodic Analysis based on Corpora of Spontaneous Speech | url=http://lg.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/13-02.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n|-\n!| Meaning\n!| [[Underlying representation|Underlying form]]\n!| Pronunciation in isolation\n!| Topic particle ({{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''(w)a'')\n!| Accusative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'')\n!| Dative particle ({{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'')\n|-\n| this\n| {{IPA|/kore/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/kora/}} or {{IPA|/korja/}}\n| {{IPA|/korjo/}}\n| \n|-\n| person\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hito/}}\n| {{IPA|/hitaa/}}\n| {{IPA|/hitoo/}}\n| \n|-\n| sugar\n| {{IPA|/satoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/satoo/}}\n| {{IPA|/satoowa/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| now\n| {{IPA|/ima/}}\n| {{IPA|/ima/}}\n| {{IPA|/imoo/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| time\n| {{IPA|/toki/}}\n| {{IPA|/toki/}}\n| {{IPA|/tokjaa/}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| candy\n| {{IPA|/ame/}}\n| {{IPA|/ame/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/ameo/}}\n| \n|-\n| oil\n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekiju/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekiju/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/\u0255ekijoo/}}\n| \n|-\n| mountain\n| {{IPA|/jama/}}\n| {{IPA|/jamaa/}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA|/jamaai/}}\n|-\n| care\n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iN/}}\n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iN/}}\n| \n| {{IPA|/jood\u0361\u0291iNno/}}\n| \n|}\n\n* Note: Blank entries indicate that examples could not be found or inferred from the source.\n\n=== Historical attestation ===\n\nThe phenomenon of resyllabification (or particle fusion) is first attested for the Kagoshima dialect in the 18th-century works of [[Gonza]], a Japanese castaway from [[Satsuma, Kagoshima|Satsuma]] who was taken to [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia around 1733-1734. Under the supervision of assistant librarian Andrei Bogdanov, Gonza helped produce several reference works on the Japanese language in Russian, including an introductory, a grammar and a dictionary.<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\">{{cite web | first=Nobuko | last=Kibe | title=18\u4e16\u7d00\u85a9\u6469\u306e\u6f02\u6d41\u6c11\u30b4\u30f3\u30b6\u306e\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | trans-title=On the accent of the 18th-century Satsuma drifter Gonza | url=https://db3.ninjal.ac.jp/SJL/getpdf.php?number=1910970840cs | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> These works provide the oldest glimpse into the Kagoshima dialect.\n\nFor the most part, the works of Gonza show that the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and the dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' followed the same rules as they do today, fusing with the final syllable of the preceding word and being subject to the same exceptions that exist today. The accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''wo'', however, was independent and shows fusion in only a couple recorded examples.<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"display: inline-table;\"\n|+ Topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Thief || n\u00fasda || {{lang|ja|\u76d7\u4eba\u306f}}<br />''nusuto wa''\n|-\n| Cow, heifer || \u00fasha || {{lang|ja|\u725d\u725b\u306f}}<br />''meushi wa''\n|-\n| Autumn || aky\u00e0|| {{lang|ja|\u79cb\u306f}}<br />''aki wa''\n|-\n| Night || yor\u00e0 || {{lang|ja|\u591c\u306f}}<br />''yoru wa''\n|-\n| I || \u00f3ra || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u306f}}<br />''ore wa''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Dative particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" /><br />(recorded as ''n'' after a long vowel)\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Country || k\u00fani || {{lang|ja|\u56fd\u306b}}<br />''kuni ni''\n|-\n| Person || ft\u00e8 || {{lang|ja|\u4eba\u306b}}<br />''hito ni''\n|-\n| Garden || n\u00edwe || {{lang|ja|\u5ead\u306b}}<br />''niwa ni''\n|-\n| One generation || \u00edchden || {{lang|ja|\u4e00\u4ee3\u306b}}<br />''ichidai ni''\n|-\n| I || \u00f3re || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u306b}}<br />''ore ni''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Accusative particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''wo''<ref name=\"GonzaNobukoKibe\" />\n|-\n! Meaning !! Recorded example !! Modern standard Japanese\n|-\n| Write a character || \u0292\u00f3 kak || {{lang|ja|\u5b57\u3092\u66f8\u304f}}<br />''ji o kaku''\n|-\n| What || n\u00e1nyu || {{lang|ja|\u4f55\u3092}}<br />''nani o''\n|-\n| Country || k\u00fan wo || {{lang|ja|\u56fd\u3092}}<br />''kuni o''\n|-\n| Me || \u00f3i wo || {{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u3092}}<br />''ore o''\n|}\n\n== Syntactic case-marking particles ==\n\n=== ga and no ===\nIn [[Old Japanese]], the particles ''ga'' and ''no'' had overlapping functions as [[genitive]] and [[nominative]] markers, and were ultimately distinguished by their degree of [[politeness]].<ref name=\"Shibatani\">Shibatani (1990), pp. 205-206</ref> Satsug\u016b, like other Western [[Japanese dialects#Ky\u016bsh\u016b|Ky\u016bsh\u016b]] and [[Ryukyuan languages|Ryukyuan]] dialects, is notable in that this original distinction is, to a certain extent, kept.\n\nIn Kagoshima, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' is considered somewhat more derogatory and occurs mainly with a human subject or possessor,<ref>{{cite book | title=Rethinking Japan: Literature, Visual Arts & Linguistics | authors=Adriana Boscaro, Franco Gatti and Massimo Raveri | publisher=Routledge | year=1991 | page=320 | isbn=978-0-904404-78-4}}</ref> whereas ''no'' (or ''n'') is considered more neutral or polite.<ref name=\"Shibatani\" />\n\nExamples:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4ffa'''\u304c'''\u5bb6}} (''oi '''ga''' e'')\n|oi{{=}}ga e\n|1{{=}}GEN home\n|'My house', 'my family'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4ffa'''\u304c'''\u3066\u306d\u3052}} (''oi '''ga''' tenege'')<ref>{{cite web | title=13 [\u304a\u308c\u306e]\uff08\u624b\u62ed\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-13.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|oi{{=}}ga tenege\n|1{{=}}GEN handtowel\n|'My handtowel'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5148\u751f'''\u306e'''\u3066\u306d\u3052}} (''sense '''no''' tenege'')<ref>{{cite web | title=14 \u5148\u751f[\u306e](\u624b\u62ed) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-14.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|sense{{=}}no tenege\n|teacher{{=}}GEN handtowel\n|'The teacher's handtowel'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' is sometimes reduced to {{lang|ja|\u3093}} ''n''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u673a'''\u3093'''\u4e2d}} (''tsukue'''n''' naka'')\n|tsukue{{=}}n naka\n|desk{{=}}GEN inside\n|'inside the desk'}}\n\n=== i ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and its variant {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni'' can be used to mark a location (like \"in\" or \"at\" in English), indicate a direction (like \"to\" or \"towards\"), mark an indirect object, or mark the agent in a [[Passive voice|passive]] sentence. Its usage is very similar to those of the particles {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni'' \"in/at/to\" and {{lang|ja|\u3078}} ''e'' \"to/towards\" in standard Japanese.\n\nLike the particles {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'', when {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject to vowel coalescence.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304a'''\u308c'''\u8cb8\u305b}} (''Or'''e''' kase'')<ref>{{cite web | title=25 \u304a\u308c[\u306b]\uff08\u8cb8\u305b\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-25.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|ore{{=}}i kas-e\n|1{{=}}DAT lend-IMP\n|'Lend it to me'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u305d'''\u3051'''\u884c\u304b\u3093\u304b}} (''asok'''e''' ikan ka'')\n|asoko{{=}}i ik-an{{=}}ka\n|over_there{{=}}DAT go-NEG{{=}}Q\n|\"How about we go over there\"}}\n\n==== ina ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3044\u306a}} ''ina'' (or {{lang|ja|\u3044\u306b\u3083\u3042}} ''inyaa'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> generally means \"for\", \"in\", \"to\" or \"in order to\". Etymologically, it is a combination of the particles {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' and {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' and is cognate with the standard Japanese construction {{lang|ja|\u306b\u306f}} ''ni wa''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u660e\u65e5\u305a'''\u3044\u306a'''}} (''ashita zu'''ina''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\" />\n|ashita{{=}}zui{{=}}ina\n|tomorrow{{=}}until{{=}}DAT.TOP\n|\"By tomorrow\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3053'''\u3051\u306b\u3083\u3042'''\u3059\u3063\u3053\u3081\u306e\u53d7\u304b\u3063\u3068\u3044}} (''kok'''enyaa''' sukkome no ukattoi'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|koko{{=}}inyaa sukkome{{=}}no uka-tte{{=}}o-i\n|here{{=}}DAT.TOP scalpel_sawtail{{=}}NOM float-CONJ{{=}}PROG-INF\n|\"There are Scalpel Sawtail fish floating (in) here\"}}\n\n=== kara ===\nLike standard Japanese, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' and its regional variants {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3042}} ''kaa'' and {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' are used to indicate a time or place from which something begins. In this sense, it can generally be translated to \"from\" in English.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4eca'''\u304b\u3042'''}} (''Ima '''kaa''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|ima{{=}}kaa\n|now{{=}}ABL\n|'From now'}}\n\nUnlike standard Japanese, this particle is not used to mark a reason. Instead, the Kagoshima particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' is used for that purpose. For example, in the standard Japanese sentence {{lang|ja|\u753a'''\u304b\u3089'''\u53d6\u3063\u3066\u304f\u308b\u3082\u306e\u3067\u3059\u304b\u3089}} ''machi '''kara''' totte kuru mono desu '''kara''''' \"'''because''' it was bought '''from''' town\",<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" /> the first instance remains {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' in Kagoshima while the second would become {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'':\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u753a'''\u304b\u3042'''\u53d6\u3063\u304f\u3093\u3082\u3093\u3058\u3083\u3093\u3067}} (''mak'''kaa''' tokkun mon jan de'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|ma\u0294{{=}}kaa to\u0294-ku-n{{=}}mon ja-n{{=}}de\n|town{{=}}ABL take-come-NPST{{=}}NMZ COP{{=}}NPST{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Because it was bought from town'}}\n\nIn a few Kagoshima dialects, the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' can be used in two additional ways that are different from standard Japanese.\n\n(1) In the first, it can be used to indicate the mean used to arrive to a situation (such as the mean of transportation), overlapping with the standard particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' \"by\" in this sense. For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8239'''\u304b\u3089'''\u6765\u305f}} (''fune '''kara''' kita'')<ref>{{cite web | title=29 \u8239[\u3067]\uff08\u6765\u305f\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-29.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|fune{{=}}kara k-ita\n|boat{{=}}ABL come-PST\n|'(He) came by boat'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u30d0\u30b9'''\u304b\u3089'''\u884c\u304f\u3067\u3048}} (''basu '''kara''' iku dee'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|basu{{=}}kara ik-u{{=}}dee\n|bus{{=}}ABL go-NPST{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Since (I) go by bus'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' does not replace the other usages of {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' \"by\". For instance, it cannot be used to mark the tool used to achieve an action. So in the sentence \"to write ''with'' a brush\", {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' would be used.<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n\n(2) In the second, it can be used to mark the agent in an [[Passive voice#Adversative passive|adversative-passive]] sentence, replacing the standard particle {{lang|ja|\u306b}} ''ni''. For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u72ac'''\u304b\u3089'''\u3048\u304b\u3051\u3089\u308b\u305f}} (''in '''kara''' ekakeraruta'')<ref>{{cite web | title=27 \u72ac[\u306b]\uff08\u8ffd\u3044\u304b\u3051\u3089\u308c\u305f) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-27.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|in{{=}}kara ekake-raru-ta\n|dog{{=}}ABL chase-PAS-PST\n|'(I) was chased by a dog'}}\n\n=== o (1) ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' is a case particle that marks the direct object in a sentence. Depending on the word that precedes, it can also be pronounced {{lang|ja|\u3046}} ''u''.\n\nLike the particles {{lang|ja|\u3042}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', when {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject resyllabification. For instance, {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3044}} ''koi'' \"this\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3088}} ''koyo'' \"this={{gcl|ACC}}\".\n\nExample:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u307b\u3093'''\u306e'''\u8aad\u3093}} (''hon'''no''' yon'')\n|hon{{=}}o yo-n\n|book{{=}}ACC read-NPST\n|'(I) read a book.'}}\n\n==== oba ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3070}} ''ba'' or {{lang|ja|\u3092\u3070}} ''oba'' marks a topicalized direct object. This form historically derives from a contraction of the [[accusative case|accusative]] marker ''wo'' and the topic particle ''\u0278a'' (modern day ''wa'').<ref name=\"Shibatani\" /> In several Western Ky\u016bsh\u016b dialects, ''ba'' has completely replaced the particle ''o'' as the accusative marker. However, the use of the particle ''ba'' within the Satsug\u016b dialect is restricted mainly to the Koshikijima Islands<ref name=\"koshikijima\">{{cite web | url=http://www.koshikijima.net/hougen/hougen.html |  title=\u7511\u5cf6\u306e\u65b9\u8a00\uff08\u6587\u4f8b\u96c6\uff09 | publisher=K&I PROJECT | accessdate=2010-01-28}}</ref> and is not as widespread elsewhere. Considered an archaism in Standard Japanese,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tangorin.com/general/woba|title=woba\u3010\u3092\u3070\u3011|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Tangorin.com|accessdate=2009-12-08}}</ref> the form ''oba'', pronounced ''uba'' in Southern Kagoshima, is more frequently used instead.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~hi5k-stu/bbs/bbs0210.htm | author=massangeana | title=\u8a00\u8449\u306e\u4e16\u754c\u30fb\u4f1d\u8a00\u677f\u30002002\u5e7410\u6708: \u3044\u308d\u3044\u308d | date=2002-10-25 | accessdate=2009-12-08}}</ref> In contrast with the particle ''o'', ''oba'' can be described as an emphatic accusative; that is, it places more emphasis on the direct object.\n\nExamples:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u307f\u3063'''\u3092\u3070'''\u98f2\u3093\u3060}} (''mi\u0294 '''oba''' nonda'')\n|mi\u0294{{=}}o{{=}}ba no-nda\n|water{{=}}ACC{{=}}TOP drink-PST\n|'(I) drank water.'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u672c'''\u3070'''\u8aad\u3093}} (''hon '''ba''' yon'')\n|hon{{=}}ba yo-n\n|book{{=}}ACC.TOP read-NPST\n|'(I) read a book.'}}\n\n=== see ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305b\u3048}} ''see'' and its many regional variations (e.g. {{lang|ja|\u305b}} ''se'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3044}} ''sai'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3048}} ''sae'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3093}} ''san'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u306d}} ''sane'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3081}} ''same'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3081\u3048}} ''samee'', {{lang|ja|\u3055\u307f\u3083\u3042}} ''samyaa'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Sagyou\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u30b5\u884c | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7sagyou.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121127/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7sagyou.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=19 \u6771\u306e\u65b9[\u3078]\uff08\u884c\u3051\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-19.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=\u3055\u3044\uff08\u3055\u3048\uff09 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%95%e3%81%84%e3%83%bb%e3%81%95%e3%81%88/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> marks direction. It can roughly be translated as \"in\" or \"to\" in English and is comparable in usage to {{lang|ja|\u3078}} ''e'' in standard Japanese. Etymologically, the particle is said to originate from the expression {{lang|ja|\u69d8\u306b}} ''sama ni'' \"by way of, in the state of\".<ref>{{cite web | title=\u305b\u3047 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%9b%e3%81%87/ | language=ja | access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u6771\u4eac'''\u305b\u3048'''}} (''tokyo '''see''''')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\">{{cite web | title=\u304b\u3054\u3063\u307e\u306e\u8a71 - \u95a2\u6771\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u4eba\u4f1a\u9023\u5408\u4f1a | website=Kagoshima Kenjinkai | url=http://www.kagoshimakenjinkai.ne.jp/kaggoma.html | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama |title=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u77ed\u3044\u9577\u6bcd\u97f3 | trans-title=Phonologically Long Vowels in Kagoshima Japanese | url=http://lg.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/18-03.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n|tokyo{{=}}see\n|Tokyo{{=}}LAT\n|'In/to Tokyo'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u6307\u5bbf'''\u305b\u3048'''\u3001\u884c\u3063\u304d\u305f\u3002}} (''ibusus'''see''', ikkita.'')\n|ibusu\u0294{{=}}see i\u0294{{=}}ki-ta\n|Ibusuki{{=}}LAT go{{=}}come-PST\n|'(I) came back from Ibusuki'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e0b'''\u305b\u3048'''\u884c\u305f\u3002}} (''shita '''see''' ita.'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|shita{{=}}see i-ta\n|down{{=}}LAT go-PST\n|'(I) went down', '(I) went to the bottom'}}\n\n=== to ===\nOther than its standard usages, the particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} is also a nominalizing particle in the Kagoshima dialects. That is, it can be appended to a verb, an adjective or another utterance to transform it into a noun. This usage is similar to how {{lang|ja|\u306e}} ''no'' is used in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u305f\u3044\u304c'''\u3068'''}} (''Atai ga '''to''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u30bf\u884c | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7tagyou.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121138/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7tagyou.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|atai{{=}}ga{{=}}to\n|1{{=}}GEN{{=}}NMZ\n|'Mine'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b'''\u3068'''\u3068\u3075\u3068\u304b'''\u3068'''\u3068}} (''komanka '''to''' to futoka '''to''' to'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\" />\n|koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}to futo-ka{{=}}to{{=}}to\n|small-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}COM big-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}COM\n|'The small one and the big one'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305f\u3051\u3048'''\u3068'''\u304c\u826f\u304b}} (''takee '''to''' ga yoka'')<ref name=\"TeruoHirayama\">{{cite web | first=Teruo | last=Hirayama | title=\n\u30c8\u30ab\u30e9\u7fa4\u5cf6\u30fb\u5c4b\u4e45\u5cf6\u30fb\u7a2e\u5b50\u5cf6\u306e\u65b9\u8a00 | trans-title=Dialects of the Tokara Islands, Yakushima and Tanegashima | url=https://db3.ninjal.ac.jp/SJL/getpdf.php?number=0690820960 | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> (Example from Onoaida, Yakushima)\n|taka{{=}}i{{=}}to{{=}}ga yo-ka\n|tall{{=}}ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}NOM good-ADJ\n|'The tall one is good'}}\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} can also be used at the end of declarative sentences to add mild emphasis.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u884c\u3063'''\u3068'''\u3088}} (''It'''to''' yo'')<ref name=\"rtymg285Tagyou\" />\n|i\u0294{{=}}to{{=}}yo\n|go.NPST{{=}}EMP{{=}}EMP\n|\"I'm going\"}}\n\n==== ta ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305f}} ''ta'' or its variant {{lang|ja|\u305f\u3042}} ''taa'' is a combination of the nominalizing particle {{lang|ja|\u3068}} ''to'' and the topic particle {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a''. It can be combined with a verb or adjective to turn it into a noun, similar to how {{lang|ja|\u3082\u306e\u306f}} ''mono wa'' and {{lang|ja|\u306e\u306f}} ''no wa'' work in standard Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3044\u3051\uff1f\u4e00\u756a\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b'''\u305f'''\u3002}} (''doi ke? ibban komanka '''ta'''.'')\n|doi{{=}}ke? i\u0294.ban koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}a.\n|which{{=}}Q? one.number small-ADJ{{=}}NOM{{=}}TOP.\n|'Which one? The smallest one.'}}\n\n=== yokka ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3088\u3063\u304b}} ''yokka''<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> or its variant {{lang|ja|\u3088\u304b}} ''yoka''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is used in place of standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3088\u308a}} ''yori'' and, like it, it has two main functions. The first is that it can be used to indicate the origin of something, akin to \"from\" or \"beginning from\" in English. The second is that it can be used to make comparisons, roughly translating to \"more than\" or \"rather than\". In southern Koshikijima and northern Tanegashima, the variant {{lang|ja|\u3088\u3044\u304b}} ''yoika'' is used, while in northern Koshikijima, the forms {{lang|ja|\u3088\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''yokyaa'' and {{lang|ja|\u3086\u3046\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''yuukyaa'' are observed.<ref>{{cite web | title=31 \u305d\u308c[\u3088\u308a]\uff08\u3042\u306e\u65b9\u304c\u826f\u3044\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-31.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> Etymologically, the particle is considered a contraction of {{lang|ja|\u3088\u308a}} ''yori'' and {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka''.<ref name=\"naiyokka\">{{cite web | title=\u306a\u3044\u3088\u3063\u304b\u30fb\u306a\u3044\u3088\u3063\u3082 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%aa%e3%81%84%e3%82%88%e3%81%a3%e3%81%8b%e3%83%bb%e3%81%aa%e3%81%84%e3%82%88%e3%81%a3%e3%82%82/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55'''\u3088\u3063\u304b'''}} (''nai '''yokka''''')<ref name=\"naiyokka\" />\n|nai{{=}}yokka\n|what{{=}}COMP\n|'More than anything'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u82b1'''\u3088\u3063\u304b'''\u56e3\u5b50}} (''hana '''yokka''' dango'')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" />\n|hana{{=}}yokka dango\n|flower{{=}}COMP dumpling\n|'Dumplings rather than flowers', 'Substance over form'}}\n\n== Binding particles ==\n\n=== (w)a ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306f }} ''a'' or ''wa'' is a [[topic marker]]. That is, it marks the main thing being talked about in a sentence. Like the particles {{lang|ja|\u3092}} ''o'' and {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'', when {{lang|ja|\u306f}} ''a'' is added to a word, the final syllable of that word will be subject resyllabification. For instance, {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3044}} ''koi'' \"this\" becomes {{lang|ja|\u3053\u3084}} ''koya'' \"this={{gcl|TOP}}\" when topicalized.\n\n=== seka ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305b\u304b}} ''seka''<ref name=\"Higashimorokata\" /><ref>{{cite web | title=\u305b\u304b | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%9b%e3%81%8b/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> (or {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3042\u304b}} ''saaka'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> translates to \"if only\" and is always followed by a verb in the conditional form. In this usage, it is functionally equivalent to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u3055\u3048}} ''sae''.\n\nExample from Koshikijima:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8eca'''\u3055\u3042\u304b'''\u6301\u3063\u3068\u304a\u308c\u3070}} (''kuruma '''saaka''' mottooreba'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n|kuruma{{=}}saaka mo{{=}}tte{{=}}o{{=}}reba\n|car{{=}}if_only have{{=}}CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}COND\n|'If you have a car'}}\n\n== Conjunctive particles ==\n\n=== batten ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u3066\u3093}} ''batten''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is a conjunctive particle meaning \"but\" or \"although\". It is less commonly used than {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3093}} ''don''.\n\n=== de ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3067}} ''de'' (sometimes {{lang|ja|\u3067\u3048}} ''dee'' in northern Koshikijima)<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> can be combined with verbs or adjectives to mean \"because\".<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> It is used in place of the standard Japanese particles {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3089}} ''kara'' or {{lang|ja|\u306e\u3067}} ''node''.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304d\u3085\u306f\u3066\u305d\u304b'''\u3067'''\u3082\u3046\u884c\u304b\u3093\u3002}} (''kyu wa tesoka '''de''' m\u014d ikan.'')\n|kyu{{=}}wa teso-ka{{=}}de m\u014d ik-an.\n|today{{=}}TOP tired-ADJ{{=}}CNSQ anymore go-NEG\n|\"I won't be going anymore because I'm too tired today.\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u96e8\u304c\u964d\u3063\u3068\u3063'''\u3067'''}} (''ame ga futtod'''de''''')<ref>{{cite web | title=33 \uff08\u96e8\u304c\uff09\u964d\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b[\u304b\u3089] | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-33.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|ame{{=}}ga fu-tte{{=}}o\u0294{{=}}de\n|rain{{=}}NOM fall{{=}}CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}CNSQ\n|'Because it is raining'}}\n\n=== don ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3093}} ''don''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> is a conjunctive particle meaning \"but\" or \"although\". It is etymologically related to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u3082}} ''domo'' \"even though\", most notably used in the expression {{lang|ja|\u3051\u308c\u3069\u3082}} ''keredomo'' \"but\".\n\n== Adverbial particles ==\n\n=== bakkai ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044}} ''bakkai'', roughly translating to \"just\", is functionally the same as standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3070\u304b\u308a}} ''bakari'' (colloquially {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3063\u304b\u308a}} ''bakkari'').<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044 | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%b0%e3%81%a3%e3%81%8b%e3%81%84/ | language=ja | access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\">{{cite web | title=\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\u3000\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u8f9e\u5178 | website=\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b | url=http://onjyodoi.sakura.ne.jp/jiten/jiten.html | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3081\u306b\u3063\u3042\u3081'''\u3070\u3063\u304b\u3044'''\u964d\u3063\u3068\u3063\u3069}} (''meni\u0294 ame '''bakkai''' futtoddo'')<ref>{{cite web | title=49 \u96e8[\u3070\u304b\u308a]\uff08\u964d\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-49.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|me-ni\u0294 ame{{=}}bakkai fu-tte{{=}}o\u0294{{=}}do.\n|every-day rain{{=}}just fall-CONJ{{=}}PROG{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's just raining every day\"}}\n\n=== doma ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u307e}} ''doma''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> typically follows nouns and marks approximation. It can be translated as \"roughly\", \"approximately\" , \"just about\", \"around\" or \"or so\" in English. The closest standard Japanese equivalents would be {{lang|ja|\u3070\u304b\u308a\u306f}} ''bakari wa'', {{lang|ja|\u3050\u3089\u3044\u306f}} ''gurai wa'' and {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3069\u306f}} ''nado wa''.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /><ref name=\"KenteiDoma\">{{cite web | title=\u3069\u307e | website=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u5f01\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u8f9e\u5178 | url=https://kagoshimaben-kentei.com/jaddo/%e3%81%a9%e3%81%be-2/ | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nEtymologically, {{lang|ja|\u3069\u307e}} ''doma'' stems from the word {{lang|ja|\u5171}} ''tomo'', meaning \"together with\" in standard Japanese, and the topic particle \u306f ''(w)a''.<ref name=\"KenteiDoma\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e94\u4eba'''\u3069\u307e'''}} (''go nin '''doma''''')<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />\n|go nin doma\n|five people roughly\n|'Roughly five people'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305d\u3052\u3093\u304b\u3063\u305f\u304f\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3093'''\u3069\u307e'''\u3044\u3089\u3093\u3002}} (''sogen kattakutta kan '''doma''' iran.'')\n|so{{=}}gen kattakutta kan doma iran.\n|this{{=}}like scribble.PST paper roughly want.NEG\n|'I do not want scribbled paper like this'}}\n\n=== nando ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3093\u3069}} ''nando''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and its variant {{lang|ja|\u306a\u3069}} ''nado'' roughly translates to \"for example\" or \"such as\" in English.\n\n=== shiko ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3053}} ''shiko'' roughly translates to \"only\" or \"to such extent\" in English. It is used in place of standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3060\u3051}} ''dake''<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> or {{lang|ja|\u307b\u3069}} ''hodo''<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" />. Etymologically, {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3053}} ''shiko'' may be related to standard Japanese {{lang|ja|\u3057\u304d}} ''shiki'', found in compounds like {{lang|ja|\u3053\u308c\u3057\u304d}} ''koreshiki'' \"only this much\", as well as {{lang|ja|\u3057\u304b}} ''shika'' \"only\", which is limited in standard Japanese to negative phrases.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069'''\u3057\u3053'''\u3067\u3093}} (''do'''shiko''' den'')\n|do{{=}}shiko de{{=}}n\n|what{{=}}extent is{{=}}however\n|'As many as one likes'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3042\u3063\u305f'''\u3057\u3053'''\u6301\u3063\u3051}} (''atta '''shiko''' mokke'')\n|atta{{=}}shiko mo\u0294{{=}}ke\n|have.PST{{=}}extent bring{{=}}come.IMP\n|'Bring all that you have'}}\n\n=== Terminative (or limitative) particles ===\n\n==== gii ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304e\u3044}} ''gii'' or its variant {{lang|ja|\u304e}} ''gi'' is used to indicate a time or place as a limit<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and can be translated as \"until\" or \"up to\" in English. It is functionally similar to the particle {{lang|ja|\u307e\u3067}} ''made'' in Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> Etymologically, the particle originated from the noun {{lang|ja|\u5207\u308a}} ''kiri'' meaning \"end\" or \"bound\", which also gave way to the standard Japanese particle {{lang|ja|\u304d\u308a}} ''kiri'' (sometimes {{lang|ja|\u304e\u308a}} ''giri''), meaning \"just\" or \"only\".<ref>{{cite web | title=\u5207\u308a | website=Jisho.org | url=https://jisho.org/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keyword=%E5%88%87%E3%82%8A | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e94\u6642'''\u304e'''}} (''go ji '''gi''''')\n|go ji{{=}}gi\n|five hour{{=}}TERM\n|\"Until 5 o'clock\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u30cf\u30a4\u3001\u3053\u3044'''\u304e\u3044'''\u3088\u3002}} (''hai, koi '''gii''' yo.'')\n|hai koi{{=}}gii{{=}}yo\n|yes this{{=}}TERM{{=}}EMP\n|'Yes, so far'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3044\u3063\u3068\u3063\u3001\u304b\u3054\u3063\u307e'''\u304e\u3043'''\u3044\u305f\u3063\u304f\u3063\u3067\u3002}} (''itto\u0294, kagomma '''gii''' itakudde'')<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3053\u3053\u304c\u5909\u3060\u3088\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u4eba\u306e\u65b9\u8a00 | website=NAVER \u307e\u3068\u3081 | url=https://matome.naver.jp/odai/2134812638271947601 | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|itto\u0294, kagomma{{=}}gii itaku\u0294{{=}}de\n| hold_on kagoshima{{=}}TERM go_and_return{{=}}CNSQ\n|\"It's because I'm going to Kagoshima and back\"}}\n\n==== zui ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' (also spelled {{lang|ja|\u3065\u3044}} ''dzui'' and sometimes reduced to the form {{lang|ja|\u3058}} ''ji'') is used to indicate a time or place as a limit<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /><ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> and can be translated as \"to\", \"until\" or \"up to\" in English. It is functionally similar to the particle {{lang|ja|\u307e\u3067}} ''made'' in Japanese.<ref name=\"\u304a\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3069\u3044\u306e\u5c0f\u5c4b\" /> In the [[Higashimorokata District, Miyazaki|Higashimorokata district]] of [[Miyazaki Prefecture|Miyazaki]], the form {{lang|ja|\u305a\u308a}} ''zuri'' is used.<ref name=\"Higashimorokata\">{{cite web | title=\u5bae\u5d0e\u770c\u6771\u8af8\u306e\u65b9\u8a00\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/97061395.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nEtymologically, the particle {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' originates from the noun {{lang|ja|\u51fa\u308a}} \"setting out (to)\", which was historically pronounced ''dzuri'' in Kagoshima and is equivalent to the form {{lang|ja|\u51fa}} ''de'' \"coming out\" in modern standard Japanese. This is evidenced by the fact that the verb {{lang|ja|\u51fa\u308b}} \"to go out; to exit; to set out\" and its nominal form are still pronounced \u305a\u3044 ''zui'' or ''dzui'' in the traditional Kagoshima dialects.<ref>{{cite web | title=\u9e7f\u5150\u5cf6\u770c\u7511\u5cf6\u91cc\u65b9\u8a00 | url=http://hougen.sakura.ne.jp/shuppan/2017/3-16.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u6642'''\u305a\u3044'''}} (''i'''zzui''''')<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" />\n|i\u0294{{=}}zui\n|when{{=}}TERM\n|'Until when?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u51e6'''\u305a\u3044'''}} (''doko '''zui''''')\n|doko{{=}}zui\n|where{{=}}TERM\n|'Up to where?', 'How far?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5e02\u6765\u304b\u3089\u5e02\u6bd4\u91ce'''\u3065\u3044'''}} (''Ichiki kara Ichihino '''dzui''''')<ref>{{cite web | title=\u3044\u3061\u304d\u4e32\u6728\u91ce\u5e02 - \u6c11\u8a71\u7de8 | url=https://sitereports.nabunken.go.jp/files/attach/30/30471/22057_2_%E3%81%84%E3%81%A1%E3%81%8D%E4%B8%B2%E6%9C%A8%E9%87%8E%E5%B8%82%E9%83%B7%E5%9C%9F%E5%8F%B2%E6%96%99%E9%9B%861%E6%B0%91%E8%A9%B1%E3%83%BB%E7%A5%AD%E3%82%8A%E7%B7%A8.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03 | page=29}}</ref>\n|ichiki{{=}}kara ichihino{{=}}dzui\n|ichiki{{=}}ABL ichihino{{=}}TERM\n|'From Ichiki to Ichihino'}}\n\nIn Koshikijima, {{lang|ja|\u305a\u3044}} ''zui'' can also be used in the sense of \"even\" or \"so far as\":\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u9bdb'''\u305a\u3044'''\u3053\u304a\u3060}} (''tai '''zui''' kooda'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" />\n|tai{{=}}zui koo-da\n|sea_bream{{=}}TERM eat-PST\n|'(I) even ate sea bream', '(I) went so far as eating sea bream'}}\n\n== Sentence-final particles ==\n\n=== Question particles ===\n\n==== ka ====\nLike standard Japanese, the sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' (pronounced {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' in Makurazaki city) is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. Compared to the question particles {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke'' and {{lang|ja|\u306a}} ''na'', the particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'' is neutral and can be used with anyone regardless of age.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4f55\u6708'''\u304b'''\uff1f}} (''nan gak'''ka'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n|nan ga\u0294{{=}}ka\n|what month{{=}}Q\n|'What month?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3084\u3063\u305f\u308d\u304c\uff1f}} (''do yattaro '''ga'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n|do ya-tta-ro{{=}}ga\n|how COP-PST-INFER{{=}}Q\n|'How was it?'}}\n\n==== ke (1) ====\nThe sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke'' or sometimes {{lang|ja|\u3051\u3048}} ''kee'' (pronounced {{lang|ja|\u3052}} ''ge'' and {{lang|ja|\u3052\u3048}} ''gee'' in Makurazaki city) is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. While this particle is functionally equivalent to the question particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'', it is more specifically used when talking to someone who is younger.<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\">{{cite web | first1=Nobuko | last1=Kibe | first2=Tomoyo | last2=Otsuki | first3=Kumiko | last3=Sato | title=Intonational Variations at the End of Interrogative Sentences in Japanese Dialects: From the \u201cCorpus of Japanese Dialects\u201d | publisher=National Institute for Japanese Language and Linguistics (NINJAL) | url=https://pj.ninjal.ac.jp/corpus_center/en/lrec2018sss_kibe.pdf | access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3044'''\u3051'''\uff1f\u4e00\u756a\u3053\u307e\u3093\u304b\u305f\u3002}} (''doi '''ke'''? ibban komanka ta.'')\n|doi{{=}}ke? i\u0294-ban koman-ka{{=}}to{{=}}a.\n|which{{=}}Q? one-number small-ADJ{{=}}NMZ{{=}}TOP.\n|'Which one? The smallest one.'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u660e\u65e5\u4f11\u307f'''\u3051\u3048'''\uff1f}} (''ashita yasumi '''kee'''?'')<ref name=\"\u5742\u7530\u52dd\">{{cite book | title=\u304b\u3054\u3057\u307e\u5f01\u5165\u9580\u8b1b\u5ea7: \u57fa\u790e\u304b\u3089\u5fdc\u7528\u307e\u3067 | first=\u52dd| last=\u5742\u7530 | page=117 | year=2007 | publisher=\u56f3\u66f8\u51fa\u7248\u3000\u5357\u65b9\u65b0\u793e | isbn=4861241073}}</ref>\n|ashita yasumi{{=}}kee?\n|tomorrow holiday{{=}}Q?\n|'Is tomorrow a holiday?'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u623b\u3063\u6765\u305f'''\u3052'''\uff1f}} (''modokkita '''ge'''?'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" /> (Example from around Makurazaki city)\n|modo-\u0294{{=}}ki-ta{{=}}ge?\n|return-SEQ{{=}}come-PST{{=}}Q\n|'Have (they) come back?'}}\n\n==== na ====\nThe sentence-final particle {{lang|ja|\u306a}} ''na'' is used to mark a question at the end of a phrase. While this particle is functionally equivalent to the question particle {{lang|ja|\u304b}} ''ka'', it is more specifically used when talking to someone who is older.<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u623b\u3063\u3066\u6765\u305f\u3082\u3093\u3062\u3083\u306a\u304c\u3069\u306a\uff1f}} (''Modotte kita mon janaga do na'')<ref name=\"NobukoKibe\" /> (Example from around Makurazaki city)\n|modo-tte ki-ta{{=}}mon ja-naga{{=}}do{{=}}na\n|return-SEQ come-PST{{=}}NMLZ COP-NEG{{=}}EMP{{=}}Q\n|'Is it not the case that the person came back?'}}\n\n=== Emphatic particles ===\n\n==== (w)ai, (w)a and i ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3042\u3044}} ''ai'' or more rarely {{lang|ja|\u308f\u3044}} ''wai'' is a sentence-final particle used to emphasize the utterance and to indicate that the speaker is expressing their own view. This particle attaches to the preceding word (typically a verb in its non-past form) and often fuses with the vowel of the final syllable of that word. Functionally, this particle is similar in usage to the particle {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' in standard Japanese. In the Koshikijima islands, the variants {{lang|ja|\u3042}} ''a'' and {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'' are used.<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\" />\n\nEtymologically, the particle is said to originate from the historical pronoun {{lang|ja|\u6211}} ''ware'' \"I\" and to be cognate with the sentence-ending particles {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'', {{lang|ja|\u308f\u3044}} ''wai'' and {{lang|ja|\u3070\u3044}} ''bai'' used dialectally throughout Japan.<ref name=\"KenjiTomosada\">{{cite web | first=Kenji | last=Tomosada | title=The Japanese language and character particles, as seen in dialect: Character particles and sentence-ending particles | publisher=Prefectural University of Hiroshima | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/288873317_The_Japanese_language_and_character_particles_as_seen_in_dialect | access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u66f8\u4ed8\u3092\u5fd8\u308c\u305f\u3042'''\u3044'''}} (''kattsuke o wasuretaa'''i''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|kattsuke{{=}}o wasure-ta{{=}}ai\n|document{{=}}ACC forget-PST{{=}}EMP\n|\"(I) forgot the documents\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u5371\u306d\u8eca\u3084\u3089'''\u3044'''}} (''anne kuima yara'''i''''')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|anna{{=}}i kuima ya-ru{{=}}ai\n|dangerous{{=}}ADJ car COP-NPST{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's a dangerous car\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u305d\u3044\u3082\u826f\u304b\u3042\u3044\u306d}} (''soi mo yokaa'''i''' ne'')<ref name=\"NozomiKendaka\" />\n|soi{{=}}mo yo-ka{{=}}ai{{=}}ne\n|that{{=}}also good-ADJ{{=}}EMP{{=}}EMP\n|\"That is also good\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|abbreviations=CONJC:conjectural|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3069\u3089\u3001\u65e5\u304c\u6e1b\u3089\u3093\u3046\u3061\u623b\u3069\u3044\u3082\u305d}} (''dora, hi ga heran uchi modoimoso '''wai'''. '')<ref name=\"KenjiTomosada\" />\n|dora hi{{=}}ga her-an uchi{{=}}i modo-i-mos-o{{=}}wai\n|whatever sun{{=}}NOM decrease-CONJC home{{=}}DAT return-INF-POL-VOL{{=}}EMP\n|\"Whatever the case, let's return before the sun goes down\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u8e74\u3063\u3068\u3089\u3042}} (''kettor'''aa''''')<ref name=\"KurokiKunihiko\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|ke-tte{{=}}o-ru{{=}}a\n|kick-SEQ{{=}}PROG-NPST{{=}}EMP\n|\"(I am) kicking\"}}\n\nAfter a verb in its [[Kagoshima verb conjugations#Volitional (Presumptive)|volitional form]] (also called the presumptive form), the particle is reduced to {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' and serves to add insistence to what is being said. Examples from [[Izumi, Kagoshima]] include {{lang|ja|\u98f2\u3082\u3044}} ''nomoi'' \"let's drink\", {{lang|ja|\u884c\u3053\u3044}} ''ikoi'' \"let's go\", {{lang|ja|\u898b\u308d\u3044}} ''miroi'' \"let's see\" and {{lang|ja|\u3057\u3085\u3044}} ''shui'' \"let's do (it)\".<ref name=\"NozomiKodamaIzumi\">{{cite web | first=Nozomi | last=Kodama | title=\u51fa\u6c34\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u30e2\u30fc\u30e9\u58f0\u8abf\u5358\u4f4d\u3068\u30a4\u30f3\u30c8\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 | trans-title=Moraic TBU's and Intonation in Izumi (Kagoshima) Dialect | url=http://l118.let.kumamoto-u.ac.jp/ariake/09-01.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==== do ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3069}} ''do'', sometimes lengthened to {{lang|ja|\u3069\u304a\u30fb\u3069\u30fc}} ''doo'', can follow a verb or an adjective and is used to indicate assertion or add emphasis to what is said. It is functionally similar to the particles {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' and {{lang|ja|\u305e}} ''zo'' in standard Japanese<ref name=\"Kenjinkai\" /> as well as the particle {{lang|ja|\u3069\u30fc}} ''doo'' used in most Ryukyuan languages such as Okinawan.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3088\u304b'''\u3069'''}} (''yoka '''do''''')\n|yo-ka{{=}}do\n|good-ADJ{{=}}EMP\n|\"It's good!\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304b\u3048\u308d'''\u3069'''}} (''kaero '''do''''')\n|kae-ro{{=}}do\n|return-VOL{{=}}EMP\n|\"I'm going home!\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4eca\u65e5\u306f\u3088\u304b\u5929\u6c17\u3058\u3083\u3063'''\u3069'''}} (''kyu wa yoka tenki jad'''do''''')\n|kyu{{=}}wa yo-ka tenki ja\u0294{{=}}do\n|today{{=}}TOP good-ADJ weather is{{=}}EMP\n|'The weather is quite fine today!'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3093\u3093\u307e\u304b\u3063\u305f'''\u3069\u30fc'''}} (''nnmakatta '''doo''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Intonation\">{{cite web | website=geocities.jp | date=2018-11-05 | title=\u6587\u7bc0\u3068\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u3001\u304a\u3088\u3073\u30a4\u30f3\u30c8\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 | url=http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7intonation.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105121314/http://www.geocities.jp/rtymg285/7intonation.html | archive-date=2018-11-05 | url-status=dead | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|nnma-ka-tta{{=}}doo\n|delicious-ADJ-PST{{=}}EMP\n|\"It was delicious!\"}}\n\n==== gaa ====\n\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304c\u3042}} ''gaa'' or sometimes just {{lang|ja|\u304c}} ''ga'' has two primary functions.\n\nThe first is that it can be used to mark an interjection or a [[tag question]], similar to \"eh?\", \"right?\" or \"isn't it?\" in English or {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3084\u3063\u305b\u3093'''\u304c\u3042'''}} (''yassen '''gaa''''')\n|yassen{{=}}gaa\n|hopeless{{=}}Q\n|\"It's hopeless, eh?\"}}\n\nThe second is that it can be used to indicate a suggestion or mark insistence when following a verb in its plain form. In this sense, it can be translated to \"let's (...)\", \"(we) should (...)\" or \"shall we (...)?\" in English.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u4e00\u7dd2\u306b\u884c\u304f'''\u304c'''}} (''issho ni iku '''ga''''')<ref name=\"\u5742\u7530\u52dd\" />\n|issho{{=}}ni i-ku{{=}}ga\n|together{{=}}DAT go-NPST{{=}}Q\n|\"Let's go together\", \"Shall we go together?\"}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u304f'''\u304c'''}} (''ku '''ga''''')\n|ku{{=}}ga\n|eat.NPST{{=}}Q\n|\"Let's eat\", \"(We) should eat\"}}\n\n==== nee ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u306d\u3048}} ''nee'' or sometimes just {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' is used to mark an interjection or a tag question, similar to \"eh?\", \"right?\" or \"isn't it?\" in English or {{lang|ja|\u306d}} ''ne'' in standard Japanese. \n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3093\u3093\u307e\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3069'''\u306d\u3048'''}} (''nnmakatta doo '''nee''''')<ref name=\"rtymg285Intonation\" />\n|nnma-ka-tta{{=}}do{{=}}nee\n|delicious-ADJ-PST{{=}}EMP{{=}}Q\n|\"It was delicious, don't you agree?\"}}\n\n==== o (2) ====\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u304a\u30fb\u3092}} ''o'' or {{lang|ja|\u304a\u30fc\u30fb\u3092\u30fc}} ''oo'' is a sentence-final particle used to stress the utterance. It is similar in usage to the particles {{lang|ja|\u3088}} ''yo'' and {{lang|ja|\u308f}} ''wa'' in standard Japanese.\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u65e9\u3088\u884c\u3063\u304d\u3083\u3044'''\u304a\u30fc'''}} (''hayo ikkyai '''oo''''')<ref name=\"Showa\">{{cite web | title=\u662d\u548c\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e\u65b9\u8a00\u306e\u7dcf\u4f1a\u7684\u7814\u7a76 \u65b9\u8a00\u6587\u672b\u8a5e(\u6587\u672b\u52a9\u8a5e)\u306e\u7814\u7a76 | url=http://hougen.sakura.ne.jp/shuppan/2017/3-16.pdf | trans-title=General Assembly Study of Showa Japanese: Study on dialect final particles | language=ja | access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> (Example from the Eastern Satsuma Peninsula)\n|haya{{=}}u i-ki{{=}}ya-i oo\n|fast{{=}}ADV go-INF{{=}}do.aux.POL-IMP EMP\n|'Please go quickly'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u826f\u304b\u5929\u6c17\u3062\u3083\u306a'''\u304a'''}} (''yoka tenki ja na '''o''''')<ref name=\"Showa\" /> (Example from Yakushima)\n|yo-ka tenki ja na o\n|good-ADJ weather COP EMP EMP\n|'The weather is quite nice'}}\n\nIn Tanegashima, this particle fuses with the preceding word. For example, the phrase {{lang|ja|\u826f\u304b\u304a}} ''yoka o'' \"it's good\" would become {{lang|ja|\u826f\u3053\u30fc}} ''yokoo''.<ref name=\"Showa\" />\n\n== Unclassified ==\n\n=== ke (2) ===\nThe particle {{lang|ja|\u3051}} ''ke''<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\">{{cite web | title=\u898b\u306b(\u884c\u3063\u305f) | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-21.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> can be used with verbs in their stem form to indicate purpose or intent. It normally occurs in the construction {{lang|ja|\uff5e\u3051\u884c\u3063}} ''~ ke i\u0294'' \"to go (do something)\". In parts of the Koshikijima islands, the variant {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3083\u3042}} ''kyaa'' is used, while in Tanegashima, the variant {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3042}} ''kaa'' is observed.<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\" />\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u898b'''\u3051'''\u884c\u3063\u305f}} (''mi '''ke''' itta.'')<ref name=\"NinjalMINI\" />\n|mi{{=}}ke i-tta\n|see{{=}}PURP go-PST\n|'(I) went to look'}}\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u9b5a\u91e3\u308a\u304d\u3083\u3042\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3044}} (''io tsuri '''kyaa''' ikoo i.'')<ref name=\"SatoGrammar\" /> (Example from Koshikijima)\n|io tsur-i{{=}}kyaa ik-oo{{=}}i\n|fish angle-INF{{=}}PURP go-HORT{{=}}EMP\n|\"Let's go fishing!\"}}\n\nNote that this particle can only be used with verbs. With nouns, the particle {{lang|ja|\u3044}} ''i'' is used instead.<ref name=\"NinjalSHIGOTO\">{{cite web | title=\u4ed5\u4e8b[\u306b]\uff08\u884c\u3063\u305f\uff09 | url=https://www2.ninjal.ac.jp/hogen/dp/gaj-pdf/gaj-map-legend/vol1/GAJ1-22.pdf | language=ja | access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> For example:\n\n:{{interlinear|lang=ja\n|top={{lang|ja|\u3057\u3054'''\u3066'''\u884c\u3063\u305f}} (''shigot'''e''' itta'')<ref name=\"NinjalSHIGOTO\" />\n|shigoto{{=}}i i-tta\n|work{{=}}DAT go-PST\n|'(I) went to work'}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kagoshima dialect]]\n* [[Japanese particles]]\n* [[Japanese grammar#Particles|Japanese grammar: particles]]\n* [[Kansai dialect#Particles|Kansai dialect: particles]]\n* [[Okinawan language#Particles|Okinawan language: particles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japanese language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kagoshima dialect}}\n[[Category:Japanese dialects]]\n[[Category:Kagoshima Prefecture]]\n", "name_user": "Io Katai", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improving structure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particles_of_the_Kagoshima_dialects"}
{"title_page": "Imploding the Mirage", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Imploding the Mirage\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Killers]]\n| cover      = The Killers - Imploding the Mirage.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2020|05|29|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio     = {{flatlist|\n* Los Angeles\n* Las Vegas\n* [[Park City, Utah]]}}\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Shawn Everett]]\n* [[Jonathan Rado]]\n| prev_title = [[Wonderful Wonderful (The Killers album)|Wonderful Wonderful]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| name        = Imploding the Mirage\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = [[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\n| single1date = March 13, 2020\n| single2     = My Own Souls Warning\n| single2date = TBC\n}}\n}}\n'''''Imploding the Mirage''''' is the upcoming sixth studio album by American rock band [[the Killers]]. It is scheduled to be released through [[Island Records]] on May 29, 2020.<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-killers-imploding-the-mirage-tour/|title=The Killers Announce New Album Imploding the Mirage, Massive World Tour|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> It was preceded by the lead single \"[[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\", released on March 13, 2020.<ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/the-killers-new-song-caution-imploding-the-mirage-artwork/|title=The Killers Unveil 'Caution' Song, 'Imploding the Mirage' Artwork|website=[[Loudwire]]|last=Childers|first=Chad|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The band will embark on a world tour in support of the album, although they have since delayed ticket sales due to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2020/03/the-killers-postpone-putting-tickets-on-sale-for-upcoming-tour/|title=The Killers Postpone Putting Tickets On-Sale For Upcoming Tour|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|author=''Spin'' staff|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe band formally announced the album on social media on November 15, 2019. Frontman [[Brandon Flowers]] told ''[[NME]]'' that the band went to [[Utah]] to record part of the album as it was where Flowers \"fell in love with music for the first time\", also saying that it was \"interesting to be there again and hear some of that music with the geography matching the sensation. Some of that stuff is starting to resurface and a lot of that had to do with [[synthesizer]] music. It's always been part of our DNA but it's definitely creeping up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-killers-new-album-imploding-the-mirage-913133/|title=The Killers Announce New Album 'Imploding the Mirage'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=November 18, 2019|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album artwork is \"Dance of the Wind and Storm\" by [[Thomas Blackshear]].\n\n==Recording==\n''Imploding the Mirage'' was recorded in various locations, including in [[Los Angeles]], [[Las Vegas]] and [[Park City, Utah]], and produced by Canadian producer [[Shawn Everett]], and [[Jonathan Rado]] of the band [[Foxygen]]. It features contributions from [[Lindsey Buckingham]] (\"Caution\"),<ref name=\"CoS\"/> [[k.d. lang]], [[Weyes Blood]] (\"My God\"), [[Adam Granduciel]] from [[The War on Drugs (band)|The War on Drugs]], [[Blake Mills]] and [[Lucius (band)|Lucius]].<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nThe album will feature 10 tracks. All aside from \"Caution\" have yet to be revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/imploding-the-mirage/1502453888|title=Imploding the Mirage by The Killers|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| title4 = [[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\n| length4 = 4:29\n}}\n\n===Confirmed Tracks===\nThese tracks were confirmed during interviews with Radio.com and The Times.\n* \"Dying Breed\"\n* \"Fire in Bone\"\n* \"Lightning Fields\"\n* \"My God\"\n* \"My Own Soul's Warning\"\n\n===Probable other tracks===\nThese tracks were revealed on an \"A List\" of songs likely to be included on the album in December 2019:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/the-killers-tease-update-imploding-the-mirage-tracklist-2591640|title=The Killers tease update on 'Imploding The Mirage' tracklist|work=[[NME]]|last=Neale|first=Matthew|date=December 29, 2019|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Blowback\"\n* \"Imploding the Mirage\"\n* \"Running Towards a Place\"\n* \"When the Dreams Run Dry\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Killers}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Shawn Everett]]\n[[Category:The Killers albums]]\n[[Category:Island Records albums]]\n[[Category:Upcoming albums]]\n\n{{2020s-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Imploding the Mirage\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Killers]]\n| cover      = The Killers - Imploding the Mirage.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2020|05|29|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio     = {{flatlist|\n* Los Angeles\n* Las Vegas\n* [[Park City, Utah]]}}\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Shawn Everett]]\n* [[Jonathan Rado]]\n| prev_title = [[Wonderful Wonderful (The Killers album)|Wonderful Wonderful]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| name        = Imploding the Mirage\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = [[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\n| single1date = March 13, 2020\n| single2     = My Own Souls Warning\n| single2date = TBC\n}}\n}}\n'''''Imploding the Mirage''''' is the upcoming sixth studio album by American rock band [[the Killers]]. It is scheduled to be released through [[Island Records]] on May 29, 2020.<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-killers-imploding-the-mirage-tour/|title=The Killers Announce New Album Imploding the Mirage, Massive World Tour|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> It was preceded by the lead single \"[[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\", released on March 13, 2020.<ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/the-killers-new-song-caution-imploding-the-mirage-artwork/|title=The Killers Unveil 'Caution' Song, 'Imploding the Mirage' Artwork|website=[[Loudwire]]|last=Childers|first=Chad|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The band will embark on a world tour in support of the album, although they have since delayed ticket sales due to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2020/03/the-killers-postpone-putting-tickets-on-sale-for-upcoming-tour/|title=The Killers Postpone Putting Tickets On-Sale For Upcoming Tour|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|author=''Spin'' staff|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe band formally announced the album on social media on November 15, 2019. Frontman [[Brandon Flowers]] told ''[[NME]]'' that the band went to [[Utah]] to record part of the album as it was where Flowers \"fell in love with music for the first time\", also saying that it was \"interesting to be there again and hear some of that music with the geography matching the sensation. Some of that stuff is starting to resurface and a lot of that had to do with [[synthesizer]] music. It's always been part of our DNA but it's definitely creeping up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-killers-new-album-imploding-the-mirage-913133/|title=The Killers Announce New Album 'Imploding the Mirage'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=November 18, 2019|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album artwork is \"Dance of the Wind and Storm\" by Thomas Blackshear.\n\n==Recording==\n''Imploding the Mirage'' was recorded in various locations, including in [[Los Angeles]], [[Las Vegas]] and [[Park City, Utah]], and produced by Canadian producer [[Shawn Everett]], and [[Jonathan Rado]] of the band [[Foxygen]]. It features contributions from [[Lindsey Buckingham]] (\"Caution\"),<ref name=\"CoS\"/> [[k.d. lang]], [[Weyes Blood]] (\"My God\"), [[Adam Granduciel]] from [[The War on Drugs (band)|The War on Drugs]], [[Blake Mills]] and [[Lucius (band)|Lucius]].<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nThe album will feature 10 tracks. All aside from \"Caution\" have yet to be revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/imploding-the-mirage/1502453888|title=Imploding the Mirage by The Killers|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| title4 = [[Caution (The Killers song)|Caution]]\n| length4 = 4:29\n}}\n\n===Confirmed Tracks===\nThese tracks were confirmed during interviews with Radio.com and The Times.\n* \"Dying Breed\"\n* \"Fire in Bone\"\n* \"Lightning Fields\"\n* \"My God\"\n* \"My Own Soul's Warning\"\n\n===Probable other tracks===\nThese tracks were revealed on an \"A List\" of songs likely to be included on the album in December 2019:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/the-killers-tease-update-imploding-the-mirage-tracklist-2591640|title=The Killers tease update on 'Imploding The Mirage' tracklist|work=[[NME]]|last=Neale|first=Matthew|date=December 29, 2019|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n* \"Blowback\"\n* \"Imploding the Mirage\"\n* \"Running Towards a Place\"\n* \"When the Dreams Run Dry\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Killers}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Shawn Everett]]\n[[Category:The Killers albums]]\n[[Category:Island Records albums]]\n[[Category:Upcoming albums]]\n\n{{2020s-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jmeservy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imploding_the_Mirage"}
{"title_page": "Herilanto Raveloharison", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name    = Herilanto Raveloharison\n|image   = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|04|09}}\n|birth_place = [[Antsiranana]], [[Madagascar]]\n|nationality = Malagasy\n|occupation = Magistrate, military officer\n|module={{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|rank = Lieutenant General}}\n|title = Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning\n|term= April 2014 - June 2018\n}}\n\nLieutenant General '''Herilanto Raveloharison''' (born April 9, 1958) is a [[Madagascar|Malagasy]] magistrate, politician and military officer. He served as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning from April 2014, under Prime Minister [[Roger Kolo]] to June 2018 when he was succeeded by Professor Marcel Napetoke under [[Christian Ntsay]] government<ref>https://lexpress.mg/12/06/2018/photos-les-ministres-du-gouvernement-christian-ntsay/</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nHe was born in [[Antsiranana]], [[Madagascar]]. He is a graduate in Administration and Public Management from [[University of Paris 1 Pantheon-Sorbonne]] and [[\u00c9cole nationale de la France d'outre-mer|Institut international d'administration publique]] of Paris,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ledaily.mg/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/CV-Ministre-de-lEconomie-et-de-la-Planification-Gl-Herilanto-Raveloharison.pdf|format=PDF|title=CURRICULUM VITAE|publisher=Ledaily.mg|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nHerilanto Raveloharison has held important positions in [[Madagascar]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ecrit par Solofonjatovo Ranaivo. |url=http://ledaily.mg/le-gouvernement-publie-les-cv-de-27-ministres/ |title=Le gouvernement publie les CV de 27 ministres |publisher=Ledaily.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> He was the Minister for Environment and Forests under the [[Albert Camille Vital]] government<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Les-membres-du-gouvernement-Albert,15685.html |title=Les membres du gouvernement Albert Camille Vital |publisher=Madagascar-Tribune.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> during the transition period led by [[Andry Nirina Rajoelina]].\n\nIn 2012, he was appointed as the president of Comit\u00e9 pour la Sauvegarde de l'Integrit\u00e9 (Integrity Safeguarding Committee).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csi.gov.mg/historique/organisation/ |title=Organisation &#124; Comit\u00e9 pour la Sauvegarde de l'Int\u00e9grit\u00e9 - Madagascar |publisher=Csi.gov.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> After [[Hery Rajaonarimampianina]]'s election as the President of Republic, Major General Raveloharison was one among the 31 ministers of [[Roger Kolo]]'s government for the fourth Republic.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.midi-madagasikara.mg/a-la-une/2014/04/19/gouvernement-kolo-roger-31-ministres-dont-6-femmes-27-nouveaux-4-reconduits/ |title=Gouvernement Kolo Roger : 31 ministres dont 6 femmes, 27 nouveaux et 4 reconduits - Midi Madagasikara |publisher=Midi-madagasikara.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Raveloharison served as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning between 2014 and 2018. In September 2014, constant power-cuts afflicted the country. Fihenena Richard, Minister for Energy at that time, was dismissed. General Raveloharison was appointed to serve as an acting Minister for Energy.<ref>{{cite web|author=L\u00e9a Ratsiazo |url=http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Limogeage-du-directeur-general,20605.html |title=Limogeage du directeur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral Rasidy D\u00e9sir\u00e9 |publisher=Madagascar-Tribune.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> In December 2014, he was promoted to Lieutenant General for his effort in drafting the National Development Plan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B9-EuqDCVcacS0tpY1BwVThUYzQ/view|title=PND version definitive.pdf|work=Google Docs}}</ref> in less than six months as planned. On January 25, 2015, he was retained in office as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning in the government of Prime Minister [[Jean Ravelonarivo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150125203133/http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ |archivedate=2015-01-25 }}</ref> and retained in the government of [[Olivier Mahafaly Solonandrasana]]in April 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Les-membres-du-gouvernement-Albert,15685.html Madagascar-tribune.com]\n*[http://ledaily.mg/le-gouvernement-publie-les-cv-de-27-ministres/ Ledaily.mg]\n*[http://www.midi-madagasikara.mg/a-la-une/2014/04/19/gouvernement-kolo-roger-31-ministres-dont-6-femmes-27-nouveaux-4-reconduits/ Midi-madamasikara.mg]\n*[http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Limogeage-du-directeur-general,20605.html Madagascar-tribune.com]\n*[https://archive.is/20150125203133/http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ Newsmada.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raveloharison, Herilanto}}\n[[Category:Malagasy military personnel]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name    = Herilanto Raveloharison\n|image   = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|04|09}}\n|birth_place = [[Antsiranana]], [[Madagascar]]\n|nationality = Malagasy\n|occupation = Magistrate, military officer\n|module={{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|rank = Lieutenant General}}\n|title = Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning\n|term= April 2014 - June 2018\n}}\n\nLieutenant General '''Herilanto Raveloharison''' (born April 9, 1958) is a [[Madagascar|Malagasy]] magistrate, politician and military officer. He served as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning from April 2014, under Prime Minister [[Roger Kolo]] to June 2018 when he was succeeded by Professor Marcel Napetoke under [[Christian Ntsay]] government<ref>https://lexpress.mg/12/06/2018/photos-les-ministres-du-gouvernement-christian-ntsay/</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nHe was born in [[Antsiranana]], [[Madagascar]]. He is a graduate in Administration and Public Management from [[New Sorbonne University]] and [[\u00c9cole nationale de la France d'outre-mer]] of Paris,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ledaily.mg/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/CV-Ministre-de-lEconomie-et-de-la-Planification-Gl-Herilanto-Raveloharison.pdf|format=PDF|title=CURRICULUM VITAE|publisher=Ledaily.mg|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nHerilanto Raveloharison has held important positions in [[Madagascar]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ecrit par Solofonjatovo Ranaivo. |url=http://ledaily.mg/le-gouvernement-publie-les-cv-de-27-ministres/ |title=Le gouvernement publie les CV de 27 ministres |publisher=Ledaily.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> He was the Minister for Environment and Forests under the [[Albert Camille Vital]] government<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Les-membres-du-gouvernement-Albert,15685.html |title=Les membres du gouvernement Albert Camille Vital |publisher=Madagascar-Tribune.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> during the transition period led by [[Andry Nirina Rajoelina]].\n\nIn 2012, he was appointed as the president of Comit\u00e9 pour la Sauvegarde de l'Integrit\u00e9 (Integrity Safeguarding Committee).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csi.gov.mg/historique/organisation/ |title=Organisation &#124; Comit\u00e9 pour la Sauvegarde de l'Int\u00e9grit\u00e9 - Madagascar |publisher=Csi.gov.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> After [[Hery Rajaonarimampianina]]'s election as the President of Republic, Major General Raveloharison was one among the 31 ministers of [[Roger Kolo]]'s government for the fourth Republic.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.midi-madagasikara.mg/a-la-une/2014/04/19/gouvernement-kolo-roger-31-ministres-dont-6-femmes-27-nouveaux-4-reconduits/ |title=Gouvernement Kolo Roger : 31 ministres dont 6 femmes, 27 nouveaux et 4 reconduits - Midi Madagasikara |publisher=Midi-madagasikara.mg |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Raveloharison served as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning between 2014 and 2018. In September 2014, constant power-cuts afflicted the country. Fihenena Richard, Minister for Energy at that time, was dismissed. General Raveloharison was appointed to serve as an acting Minister for Energy.<ref>{{cite web|author=L\u00e9a Ratsiazo |url=http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Limogeage-du-directeur-general,20605.html |title=Limogeage du directeur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral Rasidy D\u00e9sir\u00e9 |publisher=Madagascar-Tribune.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-17}}</ref> In December 2014, he was promoted to Lieutenant General for his effort in drafting the National Development Plan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B9-EuqDCVcacS0tpY1BwVThUYzQ/view|title=PND version definitive.pdf|work=Google Docs}}</ref> in less than six months as planned. On January 25, 2015, he was retained in office as the Minister for Economy and Strategic Planning in the government of Prime Minister [[Jean Ravelonarivo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150125203133/http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ |archivedate=2015-01-25 }}</ref> and retained in the government of [[Olivier Mahafaly Solonandrasana]]in April 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Les-membres-du-gouvernement-Albert,15685.html Madagascar-tribune.com]\n*[http://ledaily.mg/le-gouvernement-publie-les-cv-de-27-ministres/ Ledaily.mg]\n*[http://www.midi-madagasikara.mg/a-la-une/2014/04/19/gouvernement-kolo-roger-31-ministres-dont-6-femmes-27-nouveaux-4-reconduits/ Midi-madamasikara.mg]\n*[http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Limogeage-du-directeur-general,20605.html Madagascar-tribune.com]\n*[https://archive.is/20150125203133/http://www.newsmada.com/2015/01/25/gouvernement-ravelonarivo-25-janvier-2015/ Newsmada.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raveloharison, Herilanto}}\n[[Category:Malagasy military personnel]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Alain Schneider", "label": "safe", "comment": "real universities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herilanto_Raveloharison"}
{"title_page": "Little House on the Prairie (novel)", "text_new": "{{Infobox book \n| name          = Little House on the Prairie\n| image         = Image:LHbookCover.jpg\n| caption       = Front dust jacket with Sewell's illustration <!-- series article displays front hardcover -->\n| author        = [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]]\n| illustrator   = [[Helen Sewell]]<ref name=LCC1/> <br>[[Garth Williams]] (1953)<ref name=LCC2/>\n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n\n| series        = [[Little House series|''Little House'']]\n| genre         = Children's novel <br>[[Family saga]]<br />[[Western (genre)|Western]]\n| publisher     = [[Harper & Brothers]]\n| pub_date      = September 19, 1935<ref name=kirkus/>\n| media_type    = Print ([[hardcover]])\n| pages         = 200;<ref name=LCC1/> 334 pp.<ref name=LCC2/>\n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 18319291 <!-- first edition -->\n| congress      = PZ7.W6461 Lit 1971<ref name=LCC1/>\n| preceded_by   = [[Farmer Boy]]\n| followed_by   = [[On the Banks of Plum Creek]]\n}}\n'''''Little House on the Prairie''''' is an autobiographical children's novel by [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]], published in 1935.<ref name=\"google\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=KO0tMOWl5AEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=little+house Little House on the Prairie] Google Books</ref> It was the third novel published in the [[Little House series|''Little House'' series]], continuing the story of the first, ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932), but not related to the second. Thus, it is sometimes called the second one in the series, or the second volume of \"the Laura Years\".<ref name=kirkus/>{{efn|name=almanzo}}\n\n== Plot summary ==\nThe novel is about the months the Ingalls spent on the [[Kansas]] [[prairie]] around the town of [[Independence, Kansas|Independence]]. Laura describes how her father built their one-room log house in Indian Territory, having heard that the government planned to open the territory to [[european colonization of the Americas|white settlers]] soon.\n\nIn contrast to ''Little House in the Big Woods'', the Ingalls face difficulty and danger in this book. They all fall ill from [[malaria]],<ref>[http://www.enotalone.com/article/10980.html History of Malaria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829004316/http://www.enotalone.com/article/10980.html |date=August 29, 2008 }}</ref> which was ascribed to breathing the night air or eating watermelon. [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]]s are a common sight for them, as their house was built in [[Osage Nation|Osage]] territory, and Ma's open [[prejudice]] about Indians contrasts with Laura's more childlike observations about those who live and ride nearby. They begin to congregate at the nearby river bottoms and their war cries unnerve the settlers, who worry they may be attacked, but an Osage chief who was friendly with Pa is able to avert the hostilities.\n\nBy the end of the novel, all the Ingalls' work is undone when word comes that U.S. soldiers are being sent to remove white settlers from Indian Territory. Pa decides to move his family away before they can be forced to leave.\n\n==Historical background==\nThe Ingalls moved from Wisconsin to Kansas in 1868 (stopping for a while in [[Rothville, Missouri]]), and lived there between 1869 and 1870. [[Carrie Ingalls|Carrie]] was born there in August, and a few weeks after her birth, they were forced to leave the territory (however, in the novel, she is present during the move to Kansas). They moved back to Wisconsin, where they lived the next four years. In 1874 they started for [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]], stopping for a while in [[Lake City, Minnesota|Lake City]].\n\nAlthough Wilder states that Charles had been told that the Kansas territory would soon be up for settlement, their homestead was on the Osage Indian reservation and Charles' information was incorrect. The Ingalls had no legal right to occupy their homestead, and once informed of their error, left the territory despite the fact that they had only just begun farming it. Several of their neighbors stayed and fought the decision.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kaye |first=Frances W. |title=Little Squatter on the Osage Diminished Reserve: Reading Laura Ingalls Wilder's Kansas Indians |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |year=2000 |pages=123\u2013140 |doi= |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1022&context=greatplainsquarterly }}</ref>\n\nAs they were preparing to leave, the Ingalls received word from Wisconsin that the man who purchased their farm near Pepin had defaulted on the mortgage. Since they had to leave Kansas, they decided to go back to Wisconsin and moved back to the farm they had left two years earlier. So instead of heading to Minnesota as the series relates, they headed to Wisconsin and lived there again for a few years before heading west to Minnesota.\n\n==Reception==\nVirginia Kirkus had handled Wilder's debut novel ''Little House in the Big Woods'' for Harper & Brothers as its book editor from 1926 to 1932. In ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'', her semimonthly bulletin from 1933, she awarded this novel a starred review (as she did the next three sequels). \"Good Americana \u2013 and a first rate tale. Personally, I liked it certainly as well, perhaps better than the other.\"<ref name=kirkus/>\n\nIn 2012, the novel was ranked number 27 among all-time children's novels in a survey published by ''[[School Library Journal]]'' \u2013 the second of three ''Little House'' books in the Top 100.<ref name=SLJChapter2012>{{cite web |url= http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2012/07/07/top-100-chapter-book-poll-results |title= Top 100 Chapter Book Poll Results |author= Bird, Elizabeth |publisher= A Fuse #8 Production. Blog. [[School Library Journal]] (blog.schoollibraryjournal.com) |date= July 7, 2012 |accessdate= 2015-10-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120713031015/http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2012/07/07/top-100-chapter-book-poll-results |archive-date= July 13, 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|25em |notes=\n{{efn|name=almanzo |1=\nOne 5-volume set, ''Little House: The Laura Years'' (January 1994) comprises volumes 1 and 3\u20136.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Little-House-Laura-Years-Boxed/dp/0064404765#reader_0064404765 \"Little House the Laura Years Boxed Set: The Early Years Collection\"]: Paperback \u2013 Box set, 1994. Amazon product page. Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref> Thus it features the Ingalls family until Laura is 14 years old, at the close of the \"Long Winter\" early in 1881.\n<br>&nbsp; The second novel, ''Farmer Boy'' (1933) features Laura's husband [[Almanzo Wilder]] as a boy. He appears in the sixth novel and their courtship begins in the seventh.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em |refs=\n\n<ref name=LCC1>\n[http://lccn.loc.gov/35027325 \"Little House on the Prairie\"] (first edition). Library of Congress Online Catalog (catalog.loc.gov). Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref>\n<ref name=LCC2>\n[http://lccn.loc.gov/52007526 \"Little House on the Prairie\"]; Newly illustrated, uniform ed. LC Online Catalog. Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref>\n\n<ref name=kirkus>\n[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/little-house-on-the-prairie \"Little House on the Prairie\"] (starred review). ''Kirkus Reviews''. September 1, 1935. Retrieved 2015-10-02. Online the review header shows a recent front cover, \"volume 2\" and \"illustrated by Garth Williams\".</ref>  \n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal |Children's literature |Kansas |Novels}}\n{{Bibliowiki|Little House on the Prairie|''Little House on the Prairie''}}\n* [http://www.littlehousebooks.com/ Little House Books] at HarperCollins Children's Books\n* [http://www.homeofourfathers.com/lisbeth/ingalls.htm The Journeys of Laura Ingalls] \u2013 web ring\n\n{{Little House}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little House on the Prairie}}\n[[Category:Little House books]]\n[[Category:1935 American novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1870s]]\n[[Category:Harper & Brothers books]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:1935 children's books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book \n| name          = Little House on the Prairie\n| image         = Image:LHbookCover.jpg\n| caption       = Front dust jacket with Sewell's illustration <!-- series article displays front hardcover -->\n| author        = [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]]\n| illustrator   = [[Helen Sewell]]<ref name=LCC1/> <br>[[Garth Williams]] (1953)<ref name=LCC2/>\n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n\n| series        = [[Little House series|''Little House'']]\n| genre         = Children's novel <br>[[Family saga]]<br />[[Western (genre)|Western]]\n| publisher     = [[Harper & Brothers]]\n| pub_date      = September 19, 1935<ref name=kirkus/>\n| media_type    = Print ([[hardcover]])\n| pages         = 200;<ref name=LCC1/> 334 pp.<ref name=LCC2/>\n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 18319291 <!-- first edition -->\n| congress      = PZ7.W6461 Lit 1971<ref name=LCC1/>\n| preceded_by   = [[Little House in the Big Woods]]\n| followed_by   = [[Farmer Boy]]\n}}\n\n'''''Little House on the Prairie''''' is an autobiographical children's novel by [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]], published in 1935.<ref name=\"google\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=KO0tMOWl5AEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=little+house Little House on the Prairie] Google Books</ref> It was the third novel published in the [[Little House series|''Little House'' series]], continuing the story of the first, ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932), but not related to the second. Thus, it is sometimes called the second one in the series, or the second volume of \"the Laura Years\".<ref name=kirkus/>{{efn|name=almanzo}}\n\n== Plot summary ==\nThe novel is about the months the Ingalls spent on the [[Kansas]] [[prairie]] around the town of [[Independence, Kansas|Independence]]. Laura describes how her father built their one-room log house in Indian Territory, having heard that the government planned to open the territory to [[european colonization of the Americas|white settlers]] soon.\n\nIn contrast to ''Little House in the Big Woods'', the Ingalls face difficulty and danger in this book. They all fall ill from [[malaria]],<ref>[http://www.enotalone.com/article/10980.html History of Malaria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829004316/http://www.enotalone.com/article/10980.html |date=August 29, 2008 }}</ref> which was ascribed to breathing the night air or eating watermelon. [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]]s are a common sight for them, as their house was built in [[Osage Nation|Osage]] territory, and Ma's open [[prejudice]] about Indians contrasts with Laura's more childlike observations about those who live and ride nearby. They begin to congregate at the nearby river bottoms and their war cries unnerve the settlers, who worry they may be attacked, but an Osage chief who was friendly with Pa is able to avert the hostilities.\n\nBy the end of the novel, all the Ingalls' work is undone when word comes that U.S. soldiers are being sent to remove white settlers from Indian Territory. Pa decides to move his family away before they can be forced to leave.\n\n==Historical background==\nThe Ingalls moved from Wisconsin to Kansas in 1868 (stopping for a while in [[Rothville, Missouri]]), and lived there between 1869 and 1870. [[Carrie Ingalls|Carrie]] was born there in August, and a few weeks after her birth, they were forced to leave the territory (however, in the novel, she is present during the move to Kansas). They moved back to Wisconsin, where they lived the next four years. In 1874 they started for [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]], stopping for a while in [[Lake City, Minnesota|Lake City]].\n\nAlthough Wilder states that Charles had been told that the Kansas territory would soon be up for settlement, their homestead was on the Osage Indian reservation and Charles' information was incorrect. The Ingalls had no legal right to occupy their homestead, and once informed of their error, left the territory despite the fact that they had only just begun farming it. Several of their neighbors stayed and fought the decision.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kaye |first=Frances W. |title=Little Squatter on the Osage Diminished Reserve: Reading Laura Ingalls Wilder's Kansas Indians |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |year=2000 |pages=123\u2013140 |doi= |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1022&context=greatplainsquarterly }}</ref>\n\nAs they were preparing to leave, the Ingalls received word from Wisconsin that the man who purchased their farm near Pepin had defaulted on the mortgage. Since they had to leave Kansas, they decided to go back to Wisconsin and moved back to the farm they had left two years earlier. So instead of heading to Minnesota as the series relates, they headed to Wisconsin and lived there again for a few years before heading west to Minnesota.\n\n==Reception==\nVirginia Kirkus had handled Wilder's debut novel ''Little House in the Big Woods'' for Harper & Brothers as its book editor from 1926 to 1932. In ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'', her semimonthly bulletin from 1933, she awarded this novel a starred review (as she did the next three sequels). \"Good Americana \u2013 and a first rate tale. Personally, I liked it certainly as well, perhaps better than the other.\"<ref name=kirkus/>\n\nIn 2012, the novel was ranked number 27 among all-time children's novels in a survey published by ''[[School Library Journal]]'' \u2013 the second of three ''Little House'' books in the Top 100.<ref name=SLJChapter2012>{{cite web |url= http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2012/07/07/top-100-chapter-book-poll-results |title= Top 100 Chapter Book Poll Results |author= Bird, Elizabeth |publisher= A Fuse #8 Production. Blog. [[School Library Journal]] (blog.schoollibraryjournal.com) |date= July 7, 2012 |accessdate= 2015-10-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120713031015/http://blog.schoollibraryjournal.com/afuse8production/2012/07/07/top-100-chapter-book-poll-results |archive-date= July 13, 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|25em |notes=\n{{efn|name=almanzo |1=\nOne 5-volume set, ''Little House: The Laura Years'' (January 1994) comprises volumes 1 and 3\u20136.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Little-House-Laura-Years-Boxed/dp/0064404765#reader_0064404765 \"Little House the Laura Years Boxed Set: The Early Years Collection\"]: Paperback \u2013 Box set, 1994. Amazon product page. Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref> Thus it features the Ingalls family until Laura is 14 years old, at the close of the \"Long Winter\" early in 1881.\n<br>&nbsp; The second novel, ''Farmer Boy'' (1933) features Laura's husband [[Almanzo Wilder]] as a boy. He appears in the sixth novel and their courtship begins in the seventh.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em |refs=\n\n<ref name=LCC1>\n[http://lccn.loc.gov/35027325 \"Little House on the Prairie\"] (first edition). Library of Congress Online Catalog (catalog.loc.gov). Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref>\n<ref name=LCC2>\n[http://lccn.loc.gov/52007526 \"Little House on the Prairie\"]; Newly illustrated, uniform ed. LC Online Catalog. Retrieved 2015-09-17.</ref>\n\n<ref name=kirkus>\n[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/little-house-on-the-prairie \"Little House on the Prairie\"] (starred review). ''Kirkus Reviews''. September 1, 1935. Retrieved 2015-10-02. Online the review header shows a recent front cover, \"volume 2\" and \"illustrated by Garth Williams\".</ref>  \n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal |Children's literature |Kansas |Novels}}\n{{Bibliowiki|Little House on the Prairie|''Little House on the Prairie''}}\n*